<FILEID>AP-NR-11-04-88 0048EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r w PM-ChallengesAhead Bjt   11-04 0644</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Challenges Ahead, Bjt,640</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>WASHINGTON TODAY: Next President Will Have To Focus On Mideast,
Soviets</HEAD>
<HEAD>An AP News Analysis</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BARRY SCHWEID</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Diplomatic Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The next U.S. president will have his hands
full trying to keep pace with Mikhail Gorbachev and finding a
formula for Mideast peace.
   The fast-moving Soviet leader is not only trying to restructure
the Soviet economy. He is permitting a diversity of views unknown in
his country since the 1917 Revolution.
   The next U.S. president must figure out how to encourage
democratic developments in a way that is consistent with American
security interests. If he goes too far, he risks leading the people
in Russia, the Baltics and Eastern Europe to expect U.S. help that
might not be there in the event of a crisis.
   The absence of a U.S. response _ apart from angry rhetoric _ to
the Soviet crackdown in Czechoslovakia in 1968 shows how limited
U.S. action might be despite cheering on democratic trends.
   But there are many steps to consider on the economic, arms
control and human rights fronts that could have an enormous impact
on living conditions.
   Will the United States provide easy credits to assist Communist
regimes in adopting Western techniques? Will arms control get the
kind of support that could take pressure off the Soviet _ and U.S. _
military? Will the United States condition its economic assistance
on tangible improvements in Soviet living standards?
   Four U.S.-Soviet summit meetings since 1985 have established a
basis for better superpower relations. As the Reagan administration
winds down, however, strains have developed over a Siberian radar
facility and new Soviet missiles and warplanes in Afghanistan.
   When the Soviets asked for a meeting in Geneva to discuss
Krasnoyarsk, U.S. officials hoped they might finally agree to
destroy the radar facility. President Reagan has complained the
radar violates the 1972 Anti-Ballistic Missile treaty.
   But the Soviets made no such offer, and the State Department
threatened to take ``proportionate'' steps or to declare Krasnoyarsk
a ``material breach'' of the treaty.
   U.S. officials disclosed the Pentagon had circulated
recommendations within the government that include deploying a
limited ballistic missile defense or reversing the planned
dismantling of three Poseidon nuclear submarines.
   The dispute over Krasnoyarsk and U.S. retaliation could weaken
U.S.-Soviet arms control efforts even as the two sides are within
range of an agreement to reduce their long-range nuclear weapons.
   A U.S. declaration that Krasnoyarsk breaches the 1972 treaty
could lead to the unraveling of the accord, a landmark in arms
control.
   In Afghanistan, meanwhile, the State Department every day this
week has denounced the Soviets for shipping in new weapons. Half the
Red Army withdrew by Aug. 15, as promised in last Spring's Geneva
accord. But the administration is concerned the Soviets are
imperiling a political settlement between rival factions and
intimidating Pakistan, besides.
   In the Middle East, the muddled situation in Israel after
Tuesday's national elections could require a shift in U.S.
diplomatic tactics.
   They have been based on trying to persuade Israel to surrender
territory in exchange for Arab recognition _ and to elicit the
promise from Jerusalem even before peace talks are held.
   Israeli Prime Minister Yitzhak Shamir refused, despite four trips
to the region this year by Secretary of State George P. Shultz. If
Shamir heads the new Israeli government, which may take two months
to restructure, there is no reason to expect him to change his mind.
   That means either letting the situation fester, which most U.S.
analysts consider dangerous, or trying another approach. One would
be concentrating U.S. pressure on the Palestinians and Jordan to
negotiate with Israel without preconditions. The other would be a
joint U.S.-Soviet formula for peace talks. But Shamir, ever
apprehensive of Moscow's intervention, is likely to resist.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>EDITOR'S NOTE </NOTE>
<TEXT>
   Barry Schweid covers U.S.-Soviet relations and
foreign affairs for The Associated Press.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
