<DOCNO> AP881104-0015 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-11-04-88 0102EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r w PM-FarmScene     11-04 0700</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Farm Scene,720</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Lyng Plans Meeting With EEC Officials On Trade Issues</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DON KENDALL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Farm Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Agriculture Secretary Richard E. Lyng says he
is headed for Europe later this month for ``one last series of
meetings'' with the European Economic Community on a range of
contentious agricultural trade issues.
   Lyng said that after Jan. 20, when the new administration takes
office, he hopes to hang up his government spurs and take it easy.
   But for now, Lyng said in an interview Thursday, he will keep
pushing on international trade and will be in Brussels around
mid-month with U.S. Trade Representative Clayton Yeutter and chief
U.S. agricultural trade negotiator Daniel Amstutz.
   No firm dates have been set for the EEC talks, however, Yeutter's
office said.
   International trade, particularly involving the EEC and Japan,
has been at the top of Lyng's list of priorities all long, he said.
And that includes trade liberalization negotiations under the
96-nation General Agreement on Tariffs and Trade.
   Lyng said the difficult parts of GATT negotiations ``relate to
the attitudes and problems with Japan, particularly on rice,'' and
the EEC _ primarily concerning its Common Agricultural Policy, high
support prices and export subsidies.
   One of the most immediate and pressing problems Lyng hopes to
address in his talks with EEC officials is the 12-nation bloc's
determination to ban imports of meat containing growth-promoting
hormones beginning Jan. 1, 1989.
   ``They're insisting they're going to implement that ban on Jan.
1,'' Lyng said. ``That would be a very serious problem for us.''
   U.S. livestock interests have estimated an EEC ban would cost
$130 million a year in lost trade, primarily in variety meats
popular on the European market. The EEC says the ban on meat
hormones is designed to ensure consumer safety.
   The Meat Industry Trade Policy Council, which includes a number
of farm, business and commodity organizations, has asked the Reagan
administration to use authority under the new trade law to cut off
meat imports from the EEC if the Jan. 1 ban goes into effect.
   Lyng said also that he, Yeutter and other U.S. trade officials
will attend the special meeting of the 96 member countries of GATT,
which will begin Dec. 5 in Montreal.
   After the next administration takes over, Lyng, 70, said he plans
to take it easy.
   ``We have no plans to move (from the Washington area), but we
haven't made a commitment to stay where we are,'' he said. ``Have no
plans whatsoever.''
   There may be some ``special part-time jobs'' that come up from
time to time, he said, but added, ``I really want to take life at a
much slower pace.''
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Soviet Union has bought 535,000 metric tons
of U.S. soybean meal for delivery in the 1988-89 marketing year that
began Oct. 1, says the Agriculture Department.
   Earlier this week, the Soviets bought 250,000 tons of soybeans
for 1988-89 delivery, the first of the new season.
   Although no further details were included in Thursday's
announcement, the meal sales could have a value of more than $120
million, based on average USDA market estimates of around $225 per
ton in the current marketing year.
   The Soviet Union bought more than 830,000 tons of soybeans and
1.3 million tons of soybean meal in 1987-88.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Holiday shoppers will find adequate supplies of
turkey and plenty of ham, according to Agriculture Department
analysts.
   ``Prices will likely be higher for turkey and lower for ham than
last year,'' the department's Economic Research Service said
Thursday. ``Cold storage stocks of turkeys on Oct. 1 were 11 percent
below the record level of 1987 and will be drawn down further by
holiday demands and a fourth-quarter production under last year's
level.''
   Pork production is up about 9 percent this year, the agency said
in a new outlook report. But the rise in output is slackening and
may only average about 1 percent higher over all of 1989.
   ``As of Sept. 1, there were 5 percent more market hogs than a
year ago'' in the major pork states, the report said. ``Farrowing
intentions for September-November and December-February indicate a
moderate production increase in first-half 1989.''
</TEXT>
