<FILEID>AP-NR-11-04-88 0107EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r w PM-AirlinePerformance     11-04 0675</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Airline Performance,670</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Government Says Airlines' On-Time Performances Are Improving</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By H. JOSEF HEBERT</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Despite a steady increase in air traffic,
airlines are cutting delays and there are signs that safety is
improving, according to the Transportation Department.
   The department said Thursday the major airlines have had at least
four out of every five flights arrive on time in each of the last
six months, including an 85.6 percent on-time record in September,
the best since the monthly figures became available 13 months ago.
   Complaints from air travelers to DOT's consumer affairs office
also continued their downward trend. The 1,370 complaints received
in October was 28 percent fewer than the 1,897 received in September
and 62 percent fewer than the 3,635 registered in October 1987, the
DOT said.
   At the same time, the department said, many of the ``safety
indicators'' show marked improvements this year.
   According to DOT figures, the number of near-collision reports by
pilots has dropped by 35 percent from 864 to 560 during the first
nine months of the year compared with the same period in l987. The
department did not say how many of the near-collision reports
involved commercial airlines.
   The number of air traffic controller errors, in which planes fly
closer than legally allowed, declined by 15 percent from 953 in the
first nine months of 1987 to 808 during the same period this year.
   ``The statistics indicate that our efforts to improve airline
safety and service to consumers are reaping dividends,'' said
Transportation Secretary Jim Burnley in a statement. ``They are
especially significant given that they come at a time of steadily
growing air traffic.''
   Nevertheless, officials acknowledge that there continue to be
pockets of concern in some parts of the country about air traffic
volume, controllers working long hours and too many controller
flight-handling errors.
   Last month the Federal Aviation Administration clamped tighter
traffic curbs on the Chicago airports, including O'Hare
International, because errors by Chicago controllers soared to 30
during the first 10 months of the year, compared to only 12 in all
of l987.
   The reduction of flights in and out of Chicago in turn has caused
increasing delay problems at O'Hare as well as at Chicago's smaller
Midway, which has added to delays at other airports, airline
officials have said.
   Burnley also has said that air traffic controllers in facilities
in New York, Atlanta and Los Angeles _ as well as Chicago _ are
still working more overtime than he would like.
   But the monthly on-time statistics released Thursday covered
September before the Chicago traffic curbs went into effect. During
September just over 81 percent of O'Hare's flights arrived on time
and 87 percent departed on time, the government said.
   The Dallas-Fort Worth Airport had the best on-time record with
90.8 percent of its flights arriving within 15 minutes of schedule,
while Detroit had the worst record at 69 percent.
   The figures include weather-related delays, but not those caused
by mechanical problems. The department considers a flight to be on
time if it arrives within 15 minutes of schedule.
   Between April and September, the 13 largest airlines reported an
80 percent average on-time arrival rate in each of the six months,
compared with about 74 percent between October l987 and last March,
said the DOT.
   Eastern Airlines, which throughout the year has ranked in the
bottom half of the group of airlines reporting on-time statistics,
soared to No. 1 among major air carriers in September with 90.5
percent of its flights on time.
   America West, largely a regional carrier with its hub in Phoenix,
had the overall best record with nearly 93 percent of it flights on
time, just ahead of Eastern. Northwest Airlines had the worst record
for September with 75.8 percent of its flights arriving on time.
   The airlines, meanwhile, reported receiving 5.71 reports of
mishandled baggage per 1,000 passengers carried in September, down
from 7.03 reports per 1,000 in August. The best previous month had
been May, when there were 6.16 reports per 1,000 passengers.
</TEXT>
