<1ST_LINE>r a PM-CrimefightingSenator     11-04 0308</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Crimefighting Senator,0316</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>State Senator Tackles Car Thief In Early Morning Bust</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW ORLEANS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A Louisiana state senator used tips from his
constituents to help police track down and recover his stolen car,
then chased and tackled one of the suspected thieves.
   ``I think people have to get involved to protect themselves or
they'll continue to be victims,'' said Sen. Ben Bagert.
   The New Orleans Democrat said his wife discovered that her own
car was ransacked and his car was missing Sunday morning. Bagert
said he put the word on the streets in his district that his car had
been stolen and soon began getting calls from tipsters.
   One constituent from Bagert's district, which includes affluent
and poverty-stricken areas, said he wanted to help because the
senator had done him a favor, Bagert said.
   ``The guy who started giving me the leads said they were getting
ready to cut it (the car) up pretty soon,'' he said.
   Using the man's information, Bagert drove to a spot where he
found his parked car covered with a tarpaulin. He called police, who
urged him to stay home. But they eventually allowed Bagert to
accompany them early Monday on a search for suspects.
   They failed to find the suspects at a grocery store parking lot
where tipsters said they had been seen. But when they hurried back
to the spot where the senator's car was parked, they spotted three
men driving off in it.
   The suspects saw the police, got out of the car and ran. Bagert,
clad in shorts, T-shirt and tennis shoes, ran after them along with
three police officers.
   Bagert tackled one of the suspects, police caught another one and
one escaped, according to Bagert, whose story was confirmed by
police.
   ``Cops and robbers at 4 o'clock in the morning,'' said Bagert.
``It was fun.''
</TEXT>
