<1ST_LINE>r w PM-Obit-Lindsay     11-04 0187</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Obit-Lindsay,190</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Newsweek Reporter Dies Of Cancer At 67</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   John Joseph Lindsay, the Senate reporter for
Newsweek magazine, died of cancer at his home in Washington. He was
67.
   Lindsay, who died Wednesday, had worked for The Washington Post
for eight years before joining Newsweek's Washington bureau in 1962.
He covered political nominating conventions and the campaigns of
major candidates in every election since 1952.
   He also covered the Watergate scandal, the National Governors
Association, the national committees of both the Republican and
Democratic parties, and the investigations into the assassinations
of President John F. Kennedy and Sen. Robert F. Kennedy.
   He covered the White House during the Johnson administration and
accompanied President Nixon on his 1972 trip to China.
   Lindsay was a native of Westboro, Mass., and served in the Army
from 1940 to 1946. He began his journalism career with the Bangor
Evening and Sunday Commercial in Maine after his discharge from the
Army and joined the Post in 1954.
   He was a Nieman Fellow at Harvard University in 1957-58.
   Survivors include his wife, Lorraine Lindsay of Washington, and
two children.
</TEXT>
