<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Hirohito     11-04 0189</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Hirohito,0194</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Emperor's Fever Increases, Further Bleeding Feared</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Emperor Hirohito's fever increased slightly today as
palace doctors feared the monarch's continued high temperature might
lead to further internal bleeding.
   The temperature of the world's longest-reigning monarch was 100.6
F, up slightly from the previous evening. Hirohito's normal
temperture is about 95.9 F.
   Doctors fear the continuous high fever might lead to further
bleeding in Hirohito's upper intestinal area, where physicians
conducted a bypass operation in September 1987, news reports said
today.
   Palace spokesman Kenji Maeda said the emperor's fever could
``largely be attributed to the blood transfusions'' conducted almost
daily, but doctors are now also concerned that worsening
inflammation around the upper intestine was keeping Hirohito's
temperature high.
   Physicians have stopped giving the 87-year-old monarch
antibiotics because continuous use of the drugs could damage kidney
and liver functions. But news reports said doctors are considering
resuming the medication to alleviate infection and reduce the risk
of further bleeding.
   The bedridden monarch, who has not discharged blood since
Thursday, has received 34.2 pints of transfusions since he fell
seriously ill and vomited blood on Sept. 19.
</TEXT>
