<FILEID>AP-NR-11-04-88 0124EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a AM-MillionaireBenefactor     11-04 0192</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Millionaire Benefactor,0197</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Businessman Who `Adopted' Poor Family Sentenced In Fraud Case</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WEST PALM BEACH, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A businessman who moved an
impoverished family from Miami to the suburbs was sentenced in
federal court Thursday to a two-year prison term on a bank fraud
charge.
   James Gisclair, 43, got the maximum jail term and was sentenced
to five years probation at federal court, where he pleaded guilty in
September to falsifying work records to obtain bank loans for a
now-defunct company.
   Gisclair, who must serve at least six months before he is
eligible for parole, also has been ordered to pay a $1.5 million
civil penalty on the charges.
   The Boca Raton businessman was besieged by creditors after his
much-publicized promise to ``adopt'' Anita Hunter, 28, and her five
children.
   The family was moved from Miami's impoverished Overtown section
to Delray Beach, but Ms. Hunter was unable to work because of
transportation and child-care difficulties.
   In September, the state Department of Health and Rehabilitative
Services put Ms. Hunter in a program that provides child care,
transportation to a job and federal rent subsidies. She now works in
an HRS office.
