<FILEID>AP-NR-11-04-88 0126EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a AM-Deaths 1stLd-Writethru a0797 11-04 0438</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Deaths, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0797,0448</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>Eds: ADDS Parker and Lindsay; Separates moved for AMs on Folsey as
a0803, on Parker as a0809 and Lindsay as a0401.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>George Folsey</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SANTA MONICA, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   George Folsey, a cinematographer who
was nominated for 13 Academy Awards during a career that spanned 50
years, died Tuesday stroke and long illness. He was 90.
   Folsey, who operated cameras in Hollywood for five decades, was
best known for his collaborations with directors Vincente Minelli,
George Cukor, Frank Capra, Ernst Lubitsch, Rouben Mamoulian and
Busby Berkeley.
   Among the films he shot were the Marx Brothers' ``Animal
Crackers,'' Capra's ``State of the Union,'' Minelli's ``Meet Me in
St. Louis'' and the television series ``The Fugitive.'' In 1976, he
returned to motion pictures to film special footage of Fred Astaire
and Gene Kelly for ``That's Entertainment, Part 2.''
   Folsey's Oscar nominations included ``Executive Suite,'' ``Seven
Brides for Seven Brothers'' and ``The Balcony.'' He also served as
president of the American Society of Cinematographers in the late
1950s.
</TEXT>
<BYLINE>Rudolf Romersa</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>GREENWICH, Conn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Rudolf Romersa, a vice president with
Gannett Outdoor, died Tuesday after a long illness. He was 59.
   Romersa went to work for Pacific Outdoor advertising in 1957.
Pacific was acquired in 1972 by Combined Communications Corporation,
which in turn was acquired in 1979 by Gannett Co. Inc., the the
Arlington, Va.-based news and information company.
</TEXT>
<BYLINE>Stewart Parker</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BELFAST, Northern Ireland (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Stewart Parker, 47, a playwright
who was described as a ``visionary in the theater,'' died Wednesday
of bone cancer.
   Parker's first important play, ``Spokesong,'' first performed in
Dublin, told the history of the bicycle as a way of illustrating the
history of Irish conflict and won him a London award as most
promising playwright of 1976.
   Other acclaimed plays were ``Northern Star'' and ``Pentecost,''
both dealing with the conflict between Protestants and Roman
Catholics in Northern Ireland, and a TV drama, ``I'm A Dreamer,
Montreal.''
</TEXT>
<BYLINE>John Lindsay</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   John Joseph Lindsay, the Senate reporter for
Newsweek magazine and a veteran of 26 years in the magazine's
Washington bureau, died Wednesday of cancer at age 67.
   Lindsay worked for The Washington Post for eight years before
joining Newsweek's Washington bureau in 1962. He covered political
nominating conventions and the campaigns of major candidates in
every election since 1952.
   Lindsay, who accompanied President Nixon to China in 1972, also
covered the National Governors Association, the national committees
of both the Republican and Democratic parties, the investigations
into the assassinations of President John F. Kennedy and Sen. Robert
F. Kennedy, D-N.Y., and the Watergate scandal.
</TEXT>
