<DOCNO> AP881104-0028 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-11-04-88 0309EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Brazil-Army     11-04 0170</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Brazil-Army,0173</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>40 Percent Of Brazilian Army Recruits In Poor Health</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BRASILIA, Brazil (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Forty percent of the Brazilians drafted
for military service are rejected because of malnutrition, bad teeth
and other health problems, the army says.
   A report Thursday by the Army Military Service department said
701,000 Brazilians were drafted last year, but of that number,
281,000 failed to pass the physical exam.
   The report said 26 percent of the draftees were rejected for
dental problems, and 9 percent had height or weight deficiencies
caused by malnutrition.
   It also showed that recruits from southern Brazil, the country's
most developed region, were on the average 11 pounds heavier and 3
inches taller than those from the poor North and Northeast, where
most of the rejectees came from.
   The former head of the Joint Chiefs of Staff, Gen. Waldyr de
Vasconcelos, was quoted as saying in the Rio de Janeiro newspaper
Jornal do Brasil that the report ``shows the Brazilian's quality of
life is bad and has not improved.''
</TEXT>
