<DOCNO> AP881104-0029 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-11-04-88 0150EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i AM-UN-Afghanistan     11-04 0384</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-UN-Afghanistan,0394</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Assembly Asks Political Solution Of Afghan Crisis</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PETER JAMES SPIELMANN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>UNITED NATIONS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The General Assembly reached unanimity
Thursday on Afghanistan, demanding a broad-based government and an
end to outside interference in Afghan affairs.
   The consensus resolution, sponsored by Pakistan and the Soviet
Union, passed by acclaimation.
   It says the war ``results from the violation of principles of the
Charter of the United Nations and of the recognized norms of
inter-state conduct,'' which could be interpreted as a slap at the
Soviets for entering Afghanistan or Moslem insurgents who operate
from bases in Pakistan.
   In previous years, the assembly overwhelmingly passed resolutions
calling for withdrawal of ``foreign forces'' from Afghanistan, with
the Soviet Union and its allies voting against.
   Moslem guerrillas began fighting in Afghanistan after a Communist
coup in April 1978 and Soviet military forces entered the country in
December 1979. The Soviets had an estimated 115,000 soldiers in the
country and began withdrawing May 15 under a U.N.-mediated agreement.
   In September, Soviet Foreign Minister Eduard A. Shevardnadze told
a U.N. news conference Pakistan was aiding the insurgents. He said
half the Soviet troops had withdrawn but the second phase of the
withdrawal depended on how the United Nations dealt with Moscow's
complaints.
   Ambassador Dante Caputo of Argentina, the General Assembly
president, said Thursday ``much remains to be done in order to
achieve a comprehensive solution of the Afghan question, including
the problem of the refugees and the difficulties in setting in
motion the necessary inter-Afghan dialogue aimed at establishing a
broad-based government acceptable to the Afghan people.''
   Before the war Afghanistan's population was about 15.5 million,
but about one-third have fled _ more than 3 million to Pakistan and
nearly all the others to Iran. Most of those in Pakistan live in
border cities and refugee camps that serve as bases and supply
points for the guerrillas.
   The United Nations has begun a program to resettle the refugees
and rebuild Afghanistan's shattered agricultural economy.
   Afghanistan's government invited the insurgents discuss a
coalition government, but they refused.
   Burhanuddin Rabbani, chairman of the seven-party guerrilla
alliance, said Thursday: ``The puppet regime is the shadow of the
Russian troops in Afghanistan. As soon as the Russian troops are out
of the country, the shadow will also disappear.''
</TEXT>
