<1ST_LINE>r w PM-WashingtoninBrief     11-04 0576</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Washington in Brief,600</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Military Hospitals to Treat More Dependents</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Pentagon hopes to save money on health care
for dependents and retirees by expanding many military hospitals'
capacity to treat them.
   The project is expected to cost the Army and Air Force $14.6
million but still save them $13.9 million compared with the cost of
paying to treat the dependents and retirees at civilian hospitals.
   Assistant Defense Secretary William Mayer decided to allow Army
and Air Force hospitals in 12 states to expand facilities or hire
additional nurses and other staff to provide more surgical,
obstetrics, gynecology, cardiology and psychiatry services. Similar
Navy projects are now under consideration.
   Military hospitals are required to serve dependents and retirees
on a space-available basis, giving first priority to men and women
on active duty.
   The states in which military hospitals will be expanded are
Georgia, Texas, Virginia, New Jersey, Kentucky, Kansas, Alaska,
Oklahoma, Utah, New York, Nebraska and Florida.
</TEXT>
<HEAD>___</HEAD>
<HEAD>Iraq Offers Help In Detecting Chemical Weapons Use</HEAD>
<DATELINE>UNITED NATIONS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Iraq, which acknowledged using poison gas
in its war with Iran, has agreed to help investigate allegations of
chemical warfare in the world, according to a U.N. document.
   The report by Secretary-General Javier Perez de Cuellar on
chemical and biological weapons, released Thursday, includes the
responses of 17 nations that have offered the use of laboratories or
experts in chemical warfare to develop ways of detecting use of such
weapons.
   Iraq offered the services of two doctors, two chemists and a
pharmacologist, but said ``it is not possible for Iraqi laboratories
to be used'' in chemical and biological warfare investigations.
   Last summer, Iraqi Foreign Minister Tariq Aziz was questioned
about alleged chemical warfare in the Persian Gulf war, and
responded that Iraq used such weapons only after Iran used them
first.
   Iran says it has the ability to make chemical weapons, but has
never used them. Investigations by U.N. experts confirmed that Iraq
used chemical weapons against Iran throughout the war, which began
in September 1980.
</TEXT>
<HEAD>___</HEAD>
<HEAD>Black-White Infant Mortality Rate Gap Widens, Group Says</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A children's advocacy group says the gap
between the mortality rates for black and white infants born in the
United States is continuing to widen.
   The Children's Defense Fund, basing its study on data released by
the National Center for Health Statistics, a federal agency, said
Thursday it found a black-white infant mortality ratio of 2.02 in
1986, the most recent year for which figures were available.
   The findings mean a black baby was more than twice as likely to
die in infancy as a white baby. That compared to a 1.96 ratio in
1985 and 1.69 in 1940.
   It added that, while the death rates among black and white
infants for non-preventable birth defects was virtually identical,
black babies were far more likely to die of preventable causes such
as inadequate prenatal care.
   They were four times more likely to die of prematurity and low
birth weight, three times more likely to die of pneumonia, influenza
and homicide and two times more likely to die as a result of newborn
and maternal complications, infections and accidents, the fund said.
   Overall, the U.S. infant mortality rate declined slightly from
10.6 deaths per 1,000 live births in 1985 to 10.4 in 1986.
   The mortality rate for black infants in 1986 was 18 per 1,000
births and, for white infants, 8.9 per 1,000 births.
</TEXT>
