<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP881104-0033 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-11-04-88 0232EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r p PM-Drought-Politics     11-04 0493</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Drought-Politics,470</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Does Drought Lead to Party Change?</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Political Rdp Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RANDOLPH E. SCHMID</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Do Americans blame the president or his party
for the weather? A case could be made _ at least statistically _
that they do.
   That's because, historically, droughts have tended to be followed
by a change in the party in charge of the White House.
   Eight times in this century the White House has changed party:
   _Four times in drier than normal years.
   _Four times in moist years that happened to come at the end of a
four-year term of drier than normal weather.
   Climate, thus, would seem to give an edge to Democrat Michael
Dukakis, although the polls indicate a lead for Republican George
Bush.
   Studies of the 1800s, when the nation was more economically
dependent on the farm population, show a regular pattern of
political upheavals at the White House in the wake of drought.
   This summer's drought came after a dry 1987 but followed several
relatively moist years before that.
   The pattern was similar _ though not as severe _ in the dry
season of 1980, when Republican Ronald Reagan ousted Democrat Jimmy
Carter.
   And Carter won office in 1976, a dry year that followed nearly a
decade of normal or above normal wetness, according to records kept
by the National Climatic Data Center.
   Republican Richard Nixon ended eight years of Democrats in the
White House in 1968, a year when rainfall was slightly above median,
but which followed dry years in 1966 and 1967.
   John F. Kennedy won in 1960, as three years of moist conditions
ended and the nation slipped into a slightly drier than normal
season.
   And 1952 marked the first dry season in eight years _ a year that
Dwight Eisenhower turned the Democrats out of the White House for
the first time in two decades.
   It was the famous Dust Bowl years of the 1930s that saw the
Democrats take up residence there, of course, with Franklin D.
Roosevelt winning the office.
   The GOP had captured the executive mansion in 1920, the second
straight moist year, but following a drought in 1917-18.
   In 1912 Democrat Woodrow Wilson took office, also in the second
year after a drought.
   In addition, it may have been clearing weather in California that
saved his second term.
   The 1916 election came just a day after a major storm struck the
Pacific Coast, delaying results from California which Wilson won by
a narrow margin. Wilson's win was helped by a strong vote in the
heavily Democratic counties in the state's northeast, an area that
had been blanketed by snow the day before.
   While many changes at the White House have followed droughts,
there have, of course, been dry years that didn't see a change in
party: Notably 1924, 1936 and 1956 which were below normal in rain
but which saw Calvin Coolidge, Roosevelt and Eisenhower retain their
offices.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP881104-0034 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-11-04-88 0230EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r p PM-DemocratsContributors     11-04 0445</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Democrats Contributors,450</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Show Biz Standouts, Business Chieftains Among Major Democratic
Contributors</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Actress Mary Tyler Moore and TV producer Norman
Lear are among a wide range of celebrities, financiers and others
who gave large sums to the Democratic National Committee in the past
year, according to party records.
   Notables who made sizable contributions of less than $100,000
included: California stat legislator Tom Hayden, the husband of
actress Jane Fonda, $60,000; Miss Moore, $10,000; Miami Dolphins
owner Joseph Robbie, $50,000, and Lear, $25,000.
   The information was contained in DNC records filed in Austin,
Texas.
   The funds were given to the national committee's ``soft money''
account, which does not have to conform to limits imposed on the
candidates and the political parties by the Federal Election
Commission.
   The so-called soft money accounts are largely transferred by both
the Republican and Democratic National Committees to state parties.
   Democratic National Chairman Paul G. Kirk Jr. has said he would
disclose details of the committee's soft-money fund raising after
the election.
   Texas law, however, requires the parties to file either a list of
donors or a Federal Election Commission registration record when
they transfer money into the state from elsewhere.
   Since the soft money was not raised under federal limits, the
Democrats were required to submit a list of donors.
   Those listed as contributing $100,000 were:
   Andrew A. Athens, Chicago; Robert M. Bass, Fort Worth; Eli Broad
of Kaufman & Broad, Los Angeles; Ann Cox Chambers, Atlanta; Richard
D. Cohen, Boston; Marvin Davis, Los Angeles; Mark Dayton,
Minneapolis; Richard J. Dennis, president of Richard J. Dennis and
Co., Chicago;
   Thomas A. Dennis, Chicago; Barry Diller, 20th Century Fox, Los
Angeles; Sandra Ferry, Cambridge, Mass.; Susie Field, Interscope
Investments; Frederick Field, Interscope Investments, Los Angeles;
John Freidenrich, Mountain View, Calif.; Monte Friedkin, Hallandale,
Fla,; Mitchell Kapor, Cambridge, Mass.;
   Phillip M. Klutznick, Klutznick Investments, Chicago; John R.
Koza, Las Vegas; William P. Kruer, San Diego; Allam M. Levanthal,
Boston; Carl Lindner, Cincinnati; Alida Rockefeller Messenger,
Minneappolis; Lester Miller, St. Louis; Raymond D. Nasher, Dallas;
Bernard J. O'Keefe, Wayland, Mass.;
   Arthur Ortenber, N.Y.; Milan Panic, ICN Pharmaceuticals Inc.,
Costa Mesa, Calif.; Ronald O. Perelman, chairman Revlon, N.Y.;
Hannah Jacobs Ramos, N.Y.; Carl Rheuban, Los Angeles; Blanchette
Rockefeller, N.Y.; John D. Rockefeller, Washington, D.C.; Sen. Jay
Rockefeller, D-W.Va., David Rose, of Rose Associates, N.Y.;
   Steven J. Ross, of Warner Communications, N.Y.; Madeleine Russel,
Atherton, Calif.; Herbert Simon, Indianapolis; Ballard F. Smith, La
Jolla, Calif.; Linda Arnell Smith, La Jolla; Janet G. Stein, N.Y.;
Linda and Howard Sterling, Los Angeles; Bruce G. Sundlum,
Providence, R.I.; Lew R. Wasserman, MCA-Universal Studios, Universal
City, Calif.; Leo S. Wyler, of Wyler Associates, Los Angeles.
</TEXT>
