<1ST_LINE>r p PM-DefendingHome Bjt   11-04 0672</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Defending Home, Bjt,680</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Dukakis Battles to Keep Home State in His Column</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CHRISTOPHER B. DALY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BOSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Like a military general waging a campaign far
afield, Democrat Michael Dukakis has left a small garrison of
trusted aides back in Massachusetts to protect his home territory
from enemy attacks.
   The Dukakis effort to carry Massachusetts on Election Day has all
the elements of the presidential nominee's other statewide campaigns
except one: the candidate.
   ``Basically, we are running a traditional Democratic campaign in
this state, not unlike the campaigns he ran when he was running for
governor,'' said James McGovern, a spokesman for the Dukakis
campaign in Massachusetts.
   McGovern and other Dukakis aides have complained for weeks that
they are stuck between a rock and a hard place.
   If they wage a strong campaign here, they are vulnerable to
charges that the governor is so weak that he is afraid of losing his
home state. If they don't campaign hard, they are open to the rap
that they are taking the state for granted.
   ``We're in a situation where we're damned if we do and damned if
we don't,'' McGovern moaned.
   They have decided to err on the side of caution. Although the
national campaign strategists have raided the Boston headquarters
for field workers, the campaign has kept 12 paid staff working
full-time on delivering Massachusetts.
   ``We're running a campaign,'' McGovern insisted. ``By contrast, I
am unaware of any semblance of a field organization put together in
Massachusetts by the Bush camp. In fact, I am unaware of any
campaign other than what goes on in the Statehouse by a few
Republican legislators. I don't see evidence of any real outreach.''
   In fact, the Bush campaign has not written off Massachusetts.
   At the urging of Andrew Card, a former Republican legislator in
Massachusetts and a former Reagan White House aide, the Bush
national campaign has used Massachusetts adroitly to keep Dukakis on
the defensive.
   In a state where Democrats outnumber Republicans by about 4-1 and
where no Republican except Ronald Reagan has won a statewide
election since 1972, the Bush forces are overmatched on the ground
by the Dukakis team.
   But the Republicans have run a sharper campaign, offering almost
daily press conferences to undermine Dukakis' standing.
   The campaign also scored a major coup on Sept. 1 when the vice
president toured polluted Boston Harbor and attacked Dukakis' record
on the environment. The campaign was buoyed by a second Bush visit
for a showy endorsement from the Boston Police Patrolmen's
Association.
   According to published polls, the Bush effort has had some impact
in the state where Dukakis won a landslide re-election to a third
term just two years ago with nearly 70 percent of the vote.
   A series of surveys by KRC Research published in the Boston
Herald indicated that Dukakis enjoyed a 51-37 percent lead in July.
That edge disappeared by Sept. 1, when the poll showed the race a
dead heat at 42 percent.
   By mid-October, however, Dukakis had fought back to a 10-point
advantage in Massachusetts, leading Bush by 49-39 percent, only to
see Bush gain three points among undecideds and close to 49-42
percent as of Tuesday.
   James French, Dukakis' Massachusetts campaign coordinator, was
publicly more upbeat than the figures might suggest, saying, ``We're
confident of a big victory in Massachusetts.''
   To make sure of that, the Dukakis camp has mobilized its
customarily strong field organization, with 34 field offices in the
state, phone banks, sign-holding assignments in 123 cities and towns
and an extensive get-out-the-vote effort on Election Day.
   The campaign has also dropped more than one million pieces of
literature at homes statewide and plans to use 3,000 volunteers in
the Election Day operation.
   The campaign also is running short radio advertisements attacking
the Bush record on the environment, elderly and the economy, along
with some television ads in Springfield. For the most part, though,
they are relying on what campaign aides call ``free media'' _ that
is, news coverage.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
