<DOCNO> AP881104-0036 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-11-04-88 0229EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r p PM-CampaignAds Bjt   11-04 0816</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Campaign Ads, Bjt,820</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Final Ad Blitz: Some Uplifting, Some Attacking</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JILL LAWRENCE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Reagan asks Americans to ``continue
the change'' by voting Republican, and Democrats hit hard on
pocketbook issues and Dan Quayle's qualifications in the latest
barrage of political television ads.
   The national parties launched their final round Thursday, with
the Republicans showcasing Reagan and the Democrats appealing to the
average person's pocketbook in generic spots designed to drum up
support for candidates from president on down.
   Democrat Michael Dukakis' campaign unleashed its latest broadside
against GOP vice presidential nominee Quayle, a 30-second spot
featuring a well-known excerpt from his debate with Lloyd Bentsen,
the Democratic vice presidential debate.
   Onscreen appear the words, ``Before you vote, remember this,''
followed by the debate clip.
   Quayle: ``I have as much experience in the Congress as Jack
Kennedy did when he sought the presidency.''
   Bentsen: ``I served with Jack Kennedy. I knew Jack Kennedy. Jack
Kennedy was a friend of mine. Senator, you're no Jack Kennedy.''
   These words then appear: ``President Quayle?''
   Both Dukakis and Republican George Bush are running a varied mix
of upbeat and attack ads in key TV markets across the country. Their
themes but not their names appear in numerous generic TV and radio
spots produced by the Republican and Democratic national committees.
   The RNC entered the final phase of its $9 million media drive
Thursday with the TV message from Reagan. ``America is at peace, and
we are prosperous once more,'' Reagan says in the ad. ``On Tuesday,
I hope you will vote Republican _ up and down the ticket _ to
continue the change we began in 1981.''
   The GOP also has a 60-second radio ad in which Reagan recounts
his record and says ``our work is not yet done.'' He contends the
GOP has become ``the party of the working people, the family and the
neighborhood.''
   The DNC, contending it is the true party of the average working
person, released two pocketbook appeals designed to bolster
Democratic local, state and national candidates.
   One DNC ad, featuring festive images of the GOP convention and
headlines about nasty campaigning, says: ``What's hiding behind all
of this? The Republican tax plan ... If you make $200,000, you get a
tax gift of $30,000. ... If you're a typical middle class taxpayer _
like most of us _ the Republicans will give you a tax break, too.
Twenty bucks.''
   In the other DNC spot, an announcer bemoans foreign loans and
land purchases and the millions of U.S. jobs he says were shipped
overseas. ``Are the Republicans selling out America's future?'' he
asks.
   Both the RNC and DNC are running numerous radio commercials as
well. DNC officials won't discuss their advertising budget other
than to say this is the first time they've been able to raise enough
money for generic media.
   Each national party has produced six TV ads in all. But while
most of the DNC ads ran briefly and then vanished, the RNC is still
using spots it was airing as far back as July.
   Earlier DNC spots discussed the future of America's children,
attacked the GOP record on the federal deficit, and charged that GOP
prosperity hasn't trickled down to workers or the elderly.
   One of the RNC's long-running spots shows a little girl who an
announcer says has ``known virtually nothing but peace and economic
growth'' thanks to Republicans. Another flashes images of inflation,
gas lines and Jimmy Carter set to the tune ``I Remember You.''
   A third Republican spot, on the air since Oct. 10, shows pilot
Chuck Yeager in a defense plant alleging: ``When liberal Democrats
talk about slashing defense spending, they're not just talking about
America losing ground. They're talking about Americans losing jobs.''
   The Republicans also are using two Hispanic television ads, one
talking about Hispanic gains during the Reagan years and another
citing recently named Education Secretary Lauro Cavazos as ``a
friend in Washington.''
   The Justice Department, meanwhile, said it will investigate a
Spanish-language radio ad running in Hidalgo County in south Texas.
   Democrats complained GOP officials in the county are violating
federal voting rights laws by running ads that cite penalties for
non-citizens who vote and that twice remind listeners election
officials ``will be watching.''
   Republican officials defended the ads as proper and said they are
not an attempt at intimidation.
   And in Washington state, the Bush campaign has cut much of its
Seattle television advertising in the last days before the election,
station officials said. Dan Cumming of the state Bush campaign said
the decision was made at the national level and did not reflect any
decision to write off the state.
   A statewide poll conducted by KING-TV in Seattle and released
Thursday did show Dukakis with a 10-point advantage over George
Bush, 51-41, but the survey of likely voters had a five-point margin
of error.
</TEXT>
