<FILEID>AP-NR-11-04-88 0225EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r p PM-Bush-HighSchools     11-04 0575</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Bush-High Schools,580</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Bush Aims At Wider Audience With High School Visits</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Political Rdp Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TOM RAUM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO HEIGHTS, Ill. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The students duel with the American
flags instead of waving them, and they cheer in the wrong place in a
speech, but George Bush is spending a lot of campaign time in high
schools.
   A desire to be the ``education president'' has little to do with
the visits. Bush campaign planners like the ready-made energetic
audiences that high schools, particularly those in Republican areas,
can provide.
   The school bands and always, always, the rows of spangled
cheerleaders on the stage with pompons, make for a colorful rally _
to be seen by the millions more who watch snippets of the events on
the local evening television news.
   Thus, Bush can appeal to blue-collar ``Reagan Democrats'' in
pivotal industrial Midwestern states without having to go into their
neighborhoods.
   ``We often go to schools which are familiar landscapes in the
communities,'' said Sheila Tate, Bush's press secretary. ``At this
time of the year, you like to have indoor events. And, often in a
community, a school is the biggest facility.''
   ``We also love the exuberance of the voters of tomorrow.''
   There lies one of the problems. When Bush tells rally
participants to go out and vote because he needs their help, more
often than not most of them aren't old enough. So Bush sometimes
adds an admonition to ``tell your parents.''
   And even though Republican campaign workers do their best to plan
every detail, the results aren't always what is expected when
audiences are so young.
   For instance, at a fieldhouse rally at Bloom Township High School
in this Chicago suburb on Thursday, muscular actor Arnold
Schwarzenegger got a far bigger cheer than did Bush.
   The vice president's reference to the ``L'' word mostly drew a
blank, and some students in the back of the hall ignored the speech
entirely and had sword fights with the American flags camaign
workers had distributed.
   Teenagers screech, scream, wave flags and constantly blow
airhorns handed out in the dozens by campaign staffers.
   They cheer sometimes indiscriminately, giving equally loud cheers
to mention of the death penalty or to a mention by Bush that a
Democratic Congress will spend more tax dollars.
   Bush apologized to students at one late-afternoon rally at
Lansing Catholic Central in Michigan this week for their being
``made to stay after school'' by their principal. ``But this is one
great rally.''
   Bush has been hitting a high school or two a day for the past few
weeks.
   High schools are picked for Bush's standard rally speech. More
serious speeches are usually delivered to college audiencies or to
meetings of national organizations.
   But with the campaign winding down, most of Bush's remaining
appearances will be at rallies _ and that more often than not means
more high schools.
   Bush isn't the only presidential candidate to use high school
rallies as a frequent forum for campaign appearances. President
Reagan did it and so does Democrat Michael Dukakis.
   ``This is not a campaign about (prison) furloughs and flag
factories,'' Dukakis said recently at a high school in another
Chicago suburb. ``This is a campaign about the future of America.
And especially about young people.''
   National public opinion polls show there is an age gap, usually
in the double digits _ with Bush generally enjoying more support
among the youngest voters than Dukakis.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP881104-0038 </DOCNO>
