<1ST_LINE>r p PM-Quayle     11-04 0640</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Quayle,650</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Quayle Raps Dukakis on Drug Issue</HEAD>
<NOTE>EDs: Prenoon lede uncertain; late-morning plant tour scheduled in
Louisiana.</NOTE>
<HEAD>With PM-Political Rdp Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MERRILL HARTSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>STILLWATER, Okla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Republican vice presidential candidate
Dan Quayle says Michael Dukakis' tough talk on drugs ``rings
hollow'' because the attorney general of Massachusetts has
complained of losing ground against narcotics traffickers.
   Seeking to counteract Dukakis' attacks on Vice President George
Bush's record in the Reagan administration anti-drug abuse fight,
Quayle used an Oklahoma State University speech to label the
Massachusetts governor soft on crime.
   Quayle, standing before a crowd of more than 4,000 college
students and citizens of this Oklahoma college town, sent a
long-distance challenge to Dukakis to explain a statement by the
Massachusetts attorney general, James Shannon, a Democrat.
   ``We're losing the war on drugs in the Commonwealth of
Massachusetts,'' Quayle quoted Shannon as saying. An aide to the
senator said that Shannon's statement had appeared in June 10
editions of The New York Times.
   ``With five days to go before the election, Mr. Dukakis is coming
out with a lot of tough talk about a war on drugs,'' Quayle said.
``But as with so many other areas of tough talk, the governor's
position on drugs rings hollow.''
   ``If Mr. Dukakis can't fight drugs effectively in his own
backyard, how can he make claims to do so for America?'' he asked.
   Late Thursday, Shannon issued a statement through the Dukakis
campaign, saying: ``The reason we have a drug problem in
Massachusetts and 49 other states is because George Bush blew the
one job Ronald Reagan gave him, and that was to spearhead the
administration's war on drugs.
   ``While Governor Dukakis led the nation in bringing early drug
education into the schools and spending more money on drug
enforcement, George Bush was asleep at the wheel.''
   Quayle said that Dukakis' opposition to the death penalty and
tough mandatory sentences for narcotics traffickers shows the
governor is unequipped to succeed in the battle against drug
trafficking and drug use.
   Quayle gave his speech to an enthusiastic crowd on the OSU
campus, although there were Dukakis-Bentsen signs and some hecklers
in the audience. As a blue balloon prematurely escaped its net and
sailed over Quayle's head, the senator quipped, ``Good night, Mike.''
   The Indiana senator was traveling to Louisiana and Alabama today
before heading back to Washington for a one-night stay.
   Quayle will campaign in Maryland and West Virginia on Saturday,
but no schedule has been announced for Sunday. He will travel to
Indianapolis on Monday, cast his vote and return to Washington for
Tuesday night's election returns.
   Quayle's speech here came at the end of a rocky campaign day in
which his Boeing 727 jet was grounded on an airport runway in
Owensboro, Ky., for several hours and he had to scrub two
appearances in the Greenville-Spartanburg, S.C., area. Instead,
Quayle flew to the Greenville airport and met with reporters from
the area, shook a few hands in a small crowd and got back on the
plane for the trip to Oklahoma.
   Meeting with reporters from various news organizations in
Oklahoma, Quayle signaled what responsibilities he might have in a
Bush administration.
   Although he said he thought it was ``bad luck'' to talk about
such a scenario before Election Day, Quayle did say that Bush had
talked to him about heading a space council.
   He also noted previous talk of Quayle heading the anti-drug abuse
effort, although the senator also said that legislation passed by
Congress in its waning days would require that a drug czar be a
Cabinet officer.
   Quayle also said that his experience on the congressional foreign
relations panels would make him a valuable member of the National
Security Council and said he considered himself particularly well
equipped to provide advice on education and job-training programs.
</TEXT>
