<1ST_LINE>r p PM-Bush-Latvian     11-04 0399</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Bush-Latvian,390</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Chairman of Latvians for Bush Resigns Amid Charge of Nazi Link</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Political Rdp Bjt</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The chairman of Latvians for Bush has resigned
his post following charges that he belonged to a World War II group
with Nazi ties, the Bush campaign said.
   Akselis Mangulis, who was also a volunteer with the vice
president's Coalition of American Nationalities, has ``suspended his
membership'' in the coalition, said Alixe Glen, a spokeswoman
traveling with the Republican presidential nominee.
   Mangulis is the eighth person connected with Bush's ethnic
council to step down following reports of connections to Nazi or
anti-Semitic groups.
   Editors at The Philadelphia Inquirer said Thursday night that
they were planning a story for Friday's editions on Mangulis'
membership in the Latvian Legion, a group which had connections to
the German SS, the quasi-military unit of the Nazi Party.
   Bush campaign spokesmen in Washington and on the campaign trail
told reporters Thursday evening of Mangulis' ``suspension'' and his
resignation of the Latvians for Bush post.
   Mark Goodin, a Bush spokesman, said the Mangulis' family
confirmed the association with the Latvian Legion, but said he was
conscripted in that group against his will.
   ``The charges lodged against Mangulis deserve to be clarified by
him away from the Bush-Quayle campaign,'' said Goodin. ``As of this
time, his volunteer membership in the Coalition of American
Nationalities is suspended as he pursues that right.''
   A woman who answered the phone at the Mangulis residence in
Andover, Mass., denied that he had been asked to resign from
Latvians for Bush or had been a member of a group sympathetic to the
Nazis.
   ``He was not resigning and he will run until Mr. Bush is
elected,'' said the woman who identified herself as Mrs. Mangulis
but refused to give her first name. ``Bush campaign did not ask him
to resign. He did not resign because he did not have reason to
resign.
   ``He is not in any group in World War II,'' said the woman, who
spoke with a heavy accent. ``He was a young man and he is not a Nazi
and he is not anti-Semitic. I'm telling you honest and truthful. All
are lies, never did he resign, never was it no shame.''
   She said the family is seeking legal assistance and ``I am going
to take action for this harassment.''
   She said her husband was not home.
</TEXT>
