<DOCNO> AP881104-0043 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-11-04-88 0126EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u a AM-Hostages-Nightline     11-04 0552</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Hostages-Nightline,0568</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>U.S. Middle East Expert Tried To Free Hostages, ``Nightline''
Reports</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A U.S. expert on the Middle East with ties to
George Bush's presidential campaign met with Syrian officials in
August in an attempt to free the U.S. hostages in Lebanon, ABC-TV's
``Nightline'' reported Wednesday.
   After the U.S. government learned of the meeting, Secretary of
State George Shultz told Syria that the expert, Paul Jureidini, in
no way represented the government, the program reported. Shultz also
told Jureidini to end any such contacts.
   A spokesman for Vice President Bush, Mark Goodin, denied that
Jureidini's meeting was in any way sanctioned by the campaign. As
late as July, Jureidini served as an unpaid consultant on the Middle
East to the campaign, ``Nightline'' said.
   Jureidini, who has been a frequent Pentagon consultant and has
top-level U.S. security clearance, said on the program that he told
his Syrian hosts during the meeting in Damascus that he was acting
on his own. Joining Jureidini at the meeting was his partner, Ronald
McLaurin.
   ``Nightline,'' quoting Syrian sources, reported that during the
Aug. 16 meeting, Jureidini and his hosts discussed options for
securing the release of the nine American hostages and what the
impact of any such release would be on the U.S. presidential
election.
   ``Nightline'' also reported that the release last month of
hostage Mithileshwar Singh, an Indian professor who is a legal
resident of the United States, followed third-party contacts between
the United States and Iran.
   The program said the intermediary was West German Foreign
Minister Hans-Dietrich Genscher. Through this channel, Shultz told
Iran that the U.S. hostages must be freed if there is to be real
progress in improving U.S.-Iranian relations.
   Following this contact, substantial pressure was exerted on the
Hezbollah, the radical group in Lebanon believed to be holding the
hostages, ``Nightline'' reported. That pressure led to Singh's
release, it said.
   Following his release, the U.S. government sent word to Iran via
the Japanese government that all the U.S. hostages must be released,
and that there would be no deal and no negotiations, ``Nightline''
reported.
   Iranian officials said that response was an insult; that Iran was
not trying to make a deal, only start a process that would lead to
the release of the other hostages, the program reported.
   From the Iranian perpective, the Singh release was a gesture that
could have led to more releases, ``Nightline'' said. But the U.S.
response, in the Iranian view, resulted in the door slamming shut,
it reported.
   U.S. officials told the program that the response was consistent
with U.S. policy on the hostages.
   ``Nightline'' reported that the West German contact was just one
of many such contacts regarding the hostages between Iranian
officials and people who claimed to represent either the U.S.
government or the presidential campaigns of Bush or Michael Dukakis.
   Spokesmen for both campaigns denied they had authorized any such
contacts.
   The number of such contacts was so great that in October, the
Iranian government complained in an official message to the U.S.
government, ``Nightline'' reported. Iran refused to provide the
names of those it claims made such contacts, the show reported.
   In early October, Shultz announced that such contacts were
unauthorized and that those making them should ``butt out'' and let
the State Department handle the hostage situation.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP881104-0044 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-11-04-88 0243EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r p PM-Bentsen     11-04 0471</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Bentsen,480</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Bush Backs Louisiana Senator for Democratic Leadership Post</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds note: Top prospects uncertain</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By STEVEN KOMAROW</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LAKE CHARLES, La. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Democratic vice presidential candidate
Lloyd Bentsen combined a little Capitol Hill politics with his
national campaign by endorsing Sen. Bennett Johnston, D-La., to
become the next Senate Democratic leader.
   Campaigning in Louisiana, one of the few Southern states where
polls show the Democrats are within a few points of the Republicans,
Bentsen spoke at a rally Thursday night in favor of Johnston.
   ``As far as I'm concerned, this fellow is going to be the new
majority leader of the United States Senate,'' said Bentsen.
``That's a public pledge and commitment right there.''
   It was the first time the Texas senator has taken a public stand
on the race to replace Robert C. Byrd, who is retiring as majority
leader this year.
   Johnston and Sens. Daniel Inouye, D-Hawaii, and George Mitchell,
D-Me., are competing for the powerful post. The position will remain
with the Democrats if they retain a majority in the chamber.
   Asked about Bentsen's statement afterward, Johnston said his
colleague had made his preference known privately but never before
in public. Asked how he was doing in the race, Johnston held up his
hand to show his thumb and forefinger held a little bit apart.
   Bentsen planned to stop in Houston today before heading to
California for a quick campaign swing.
   Bentsen's stand on the Senate leadership issue marked an abrupt
change from the down-home East Texas politics that occupied most of
his day on Thursday.
   Bentsen toured by bus more than 200 miles through the rural
communities near the Louisiana and Arkansas borders. The goal was to
win Reagan Democrats to the Dukakis-Bentsen ticket.
   In speeches in Longview, Paris and Sulphur Springs, Bentsen
highlighted the Democratic campaign's theme that he and presidential
nominee Michael Dukakis were on the side of the middle class and
were willing to stand up for American workers in international trade
negotiations.
   Talking to reporters on his bus, Bentsen said he still thought
the Democrats could eke out a victory next Tuesday. But he also
speculated on the kind of relationship George Bush might have with
Congress if elected president, in light of the Republicans' negative
campaigning.
   ``I don't see how... a president has any kind of mandate if he
wins by the amount of negative advertising,'' he said.
   A new president usually has a ``honeymoon'' with Congress, but in
Bush's case ``it would be an awfully short one, if you had that,''
he said.
   Bentsen drew crowds at his events with the help of actor Rob Lowe
and singer Gary Morris, who accompanied him for the trip. Morris, a
Texan who has also campaigned with Dukakis, introduced Bentsen after
warming up the crowds with a few songs.

</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP881104-0045 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-11-04-88 0246EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a PM-DesperateMan Bjt   11-04 0730</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Desperate Man, Bjt,0751</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Failing Entrepreneur Goes On Hunger Strike To Draw Wall Street's
Attention</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto NY6</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LARRY NEUMEISTER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Struck down by bad luck and last year's stock
market crash, a once-rising star among entrepreneurs is trying
desperately to save his business with a 12-day-old hunger strike in
an illegally parked van opposite the New York Stock Exchange.
   ``I've come to the seat of capitalism, the New York Stock
Exchange, to be heard,'' Jan Stuart said Thursday.
   Stuart said he has not eaten since he left his Cliffside Park,
N.J., apartment on Oct. 24 to live in a van on Wall Street, just
feet away from where George Washington was sworn in as the first
president of the United States.
   The 34-year-old owner of Jan Stuart Skin Care Co., who was once
featured on the cover of Entrepreneur Magazine, was viewed
skeptically at first as police ticketed the van for each of the
first four days and passers-by told him he was crazy.
   But as the days passed _ and Stuart's weight dropped from 190
pounds to 175 _ police left him alone and onlookers started writing
encouraging notes on his van, which features posters that read:
``Wake Up America'' and ``Help Me Save My Company.''
   Dozens of people have already signed a petition, attached to his
van, that Stuart hopes to present to the stock exchange to show that
there is concern for the small business owner in America.
   ``I have to do something drastic to keep my business going. I'm
desperately in need of funding,'' Stuart said.
   ``Small business people need help. We are the future of this
country. Big business has put me down. In the small business world,
anything can cause destruction,'' he added.
   Eight years ago, Stuart invested $2,000 in a line of
natural-ingredient men's shaving and skin care products, and turned
it into a business that had annual sales in the millions.
   As his product began showing up on the shelves of Bloomingdale's,
A&S, Lord & Taylor, Macy's and other major department stores, he
attracted national media attention.
   He built a staff of 60 workers and expanded his line to 30 skin
care products for men sold in 2,000 department stores in the United
States, Canada, England, Australia, Puerto Rico and the Caribbean.
The Entrepreneur article called him the ``Father of the Men's Skin
Care Industry.''
   But Stuart's luck turned when he attempted to raise $9.2 million
so the company could continue to grow. He said a major underwriter
went out of business and a second company that offered necessary
financing went down in the stock market crash last year.
   Some companies showed interest in teaming up with him but
``corporate constipation'' got in the way, he said, meaning he would
have to wait until lengthy feasibility studies were completed.
   ``My dream has been to build a business, become a viable part of
the American economy,'' Stuart said.
   Now, Stuart said he is left with a $2 million debt and just
enough of his products to supply mail-order clients.
   In a full-page advertisement in The New York Times on Aug. 3,
Stuart pleaded with the public to ``Please Help Me Save My
Company!'' He said the ad resulted in hundreds of letters and phone
calls but no financing.
   Now, he sits in the van he has rented for $600 a week, outfitted
with a bed and toilet, and watches as people sign their name and
offer opinions on his plight.
   ``Please eat,'' wrote Lorne Williams.
   ``Wish you all you are wishing for comes true, love you, mom,''
reads another note.
   Michael J. Basel, who works on the floor of the stock exchange,
tapped on his window and shouted him luck.
   ``He's trying to say, `I've got an idea. I want you to take me to
the moon,''' Basel said.
   ``Guys like him aren't going to make it right now,'' Basel said,
explaining that Wall Street is not funding risky ventures until it
is clear which way the economy is headed after Election Day.
   Doug Colitz, a 23-year-old Coast Guard worker in New York, said
Stuart ``must be out of his mind.''
   ``There's a lot less fortunate people in the world than him.
Business comes and goes every day in New York. It's survival of the
fittest. He's a loser, but, heh, he's got some spunk.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP881104-0046 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-11-04-88 0144EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u i AM-Japan-StocksClosing     11-04 0028</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Japan-Stocks Closing,0027</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Nikkei Stocks Down Slightly</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Nikkei Stock Average closed Friday at 27,953.25
points, down 32.01 points, on the Tokyo Stock Exchange.
</TEXT>
