<2ND_LINE>PM-South Africa,0164</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Two Blacks Shot Dead By Police</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PRETORIA, South Africa (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Two black men were shot to death by
police during unrest in a Natal Province township, officials said
today.
   The shootings took place in separate incidents during the night
at Mpumalanga, according to a police statement. It said the shots
were fired to disperse hostile crowds outside homes in the township,
but no details were given about the people involved or the cause of
the disturbance.
   Natal Province has been the site of a prolonged conflict between
members of Inkatha, a relatively conservative Zulu organization, and
supporters of the United Democratic Front, a militant anti-apartheid
coalition. More than 1,000 people have been killed in violence in
Natal the last two years.
   In Durban Supreme Court, 11 men linked to Inkatha went on trial
this week charged with abducting and killing seven youths in March
1987. The assailants allegedly suspected that the youths were United
Democratic Front supporters.
