<DOCNO> AP881104-0057 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-11-04-88 0532EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r p PM-VermontSocialist     11-04 0621</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Vermont Socialist,0637</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Socialist Mayor Wages Strong Campaign for Vermont's Lone House Seat</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MEG DENNISON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MONTPELIER, Vt. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   In his five previous statewide campaigns,
Bernard Sanders has been called spoiler and fringe candidate. Now in
his sixth political campaign, he's sporting a new label: contender.
   The socialist mayor of Vermont's largest city is running as an
independent for the state's lone seat in the U.S. House. He is
campaigning on the theme of shaking up Washington. And polls
indicate voters are buying his message.
   ``We have reached the stage where people are prepared to vote
their conscience, and for me that is a great step forward,'' Sanders
said this week while he held his signs and waved to motorists in
front of an IBM plant.
   His candidacy's strength is showing in campaign financing:
Sanders has raised $224,059, less than the $309,226 raised by
Republican Peter Smith, but more than the $199,577 raised by the
Democratic nominee, House Majority Leader Paul Poirier.
   And his strength is shown by a growing number of hard-line
Democrats who are switching to Sanders. Former Attorney General M.
Jerome Diamond, the 1980 Democratic gubernatorial nominee, said he's
backing Sanders over Poirier.
   ``I'm not willing to throw my vote away,'' said Diamond. ``Paul's
candidacy at this point is not one in which we can give our vote and
expect it not to be lost.''
   An independent poll of likely voters conducted in early October
gave Sanders nearly 25 percent of the vote, behind Smith's 39
percent. Poirier had 17 percent.
   A Sanders' tracking poll early last week showed Sanders closing
the gap on Smith, with undecided voters going to Sanders and Poirier.
   Sanders has worked in Vermont as a carpenter, youth counselor,
free-lance writer and film maker. He produced 25 films on New
England history, two television productions, one on socialist Eugene
V. Debs and one on poverty in Vermont, and several radio programs on
Vermont history.
   In the 1970s, he was a perennial candidate of the Liberty Union,
a leftist party in Vermont. He ran for governor and U.S. Senate, but
garnered few votes.
   In 1976 Sanders quit the party and later began concentrating his
political efforts in Burlington. In 1981 he ran for mayor as an
independent and ousted the longtime Democratic incumbent by 10
votes, an election that shocked the political establishment.
   He proved his election was no fluke by winning re-election in
1983, 1985 and 1987 and gaining national acclaim for his work as
mayor.
   Two years ago Sanders returned to statewide politics, as an
independent, winning 14 percent of the vote in a three-way race for
governor.
   If he won, Sanders would be one of the few socialists in Congress
and the only one to be elected as an independent. Other socialists
who have gone to Congress have been elected on the Republican or
Democratic tickets. The last time a representative won election as a
socialist was in 1929.
   Sanders has campaigned on promises of shaking up Capitol Hill
just as he's has made some waves in Vermont, and he's argued that
he'd be good for Vermont precisely because he has no debts to a
party.
   Though he wins widespread praise for being an effective mayor,
his style is often criticized as too confrontational. But some who
have worked with him call him an adroit politician.
   ``The people who don't deal with him are the people who think
he's an ineffective radical with hot matches stuck between his
toes,'' said Stephen Jeffrey, executive director of a lobbying group
representing most Vermont municipalities.
   ``You're just about to say, `I'm going to fight this guy to the
bitter end,' and you find yourself linking arms with him,'' said
Jeffrey.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
