<1ST_LINE>r i PM-UN-Palestine     11-04 0475</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-UN-Palestine,0493</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>General Assembly Condemns Israeli In Palestinian Violence</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Israel, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PETER JAMES SPIELMANN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>UNITED NATIONS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The General Assembly has overwhelmingly
condemned Israel for beating, wounding, killing and deporting
Palestinans since the uprising began Dec. 8 in the occupied
territories.
   Only the United States and Israel voted Thursday against the
resolution, while 130 nations voted for it. Sixteen abstained,
including Britain and Canada.
   The resolution said the assembly ``condemns Israel's persistent
policies and practices violating the human rights of the Palestinian
people in the occupied territories, including Jerusalem.''
   Every year, the General Assembly overwhelmingly condemns Israeli
human rights practices in the occupied territories.
   U.S. Ambassador Herbert S. Okun, the deputy permanent
representative, said the resolution ``is an unbalanced document,
condemning one of the parties for its actions without taking into
account acts of violence by the other side.
   ``The security of the state of Israel must be assured. At the
same time, the legitimate political rights of the Palestinian people
must be recognized,'' Okun said.
   The resolution criticized Israeli troops and settlers for
shooting and wounding ``defenseless Palestinian civilians, the
beating and breaking of bones, deportation, imposition of
restrictive economic measures, demolition of houses, collective
punishment and detentions, as well as denial of access to the
media.''
   It also ``demands that Israel, the occupying power, abide
immediately and scrupulously'' by the 4th Geneva Convention on
protection of civilians in time of war.
   M. Nasser al-Kidwa, the PLO's deputy U.N. representative, said
that since the uprising began nearly 11 months ago, 411 civilians
were killed through Oct. 30 and 4,500 wounded.
   The toll, he said, includes 273 people who were shot by the army,
37 shot by Israeli settlers, 36 killed in beatings or under
``mysterious conditions'' and 65 by tear gas.
   He charged that 11,400 Palestinians were detained without trial.
   Other estimates place the death toll at 306 Palestinians and 10
Israelis.
   Israeli Ambassador Johanan Bein responded by condemning
Palestinian guerrillas for burning families alive in firebombings,
bombing civilian buses and throwing grenades at sidewalk cafes and
toy shops full of children.
   An annual U.N. report released Thursday said the human rights
situation in Israel's occupied territories has deteriorated
dramatically since the Palestinian uprising began.
   The report said Israel's occupation of the West Bank, Gaza Strip
and Jerusalem since the 1967 Middle East war is itself a violation
of human rights.
   It cited shootings and abuse of civilians, including women and
children, deportation of activists, detention of thousands of
Palestinians under harsh conditions, the bulldozing of houses,
imposition of extended curfews, economic sanctions, restricted
freedom of expression, religion and travel.
   The report said several thousand Palestinians still are detained
and denied a fair trial.
   Israel does not cooperate with the special committee, which bases
its reports on interviews and reports from numerous sources,
including respected Israeli newspapers.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP881104-0059 </DOCNO>
