<2ND_LINE>PM-Weatherpage Weather,0544</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Snow Covers The Rockies</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   A storm packing at least 6 inches of snow and strong winds moved
through the Colorado Rockies today as a tornado downed trees in
Florida and showers and thunderstorms fell over much of the Midwest.
   Winter Park and Echo Lake, Colo., each received 6 inches of new
snow, and an additional 1 to 3 inches was expected.
   An advisory for snow and blowing snow was in effect for the
northern and central mountains of Colorado. Strong winds were
expected to cause blowing, drifing snow in mountain passes.
   A tornado spawned by a strong thunderstorm felled trees, some
onto houses, in a residential neighborhood just south of Fort Myers,
Fla., officials said. There were no reports of injuries, said Lee
County Sheriff's Deputy Alan Bromley.
   Showers and thunderstorms fell from southern Minnesota to
southern Missouri, and showers dampened parts of western Nebraska,
western Kansas and eastern Colorado.
   Scattered showers fell over Illinois, Indiana, eastern Ohio and
western Pennsylvania.
   In southeast Wyoming, a high wind watch was in effect. Winds
gusted Thursday night to 50 mph in Laramie and 49 mph in Cheyenne.
   Scattered light rain fell in lower elevations of Washington state
and in northwest Oregon. A snow advisory was posted for passes in
the Cascades in Washington state over 4,000 feet.
   Today's forecast called for rain from the upper Great Lakes to
the middle Mississippi, lower Ohio and Tennessee valleys; showers
and thunderstorms across the South from the lower Mississippi Valley
to the southern Atlantic Coast; scattered rain from the northern
Plains to the lower Great Lakes and upper Ohio Valley; scattered
showers along the northern Pacific Coast; and sometimes-gusty winds
from the northern and central Rockies to the middle and lower
Missouri Valley.
   High temperatures were predicted to be in the 60s or 70s across
much of the nation; the 50s from the Pacific Northwest to the
northern Rockies, northern Plains, lower Great Lakes and the
northern half of New England; the 40s over the upper Mississippi
Valley and the upper Great Lakes; the 80s acorss central and
southern Florida and from Louisiana to central and western Texas and
the desert Southwest; and the 90s in southern Texas and southwest
Arizona.
   Temperatures around the nation at 2 a.m. EST ranged from 24
degrees at Lebanon, N.H., to 81 degrees at Key West, Fla., Naval Air
Station.
   Other reports:
   _East: Atlanta 51 fair; Boston 40 fair; Buffalo 48 cloudy;
Charleston, S.C. 56 foggy; Cincinnati 58 partly cloudy; Cleveland 55
foggy; Detroit 51 foggy; Miami 73 showery; New York 41 partly
cloudy; Philadelphia 45 fair; Pittsburgh 48 showery; Portland, Maine
32 fair.
   _Central: Bismarck 37 fair; Chicago 56 foggy; Dallas-Fort Worth
65 windy; Denver 44 fair; Des Moines 52 rain; Indianapolis 60
showery; Kansas City 57 cloudy; Minneapolis-St. Paul 43 showery;
Nashville 64 partly cloudy; New Orleans 69 fair; St. Louis 63 foggy.
   _West: Albuquerque 48 fair; Anchorage 19 fair; Las Vegas 62 fair;
Los Angeles 61 foggy; Phoenix 68 fair; Salt Lake City 47 partly
cloudy; San Diego 61 foggy; San Francisco 58 partly cloudy; Seattle
46 fair.
   _Canada: Montreal 30 fair; Toronto 43 foggy.
</TEXT>
