<FILEID>AP-NR-11-04-88 0537EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Israel-Analysis     11-04 0712</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Israel-Analysis,0734</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Israeli Vote: Stalemate on Peace, Prod to Violence</HEAD>
<HEAD>An AP News Analysis</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Israel, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By G.G. LaBELLE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JERUSALEM (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The likelihood Yitzhak Shamir will head a
right-wing government increases the prospect of more confrontation
with Palestinians and promises little real movement in the overall
Arab-Israeli conflict.
   On Thursday, Shamir turned down the most extreme proposals on the
occupied West Bank and Gaza Strip _ expelling Palestinians from the
land and annexing it outright.
   But according to aide Yossi Ahimeir, the prime minister promised
potential partners in a coalition led by his right-wing Likud bloc
that he would build more Jewish settlements in the occupied West
Bank.
   Already, much of the violence in the occupied lands begins with
stoning or firebombing of Israeli cars as Jewish settlers drive from
their enclaves through land whose 1.5 million Arab residents want as
an independent Palestinian nation.
   Often the settlers are armed. The army also responds with gunfire
and by tearing down Palestinian homes when firebombs are thrown.
More than 300 Arabs and 10 Israelis have died in the nearly 11-month
Palestinian uprising.
   Now, more than 70,000 Jews live in about 130 settlements. The
settler movement Gush Emunim, or ``Bloc of the Faithful,'' said
Thursday it hopes to start 11 more this month and build a total of
50 within three years.
   In addition to the potential for violence inherent in more
settlements, Shamir will be under intense pressure to forcefully put
down the ``intefadeh,'' the revolt against Israel's 21-year
occupation.
   Among those he is talking to as coalition partners are far-right
and religious parties, some of which want to expel the Arabs and
take over the West Bank and Gaza Strip as part of biblical Israel.
   They are not likely to be conciliatory toward the Palestinians,
who are themselves angry their uprising brought no political gains.
   Said Kenaan, a pro-PLO West Bank businessman, said Tuesday's vote
showed Israelis don't want peace and added: ``We will hit back. The
moderate voice in the Palestinian camp is finished.''
   Eytan Gilboa, a Hebrew University political science professor,
said an escalated cycle of violence could grow out of Palestinian
anger and pressures on the government to end the uprising.
   ``If the levels of violence go up, if there are more firebombs,
if weapons are used, Israel will respond with fire,'' he said.
   Much of the election campaign focused on the future of the West
Bank and Gaza Strip. The vote was advertised as a crucial choice
between the left-leaning Labor Party's plan to give up land for
peace and Likud's hard-line refusal to do so.
   In the end, the balloting gave a boost to religious parties but
left unanswered the question of what to do with the occupied lands.
Likud and Labor each got only about one-third of the vote.
   Analyst Yosef Goell, writing in the English-language Jerusalem
Post, called the outcome ``a recipe of continued paralysis.'' Shamir
will likely head a right-wing coalition or bring Labor in as a
junior partner.
   His ideas will dominate and they do not promise movement. He has
rejected an international peace conference urged by the Arabs and
endorsed by Foreign Minister Shimon Peres of Labor.
   He refuses to give up occupied land, his mentor Prime Minister
Menachem Begin's way of making peace with Egypt in 1979. He offers
``autonomy'' to the Palestinians under the Camp David accords, with
the future status of the occupied lands to be worked out later.
   Shamir said last week that his election would signal the Arabs
that peace could only be achieved if Egypt, Jordan and moderate
Palestinians join in direct talks with Israel based on the 1978
U.S.-sponsored accords.
   But Hanna Siniora, a Palestinian moderate and editor of the
pro-PLO Al-Fajr newspaper, said the Arabs will reject Shamir's
effort to resuscitate the Camp David peace formula.
   When asked how Palestinians would deal with a Likud-led
government, he replied: ``We will have to cope with a difficult
situation and make these parties abandon the ideas of Camp David,
which are not acceptable to anyone in the Arab world.''
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   EDITOR'S NOTE: G.G. LaBelle is news editor of The Associated
Press bureau in Jerusalem. He covered the Middle East for more than
two years from posts in Beirut and Nicosia.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
