<HEAD>Former Assemblyman Who Worked On King's March On Washington Dies</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Former state Assemblyman Seymour Posner, who
served as public relations director for three marches on Washington
led by the Rev. Martin Luther King Jr., has died of a heart attack.
He was 63.
   Posner died Tuesday at his home in Brooklyn.
   Posner worked on the King marches in 1958, 1959 and 1963 while he
was public relations director for the Urban League.
   He was elected to the state Assembly from the South Bronx in 1965
and served for 13 years.
   From 1984 to this year, he was vice chairman of the state Workers
Compensation Board. At his death, he was legislative director of the
Central Labor Council.
   He is survived by a wife, Ann; a daughter, Naomi, of Brooklyn;
and a sister.
</TEXT>
