<HEAD>Poll Shows Dukakis Comeback in Michigan</HEAD>
<DATELINE>DETROIT (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Michael Dukakis has pulled within 4 percentage
points of George Bush in Michigan, according to a poll in today's
editions of The Detroit News.
   The News poll of 1,021 registered voters gave Bush a 48 percent
to 44 percent edge over Dukakis. The survey was conducted Monday
through Wednesday for The News by Gordon S. Black Corp. and has an
error margin of plus or minus 3 percentage points.
   ``This state is up for grabs. This weekend will determine who
wins Michigan,'' said Anthony M. Casale, a spokesman for the
Washington-based Gordon S. Black.
   Both candidates are scheduled to campaign in Michigan the next
few days. Bush was to appear at Schoolcraft College in Livonia
today, while Dukakis is to appear in Taylor on Saturday.
   President Reagan will campaign on Bush's behalf on Saturday at
Macomb Community College south campus in Warren.
   In mid-October Bush held a substantial lead over Dukakis in most
Michigan polls, but Dukakis has apparently been able to erase most
of that advantage.
</TEXT>
