<1ST_LINE>r a PM-SRPPlutonium     11-04 0241</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-SRP Plutonium,0249</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>1,400 Workers Checked For Plutonium Contamination</HEAD>
<DATELINE>AIKEN, S.C. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Savannah River Plant officials checked 1,400
workers for contamination after discovering that three more workers
had inadvertently come into contact with radioactive material.
   All 1,400 came up clean Thursday, said Becky Apter, a spokeswoman
for Du Pont, which runs the nuclear weaponry fuel plant here for the
U.S. Department of Energy.
   Wednesday's discovery brings to 17 the number of workers who have
come into contact with plutonium in an outside area near the plant's
chemical separations facility. Contamination was found on the shoes
of the first 14.
   On Wednesday, three construction workers discovered a ``very low
level'' of plutonium on their hands as they left one of the chemical
separations buildings, said Bill Reinig, Du Pont health protection
superintendent.
   He said officials still do not know the source of the plutonium
contamination. The plant is the nation's sole producer of
weapons-grade plutonium and tritium.
   Reinig said monitors show none of the contamination was carried
off the plant site.
   Since April, all three of the plant's reactors have been closed
for maintenance amid safety questions.
   Concerns about safety increased dramatically in early October,
when it was disclosed that a number of near-accidents and releases
of radioactive materials at the plant over the last three decades
were not reported to Energy Department headquarters or to the public.
   Plant and government officials say they are working to correct
the problems.
</TEXT>
