<1ST_LINE>r i PM-SAfrica-Newspaper     11-04 0371</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-SAfrica-Newspaper,0384</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>New Afrikaans Newspaper Is Launched, Predicts Mandela Release</HEAD>
<DATELINE>JOHANNESBURG, South Africa (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A new Afrikaans-language weekly
newspaper went on sale today, with a front-page story predicting
African National Congress leader Nelson Mandela will soon be freed.
   Called Free Weekly, the newspaper describes itself as politically
independent and gave extensive coverage in its premier issue to
controversial political topics.
   On its front page, in addition to a story speculating Mandela
might be freed Nov. 14, it carried a photograph of two liberal
Afrikaners at a recent meeting in West Germany with leaders of the
outlawed African National Congress.
   The ANC is fighting the white-led government and its policies of
apartheid, or racial segregation.
   The two Afrikaners flanked Joe Slovo, an ANC executive committee
member who is head of the outlawed South African Communist Party and
is depicted by South African government officials as a terrorist.
   South Africa's daily Afrikaans newspapers generally support the
government, although Beeld _ the largest-circulation Afrikaans daily
_ has differed with President P.W. Botha on several issues in recent
months.
   Botha's National Party is dominated by Afrikaners, the mainly
Dutch-descended whites whose forebears arrived in South Africa
beginning in 1652 and who now make up 60 percent of the 5-million
white minority.
   The majority 26 million blacks in South Africa have no vote in
national affairs and are separated from whites by housing, schools
and health services.
   Free Weekly said, without attribution, that Nov. 14 was a
possible date for release of Mandela, 70, has been imprisoned since
1962 and is serving a life sentence for plotting sabotage to
overthrow white-minority rule.
   Mandela is considered the most popular leader among the black
majority and there has been a worldwide campaign seeking his release.
   The newspaper also suggested Mandela might be freed in
conjunction with possible visits to South Africa by British Prime
Minister Margaret Thatcher or President Mobutu Sese Seko of Zaire.
   Mandela was stricken with tuberculosis in August and is
recuperating at a private clinic in Cape Town. Botha has said he
would prefer Mandela not be returned to Pollsmoor Prison.
   Mandela is the past has turned down offers to go free in exchange
for renouncing the use of violence by ANC guerrillas.
</TEXT>
