<2ND_LINE>PM-ZZZZ Best,0286</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Minkow Testifies That He Tried to Commit Suicide in Prison</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LINDA DEUTSCH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A fallen whiz kid testified that he tried to
hang himself in prison after he became despondent over demands
placed on him by organized crime figures.
   Barry Minkow, on trial in U.S. District Court on 57 counts of
securities, credit card and mail fraud stemming from the failure of
his ZZZZ Best carpet-cleaning firm, disclosed his suicide attempt
Thursday during cross-examination.
   The prosecutor later dismissed Minkow's claim as a fabrication.
``It's the first anybody's heard about it,'' Assistant U.S. Attorney
James Asperger said.
   Defense attorney David Kenner, when told the prosecutor had
suggested Minkow had invented the suicide attempt, said he had heard
about it.
   Minkow, 22, was totally distraught, Kenner said, adding, ``My
understanding was he decided to just end it all.''
   He was 16 when he started the company in his parents' garage and
21 when it collapsed. Major banks and private investors lost at
least $25 million invested in the firm, according to the government.
   Minkow has argued that he was forced to swindle investors out of
millions by mobsters who took control of his company.
   He admitted to many lies under Asperger's cross-examination, and
at one point, U.S. District Judge Dickran Tevrizian asked: ``When
did you start lying?''
   ``In 1983,'' said Minkow.
   ``When did you stop lying?'' asked the judge.
   ``At Terminal Island (prison) after I tried to hang myself,'' he
said.
   Minkow added that afterward his attorney, Kenner, ``told me
either face this or you go to jail for 500 years _ that's when I
stopped lying.''
</TEXT>
