<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Poland-BritainMemorial     11-04 0301</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Poland-Britain Memorial,0308</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Thatcher Unveils Memorial To WWII British Airmen</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Poland, Bjt</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WARSAW, Poland (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   British Prime Minister Margaret Thatcher
unveiled a memorial today to a British plane crew shot down in 1944
while trying to aid the Polish resistance. The only survivor of the
crash, 65-year-old LLoyd Lane, looked on.
   Mrs. Thatcher, on the final day of her three-day visit to Poland,
cut a ribbon encircling a rough stone memorial with a bronze plaque
erected on the spot where six Royal Air Force crew members died.
   The British prime minister then laid a wreath at the base of the
statue and talked with British and Polish veterans attending the
brief ceremony in a park in the city's eastern Praga district.
   Lane, now a farmer in Cornwall, southwest England, earlier
described how the Liberator bomber was hit by German anti-aircraft
fire as it flew low on an August night.
   ``We were taking supplies from Italy to the Polish Home Army, who
were rising against the Germans and were short of ammunition, guns,
medical equipment and food,'' said Lane, accompanied to the ceremony
by his wife Trevis.
   ``We ran into heavy anti-aircraft fire and were hit at about 400
feet,'' he said. ``I woke up about four hours later. Amazingly, I
had no broken bones, just burns to my face and knees.''
   He said, ``I was either blown out, thrown out or fell out of the
gun apertures either when the aircraft crashed or when it was in the
air. I had no parachute and I shall never know what happened.''
   He called for help and was captured by the Germans, who
eventually took him to a prisoner-of-war camp.
   After the memorial ceremony, Mrs. Thatcher left for Gdansk to
meet Lech Walesa, leader of the banned Solidarity trade union.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP881104-0072 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-11-04-88 0615EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a PM-Seniors'Vaccines     11-04 0563</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Seniors' Vaccines,0578</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Seniors Mistrust, Avoid Flu, Pneumonia Vaccines, Study Says</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ROBERT BYRD</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ATLANTA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Many elderly people who are fearful of adverse
effects from flu vaccine or skeptical of its effectiveness don't get
recommended annual flu shots, which could save thousands of lives,
according to a government report.
   About 60,000 deaths are reported from flu and pneumonia in the
United States each year, mostly among people 65 and over, the
national Centers for Disease Control said Thursday.
   ``Although safe, effective and inexpensive vaccines are available
for these diseases, only about 22 percent (of people 65 and up
nationwide) receive influenza vaccine annually,'' the CDC said.
   For pneumococcal vaccine, designed to prevent pneumonia and its
complications, the numbers are even lower: only 10 percent have ever
received the one-time-only shot.
   Influenza and pneumococcal vaccines are recommended by federal
health officials for all persons 65 and over, because of seniors'
increased risk of complications or death from pneumonia and flu.
   One study conducted this summer in metropolitan Atlanta indicated
the reason for low vaccine use among seniors may be mistrust of the
vaccines, not ignorance.
   Among 716 senior citizens surveyed in Fulton and DeKalb counties,
90 percent were aware of flu vaccine and 53 percent were aware of
pneumococcal vaccine. But only 55 percent received annual flu shots,
and only 38 percent had received pneumococcal vaccine.
   ``Many individuals may refuse the vaccines over concerns over
adverse effects,'' said Dr. Walter W. Williams, a CDC immunization
specialist. ``If there's one thing that may influence someone to
take or not take a vaccine, it's fear of side effects.''
   Seventy-three percent of the senior citizens in the Atlanta
survey who were aware of influenza vaccine reported ``negative
attitudes'' about it _ usually the feeling that it causes illness,
doesn't work, or isn't necessary, the CDC said.
   ``A lot of those fears are unfounded,'' Williams said, adding
that today's flu vaccines are much safer than vaccines of a
generation or two ago.
   The negative attitudes remained even among those getting flu
shots; half of those with such attitudes reported they'd had their
flu shots anyway.
   In the Atlanta survey, doctors' recommendations appeared to carry
a lot of weight with the older patients. Seventy-five percent of
those to whom a health-care provider had recommended flu vaccine
reported getting their annual shot, compared to just 7 percent of
those who had not received such a recommendation. For pneumococcal
vaccine, the percentages were similar: 76 percent and 6 percent, the
CDC said.
   ``It's very, very important for health care providers to ...
discuss those issues with patients,'' Williams said.
   While the Atlanta results cannot be projected for the nation as a
whole, they are of importance to researchers because ``they are
similar to other findings'' from more comprehensive studies,
Williams said.
   Flu kills about 20,000 Americans each year, while another 40,000
deaths result from pneumonia; more than 80 percent of those deaths
occur in people over 65, according to the CDC.
   In younger adults, flu vaccine is as much as 90 percent effective
in preventing flu entirely, Williams said. Absolute effectiveness is
lower in older persons _ between 40 and 60 percent _ but the
effectiveness in preventing serious complications and death remains
around 75 percent, he said.
   Pneumococcal vaccine is believed to be between 60 and 95 percent
effective in preventing pneumonia, Williams said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP881104-0073 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-11-04-88 0625EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a PM-Steinberg     11-04 0629</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Steinberg,0646</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Injuries to Steinberg's Companion Shock Jurors in Child-Killer Case</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SAMUEL MAULL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Jurors in the trial of a man accused of killing
an illegally adopted child watched in horror as a videotape showed
extensive bruises, lacerations and other injuries suffered by his
live-in companion.
   Some jurors put their hands to their faces and others turned
their heads Thursday as the 5{-minute tape revealed Hedda Nussbaum's
bruises, open wounds, patches of missing hair and a discolored left
leg.
   The tape, shot at a police station by a technician from the
Manhattan district attorney's office, showed the 46-year-old woman a
short time after she and Joel Steinberg were arrested Nov. 2, 1987,
in connection with the death of their illegally adopted daughter,
6-year-old Lisa Steinberg.
   The tape was used to buttress testimony of police officers,
paramedics and social workers that on the morning the child was
taken unconscious from the Steinberg household, Ms. Nussbaum
appeared battered and bruised, passive and lethargic.
   Prosecutors believe the videotape would show jurors the allegedly
violent conditions in the household and explain why Ms. Nussbaum did
not call for help for at least 10 hours after Lisa fell unconscious.
   ``Steinberg totally dominated Ms. Nussbaum both physically and
psychologically,'' said Assistant District Attorney John McCusker,
one of the prosecutors.
   But Steinberg's lawyer, Ira London, objected to the tape, calling
it ``inflammatory and prejudicial.'' London said there was no proven
connection between his client and Ms. Nussbaum's injuries, and even
if there were, it would be irrelevant to the murder trial.
   ``I don't see how this (tape) can come in (as evidence), since
there is no evidence that physical abuse had anything to do with her
(Ms. Nussbaum's) behavior,'' he said.
   Ms. Nussbaum has never said she failed to call for help for the
child because she feared Steinberg's retribution, he said. ``It was
her mistaken belief that Joel had powers to heal Lisa,'' London said.
   The color videotape showed Ms. Nussbaum raising her black
turtleneck sweater and pulling down her jeans while a female police
officer pointed with a ruler to show the size and location of
bruises and open wounds.
   When Ms. Nussbaum held her head forward, the tape revealed
patches of hair were missing from her scalp. Her right eye was
blackened; she had an open wound over the bridge of an apparently
broken nose; her lips were swollen and one was split; and she had
other injuries on her torso.
   Her buttocks were bruised, her left thigh was almost totally
discolored, and her left leg had open wounds and discoloration. Ms.
Nussbaum's right leg was ulcerated from the knee down to the ankle,
with bandages in various places.
   Charges against Ms. Nussbaum, Steinberg's live-in companion for
12 years, were dropped two weeks ago. She is expected to testify for
the prosecution about alleged violence that led to the fatal
injuries of the child.
   Lisa was taken to nearby St. Vincent's Hospital on the morning of
Nov. 2, 1987 and died three days later of a head injury.
   A 16-month-old boy, Mitchell, was found in the apartment sitting
in a dirty diaper and tethered to a playpen, authortities said. He
also was illegally adopted and now lives with his biological mother.
   Steinberg, 47, a disbarred lawyer, is on trial for second-degree
murder. He denies that he hit the child. He said she choked on
vomited food and the bruises on her chest and back resulted from his
trying to revive her. He is jailed without bail.
   Ms. Nussbaum, a former children's book editor, has had several
operations for injuries her lawyer, Barry Scheck, said she suffered
at Steinberg's hands. She also has been under psychiatric care for
nearly a year at a Westchester County facility.
</TEXT>
