<DOCNO> AP881104-0075 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-11-04-88 0640EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a PM-RhinocerosSmugglers     11-04 0531</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Rhinoceros Smugglers,0545</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Six Charged In Scheme To Smuggle Rhinceros Horns</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DEAN GOLEMBESKI</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>HARTFORD, Conn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Two South African army officers were among
six people indicted on charges that they smuggled precious
rhinoceros horns, skins of other endangered animals and AK-47
machine guns into the United States.
   The six were caught in an undercover investigation that began in
February, U.S. Attorney Stanley A. Twardy Jr. said Thursday. More
arrests are possible, he added.
   Twardy said he had no idea how long the smugglers had been in
business, nor was he able to say how many others did business with
the group. But those charged in the scheme indicated they had enough
rhino horns to earn hundreds of thousands of dollars.
   ``This is something that is unique, at least in my experience,
and from what I have been unable to uncover from the (Justice)
Department,'' Twardy said.
   The rhino horns are valued by some Orientals for their purported
medicinal and aphrodisiac properties. In the United States, rhino
horn powder can sell for up to $450 an ounce, Twardy said.
   Arrested were John C. Lukman Jr., 34, and Russell D. Beveridge
Jr., 32, both of Newington; and Mary Ann McAllister, 33, of West
Hartford, Twardy said.
   Also named in the complaint were Marius Meiring, a major in the
South African Defense Force; his wife, Pat Meiring; and Waldemar
Schutte, a South African sergeant major, Twardy said. All are South
African citizens and U.S. officials were seeking to have the three
extradited to the United States, Twardy said.
   The importation of rhino horn is illegal in most countries,
including the United States, because the animal is nearly extinct.
   Still, an illicit trade reportedly worth $3 million a year
flourishes in the Middle East and eastern Asia, where dealers pay
$450 a pound for it.
   Rhino horn is not actually a horn, but densely compacted fibers
of keratin, a protein found in hair and fingernails. In the Far
East, it is ground into traditional medicines that supposedly reduce
fever and stop nosebleeds. It is also treasured in Yemen, where it
is carved into dagger handles that sell for up to $15,000 each.
   Rhinoceroses are one of the more endangered animals in the world.
At one time 120 species lived, but only five species remain,
including black and white rhinos. Fewer than 4,000 black rhinos
remain today; about 85 percent of them live in South Africa, Nambia,
Zimbabwe and Kenya.
   A. Eugene Hester, the northeast regional director of the U.S.
Fish & Wildlife Service, said the seizure and purchase of the rhino
horns by undercover agents was the largest haul of its kind in the
United States.
   Each defendant was charged with conspriracy to commit an offense
against the United States, a crime that can be punished by up to
five years in prison and a $250,000 fine. Twardy said other charges
would be filed.
   Lukman, McAllister and Beveridge appeared Thursday in U.S.
District Court in Hartford, where McAllister and Beveridge each were
released on $25,000 non-surety bonds.
   Lukman's case was to continue today. Twardy said authorities want
Lukman held without bail because they think he might leave the
country.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP881104-0076 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-11-04-88 0645EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a PM-Lites SUB a0517 11-04 0250</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Lites, SUB, a0517,0255</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>On The Light Side</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: SUBS 3rd graf of 2nd item to fix transposed words</NOTE>
<DATELINE>PITTSBURGH (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   It's 10 p.m. _ do you know where your inmates
are?
   That's how Allegheny County officials discovered there's a slight
loophole in their house arrest system, which uses electronic
bracelets to monitor inmates: No one is keeping tabs on prisoners
after 10 p.m.
   As a result, probation authorities said, they didn't know that
inmate Donald E. Knudson Jr. left his suburban Bethel Park home
without permission at 11:56 p.m. Friday, leading police on a
two-hour car chase.
   The special electronic bracelet Knudson was wearing properly
notified authorities that he had left his home, but no one was
watching the monitoring equipment, said John Kolesar, director of
the Allegheny County Adult Probation Office.
   ``I have six staff, and we don't have enough people to have
someone in the office after 10 p.m.,'' he said.
   Inmates assigned to house arrest wear bracelets on their ankles
or wrists that send signals through a special telephone receiver in
their homes. If they leave the range of the receiver, a signal
notifies a computer in the county probation office.
   Kolesar said he needs two more staff members, at a cost of about
$50,000, to monitor house-arrest prisoners 24 hours a day.
   But he said the Pennsylvania Commission on Crime and Deliquency
will not approve additional staff members under its grant to start
the program and the county has refused to hire them.
</TEXT>
