<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Britain-Maldives     11-04 0186</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Britain-Maldives,0191</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Commonwealth Leader Wants U.N. Protection For Small Nations</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Maldives</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The United Nations should devise an emergency
system to protect small nations such as the Maldives from invasion
by foreign troops, mercenaries or terrorists, Commonwealth
Secretary-General Sir Sridath Ramphal says.
   ``If they can get away with it in the Maldives, no small state in
the Pacific, in the Caribbean, (or) in the Indian Ocean is safe from
this kind of mercenary insurgency and incursion,'' Ramphal said
Thursday in a television interview.
   Ramphal is the top official of the 48-nation commonwealth of
Britain and its former colonies.
   The British government said the Maldivian government's request
Thursday for military assistance to help fight off a coup attempt by
foreign mercenaries had been overtaken by India's decision to rush
in troops.
   At least 12 people were reported killed in battles between the
gunmen and loyalist troops.
   About 500 Britons were believed to be vacationing on the tropical
Indian Ocean archipelago, but there were no reports of British
casualties, the spokesman said. The islands were under the
protection of the British crown until 1952.
