<HEAD>Former Police Officer Convicted In Contract Killing</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A former police officer was convicted of
first-degree murder in the contract killing of a businessman whose
body is still missing.
   Robert Von Villas, 44, of Simi Valley also was found guilty
Thursday of conspiracy to murder. His murder conviction carries
special allegations for which he could face the gas chamber.
   Von Villas was convicted of the death of Thomas Weed, 52, of
Northridge, who disappeared from his San Fernando Valley apartment
Feb. 23, 1983.
   Von Villas and co-defendant Richard Herman Ford, 48, also a
former police officer, were accused of taking $20,000 from Weed's
ex-wife, Janie Ogilvie, to kill Weed.
   Ford was convicted of Weed's murder on Oct. 11. The penalty phase
of his trial begins Monday. The penalty phase of Von Villas' trial
is scheduled to begin Nov. 28.
   Ms. Ogilvie pleaded guilty to second-degree murder and is serving
a 15-year-to-life sentence.
   Ms. Ogilvie, who said Weed beat her, testified she hired the
former policemen to kill her husband and that they told her no one
would ever find the body. It is believed to be buried in the Mojave
Desert.
   Defense attorneys called Ms. Ogilvie ``crazy'' and said she was
trying to escape the death penalty in testifying against the former
officers. They also said prosecutors failed to prove Weed was killed.
   In January, Von Villas and Ford were convicted of attempting to
murder a nude dancer in order to collect $100,000 in life insurance.
They also were found guilty of staging a $210,000 jewelry heist in
1982.
</TEXT>
