<1ST_LINE>r a PM-EasternCocaine     11-04 0236</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Eastern Cocaine,0241</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Customs Fines Eastern, But Doesn't Seize Plane</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MIAMI (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Eastern Airlines says it will contest a $1 million
fine imposed after federal agents found cocaine aboard one of its
jets for the second time in as many weeks.
   ``We have one of the most comprehensive programs in the industry
to intercept drugs,'' said spokeswoman Karen Ceremsak. ``We spend
three and a half million dollars a year.''
   The Customs Service on Monday found 68 pounds of cocaine aboard a
flight from Colombia hidden in a box of ground coffee in the baggage
compartment. On Thursday, the agency fined the airline but did not
impound the Boeing 727.
   ``Customs, at the present time, is not seizing the 727, since
Eastern appears to be making serious efforts to improve its security
measures against drug smuggling,'' said Customs spokesman Cliff
Stallings.
   Last week, Customs seized an Eastern L-1011 and fined the airline
$896,000 after finding 56 pounds of cocaine in a mail bag. Eastern
protested the seizure of the plane, saying its tip led to the
discovery of the drugs, but Customs denied that.
   The plane was released after Eastern posted bond for the value of
the fine.
   Ms. Ceremsak said that despite the recent seizures, Eastern has
no plans to discontinue service to Latin America and the Caribbean.
The Colombian national airline, Avianca, ended all cargo flights
after repeated drug seizures on its planes.
</TEXT>
