<FILEID>AP-NR-11-04-88 0831EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r p PM-Democrats-Texas 1stLd-Writethru a0457 11-04 0836</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Democrats-Texas, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0457,800</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Texas Democrats Hope for Repeat of Kennedy-Johnson Feat</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: SUBS 4th graf, Kennedy and, to CORRECT vote margin to 46,000,
not 30,000</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By STEVEN KOMAROW</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>DALLAS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Kennedy-Johnson bumper stickers have surfaced
after 28 years of dormancy as Democrats hope for a miracle on
Election Day similar to the one that gave them the White House in
1960.
   ``I hope we're not all fooling ourselves,'' said George
Christian, an Austin consultant who served as Lyndon Johnson's press
secretary.
   Fragments of statistics and a nostalgic history of unexpected
election outcomes keep Democratic hopes alive that vice presidential
candidate Lloyd Bentsen can deliver its 29 electoral votes for
running mate Michael Dukakis.
   Kennedy and Johnson won the state by only 46,000 votes, and in
1982, Democrat Mark White won the governorship over Republican Bill
Clements by six percentage points even though he was trailing in the
polls by the same margin the day before the election.
   ``I think we're gonna do it,'' says Bob Slagle, the Texas state
Democratic chairman.
   ``I think it's going to be a squeaker, very close, but we're
going to win it,'' insists Bentsen.
   Dukakis picked Bentsen as his running mate in hopes of repeating
the Kennedy-Johnson feat of 1960. But the immensely popular man from
McCook, Texas, has had trouble transferring some of his popularity
to the Massachusetts governor.
   Going into the final weekend of the campaign, the closest recent
poll puts the ticket seven points behind Republicans George Bush and
Dan Quayle, while others show a margin of more than 20 points.
   Democrats, who have never won the White House without winning
Texas, cling to the lowest number. They believe a strong
get-out-the-vote program can make up the difference, and cite
Bentsen's strong political organization in the state.
   ``This election isn't going to be won or lost now by Michael
Dukakis or Lloyd Bentsen. It's all in the turnout,'' said Ann
Richards, the Texas state treasurer.
   Tom Cosgrove, the Dukakis-Bentsen campaign chief in Texas, even
suggests that the opening of hunting season last weekend may help
the Democrats because some of the gun owners who oppose Dukakis may
be out hunting on Election Day.
   ``When you were looking at 15 points down, even nine or seven is
a big improvement,'' said Christian, who has been advising Bentsen
on the campaign.
   The dismal position of the Democratic campaign in Texas is a
reflection of the problems Dukakis has had nationwide.
   As elsewhere, Democrats had high hopes after their convention in
July of carrying Texas and bringing home the state's conservative
Democrats who helped give Ronald Reagan 64 percent of the vote in
1984.
   Early polls were encouraging, and the party dealt with peripheral
issues, such as Bentsen's dual candidacies for the U.S. Senate and
the vice presidency. He says he'll resign the former if he wins the
latter.
   The dual candidaciesvoters chosing to cast their
ballots twice for Texas with Bush, a former Houston congressman, and
Bentsen.
   ``I think it probably helped him in the vice presidential race,''
said Dick Leggitt, a Washington political consultant working for
Beau Boulter, Bentsen's Senate opponent.
   Dukakis then put non-Texan Cosgrove in charge, alienating many
locals.
   Soon after, Texas Democrats watched helplessly as the issues
picked by Bush for his broadsides against Dukakis _ flag-factory
patriotism, gun control and crime _ hit at the heart of the rural
Texas voters the Democrats wanted to win back.
   The charges went unanswered for many weeks. Too long, the
candidates now concede.
   Both Bentsen and Dukakis spent precious time in Texas, with the
senator spending about 40 days in the state since the convention.
   The campaign got a lift after Bentsen's debate with Quayle.
Grumbling among state Democrats, who had been getting more vocal in
criticizing the Boston-run Dukakis campaign, was replaced by a new
spirit of cooperation.
   But Dukakis' second debate with George Bush a week later was a
downer in Texas, as elsewere.
   The campaign in mid-October launched a full-scale ad campaign to
counter the Republicans, with Bentsen and Dukakis hammering Bush for
conducting a negative campaign. Heartened again, the Texas Democrats
seemed to pick up some vigor.
   But the Bush campaign continued its ads, and the issues lingered,
especially gun control, in which the Bush campaign had allies such
as the National Rifle Association to spread the word against Dukakis.
   And, with just more than a week left in the contest, Dukakis
acknowledged he was indeed a liberal and the Texas Democrats were on
the defensive again.
   ``It's not the best word in the world,'' said Slagle, who
insisted it wasn't that bad in the context of Harry Truman and John
Kennedy that Dukakis used it.
   But the Republicans were gleeful again.
   ``I don't know what his handlers were thinking,'' said Reggie
Basher, the Bush-Quayle campaign spokesman in Texas.
</TEXT>
