<1ST_LINE>r a PM-ShuttleAstronauts     11-04 0300</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Shuttle Astronauts,0311</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Shuttle Astronauts Don Lone Ranger Masks In Talking About
Classified Flight</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LAURA TOLLEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SPACE CENTER, Houston (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The five Atlantis astronauts poked a
little fun at the secrecy surrounding their upcoming classified
shuttle mission by donning Lone Ranger-style masks for reporters.
   ``We're probably going to get in all kinds of trouble for this,''
the mission commander, Robert ``Hoot'' Gibson, said with a laugh
Thursday.
   Atlantis, which sits on a launch pad at the Kennedy Space Center
in Cape Canaveral, Fla., is scheduled for liftoff late this month on
a mission during which it will send a spy satellite into orbit.
   On regular shuttle flights, the crews usually hold a news
conference and give individual interviews about a month before the
launch date.
   Details about the upcoming mission, however, are classified and
the exact launch time won't be given until nine minutes before
liftoff. The crew members also aren't allowed to discuss their
duties on the mission and were not giving interviews.
   But there were many interview requests for the second
post-Challenger mission, so the Air Force agreed to let the five
astronauts meet briefly with several reporters Thursday _ as long as
they said nothing about their mission.
   When they arrived, the five wore big smiles and black masks. NASA
employees at the Johnson Space Center's public information office
laughed and applauded their masked arrival.
   The masks, mission specialist William Shepherd said, were
included in a press kit given to the astronauts.
   Gibson added that the crew also received flash cards with joke
answers, including: ``Yes. No. I don't know. I can't tell you. I can
tell you, but I'd have to kill you.''
   The other Atlantis crewmen are pilot Guy Gardner and mission
specialists Richard ``Mike'' Mullane and Jerry Ross.
</TEXT>
