<FILEID>AP-NR-11-04-88 0856EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u p PM-Quayle-Abortion     11-04 0534</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Quayle-Abortion,0553</2ND_LINE>
<BYLINE>Quayle's `Abortion Alternative' Medically Shaky, Experts Say
^By MALCOLM RITTER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Science Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Dan Quayle's assertion that a surgical procedure
done immediately after a rape can prevent conception is probably
wrong, experts say.
   The procedure is called dilation and curettage, or D-and-C. It
involves scraping of the lining of the uterus. The procedure has a
variety of medical uses.
   The procedure, which Quayle described as an alternative to
abortion, may stop early development of an embryo, scientists said
Thursday, but conception itself can occur in less than an hour after
intercourse.
   Moreover, said Ruth Schwartz, a member of the health care
commission of the American College of Obstetricians and
Gynecologists, a D-and-C is done in the uterus, while conception
occurs in the Fallopian tubes.
   ``It is not preventing a pregnancy from happening,'' Schwartz
said.
   Development of the embryo in rape victims is blocked through the
use of medications, which are preferable to the surgery, the experts
said.
   Doing the surgical procedure right after rape would be ``adding
great insult and injury on an already severely traumatized woman,''
Schwartz said. ``I think it would be a ridiculous notion to do as a
routine basis,'' she said.
   Surgical abortion removes an embryo after it has implanted itself
in the uterus wall, an event that occurs about a week after
conception. D-and-C can be used for first-trimester abortions,
although a suction procedure is more common.
   Quayle, who opposes abortion, brought up D-and-C when asked
Wednesday about abortion in the case of a rape.
   ``My position is that I understand from a medical situation that,
immediately after a rape, that is reported, that a woman normally,
in fact, can go to the hospital and have a D-and-C at that time,
that is before the actual forming of a life,'' he said.
   ``I understand that the medical procedure, a normal D-and-C,
right after rape, that you would not even get into a conception and
life would not even be formed,'' he said.
   W. LeRoy Heinrichs, professor of obstetrics and gynecology at the
Stanford University Medical Center, said he knew of no evidence that
an immediate D-and-C would prevent conception.
   Perhaps there could be some effect on conception because of
anesthetic in the blood, or blood or other fluids pushed into the
Fallopian tubes, he suggested. But the whole idea is probably
incorrect, he said.
   Sperm reach the Fallopian tubes within minutes of intercourse and
can fertilize the egg in less than an hour if the woman has already
ovulated, Heinrichs said. Sperm can remain viable for 48 hours, so
they can also fertilize an egg if ovulation occurs within that
period after intercourse, he said.
   An immediate D-and-C would probably stop later embryonic
development by making the uterus wall resist implantation by the
embryo, Heinrichs said, adding he knows of no evidence for that idea.
   But women who have just been raped are generally given drugs
rather than surgery to block that implantation, Schwartz and
Heinrichs said. A D-and-C would be ``heavy-handed'' and probably not
work as well as the drugs, Heinrichs said.
   If a D-and-C done after implantation removes the embryo, it
amounts to a standard abortion, Schwartz and Heinrichs said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
