11-04 0584</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Algeria-Referendum, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0535,0600</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Algerians Approve Constitutional Changes</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Leads with 4 grafs to RAISE reference to anti-government
riots. Pickup 4th graf pvs, ``The referendum...''</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By SYDNEY RUBIN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ALGIERS, Algeria (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The government said today that more than
90 percent of the nation's voters approved constitutional changes
designed to shift power away from the single political party that
has ruled for 26 years.
   The referendum was held Thursday, one month after anti-government
riots shook Algeria to its foundation.
   ``The Algerian people have chosen the road to reform,'' Interior
Minister Hedi Khediri said while announcing the results. ``The
Algerian people are as attached to freedom as to the building of
their country _ in unity.''
   The ministry said 92.27 percent of those voting in the referendum
said ``yes'' to changes promised by President Chadli Bendjedid.
   The referendum shifted some power from the president to the
premier. It also made the premier responsible to the National
Assembly, or parliament, so daily governmental operations could be
removed from direct control of the National Liberation Front, the
only legal party.
   Bendjedid has suggested independent candidates be allowed to run
for seats in the National Assembly. Until now the Front had to
approve all candidates.
   Kamel Belkacem, publisher of the pro-reform weekly newspaper
Algerie Actualite, said Bendjedid's ultimate goal is to open the
country to free, multiparty elections.
   The large vote in support of Bendjedid's reforms gives him a
strong mandate to push through other changes he hopes to make when
the party holds its congress at the end of the month.
   The front led the fight against French colonial rule. Since
independence in 1962, it has controlled the country's political,
economic, social, cultural and judicial life.
   About 26 million people live in Algeria, a country roughly three
times the size of Texas.
   The Interior Ministry said 83.08 percent of the country's 12
million voters cast ballots. The ministry said 9.3 million voted in
favor of the proposals to modify 14 articles of the constitution.
   The president was expected to appoint a new government in the
next 10 days, according to Western diplomats and Algerian sources
close to the government, who spoke on condition of anonymity.
   The sources said the composition of the next government will be a
test of the president's sincerity in initiating genuine reforms.
   ``They are having trouble finding people with experience to serve
as ministers who are not contaminated by association with previous
governments,'' one diplomat said.
   Algerians took to the streets Oct. 4 to protest shortages of food
and jobs and a declining standard of living, blamed on the
plummeting price of oil, Algeria's chief source of export earnings.
   The Interior Ministry says 176 people, mostly young men, were
killed in the six days of violence that rocked Algiers and a number
of provincial towns.
   The first task of the new government will be to deal with the
crisis that spawned the riots, instituting reforms expected to
include decentralizing control of the economy and privatizing most
non-strategic industries, diplomatic sources said.
   Khediri said the nation's ``economic problems can be attacked by
a program of austerity.'' Austerity measures taken earlier by the
government inspired the October riots.
   Algeria has a $20 billion foreign debt. Revenue from oil exports
has fallen 40 percent since 1981.
   The naming of the new government will be followed by a party
congress Nov. 27 which will consider a series of further reforms
that could redefine the party's role, Algerian and Western
diplomatic sources said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP881104-0088 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-11-04-88 0909EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a PM-MiamiHomeless     11-04 0285</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Miami Homeless,0293</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>City Commission Rejects Arrest For Sidewalk Sleepers</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MIAMI (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   City commissioners have rejected a proposal allowing
police to arrest homeless people, jail them for 10 days and fine
them up to $100.
   ``We're catching hell for it,'' Commissioner J.L. Plummer said of
the proposal, which was unanimously rejected Thursday but will be
reconsidered Dec. 15. ``We have existing laws that can be enforced.''
   The ordinance, aimed at curbing the annual influx of homeless
from Northern cities, would have banned sleeping on sidewalks and
cooking and urinating in streets and parks.
   After rejecting the measure, the five commissioners requested a
less harsh revision and promised to appoint a task force to help
street people. The revision should not call for the arrest of
homeless people, officials said.
   ``That's out,'' Mayor Xavier Suarez said. ``It actually can be
viewed as an attempt to harass the homeless.''
   The proposed ordinance had caused an uproar among advocates for
the homeless. Critics said the city was trying to clean up the
streets near the Miami Arena before the city's new NBA team debuts
there Saturday.
   The Arena is a few blocks from the city's overflowing shelter for
the homeless, whose director, Brother Paul Johnson, applauded the
commission decision.
   ``I think the idea that Miami could stop homelessness by a law
that arrests them is ridiculous,'' Johnson said. ``I think everyone
realized this morning that that cannot be done.''
   The ordinance was proposed by the Police Department. Police said
it was prompted by complaints from businessmen.
   Suarez said that despite its rejection, the ordinance had a
beneficial effect. ``The reaction to it has actually helped the
commission look at the problem of the homeless,'' he said.
</TEXT>
