<2ND_LINE>PM-Economy Rdp, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0501,0492</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Retail, Auto Sales Rise in October; Dollar Steadies</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: LEADS with six grafs to UPDATE with unemployment report; PICKS
UP 3rd graf pvs, `The Dow ...'</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By PETER COY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   The U.S. unemployment rate fell to 5.3 percent in October, the
government said today in its last major economic report before
Tuesday's election.
   The decline from September's 5.4 percent returned the rate to
June's 5.3 percent, the lowest since May 1974.
   The Labor Department said employers added 325,000 jobs last
month, compared with average monthly increases of 240,000 in August
and September.
   Nearly 100,000 of the new jobs were on assembly lines, more than
double the drop of 45,000 manufacturing jobs over the two previous
months, the department said.
   On Thursday, retailers and automakers reported improved October
sales over a year ago, when the 1987 stock crash was sending tremors
through the buying public.
   The sales reports had little effect on the financial markets, but
stocks and bonds were helped by a steadying of the dollar against
major foreign currencies.
   The Dow Jones average of 30 industrials rose 13.51 points to
2,170.34 on Thursday, while advancing issues outnumbered declines 4
to 3 on the New York Stock Exchange.
   Bond prices also rose. The Treasury's bellwether 30-year bond
rose { point, or about $5 per $1,000 face amount, while its yield
fell to 8.74 percent from 8.78 percent late Wednesday.
   In addition to the dollar's steadiness, the bond market was
helped by a decline in precious metals prices and a perception that
the retail and auto sales were fairly weak. Bond traders fear the
inflation that often accompanies strong sales, which can be a sign
of a strong economy.
   But the pace of bond trading was restrained as many investors
stayed out of the market in advance of today's scheduled government
report on U.S. unemployment during October.
   The dollar's leveling followed several days of decline. In New
York, the dollar rose to 124.68 Japanese yen Thursday from 124.40
yen the day before.
   Stocks have come under some pressure from the dollar's persistent
decline in recent days, which has raised fears that the Federal
Reserve could bolster the currency by nudging interest rates higher.
   U.S. automakers said they sold 7.9 percent more cars and light
trucks in late October this year compared with the same period last
year, when the initial impact of the stock market crash was being
felt.
   Analysts said the retail sales report indicated continued
sluggishness, though some predicted a healthy Christmas season.
   ``There was some gradual improvement in the pace of sales from
August and September with particular strength noted in some of the
apparel categories,'' said Jeffrey Feiner, a retail industry analyst
with the investment firm Merrill Lynch & Co.
   But Jeffrey Edelman, an analyst with Drexel Burnham Lambert Inc.,
said, ``The numbers were a little below expectations.''
</TEXT>
