<HEAD>Leftists Burn American Flag In Rally Outside U.S. Embassy</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: SUBS 1st graf to make clear that protesters demanded no
negotiation of new treaty in 1991.</NOTE>
<DATELINE>MANILA, Philippines (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Hundreds of leftists burned an
American flag outside the U.S. Embassy today to condemn the recent
agreement extending U.S. bases in the country and demand the
government refuse to negotiate a new treaty in 1991.
   Protesters, representing several labor and student groups,
carried banners reading ``No to U.S. Bases'' and ``U.S. Imperialism
_ Cause of Poverty.''
   Police estimated the crowd at 1,000. But reporters said the
numbers dwindled in half as rain fell. The group dispersed without
incident at the end of the protest.
   ``Dismantle U.S. bases in the country now,'' Crispin Beltran,
leader of the left-wing May First Movement, told the crowd. ``We
condemn the talks. ... This is an historic sellout of Philippine
sovereignty.''
   Beltran was referring to a U.S.-Philippine agreement Oct. 17 that
reaffirmed the presence of the six bases in this country until
September 1991.
   The United States agreed to provide $962 million in economic and
military aid over the final two years of the agreement. Previously,
Washington paid $180 million a year for use of Clark Air Base, Subic
Bay naval base and four smaller installations.
   After 1991, any extension of the bases must be under a formal
treaty ratified by two-thirds of the 23-member senate, where
opposition to the installations is strong.
   Under the agreement, either the Philippines or the United States
can unilaterally terminate the agreement after Sept. 16, 1991, with
one year's notice. That could extend the bases until September 1992.
   President Corazon Aquino, however, said this week the Philippines
considers the agreement void on Sept. 16, 1991, unless the treaty
has been ratified.
   Western diplomats, speaking on condition of anonymity, said the
United States also wanted negotiations completed and a treaty
ratified before the September 1991 date.
</TEXT>
