<HEAD>Woman Dies in Rare Case of Swine Flu</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ATLANTA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A pregnant woman has died in a rare case of
pig-to-human transmission of swine flu, according to the Centers for
Disease Control.
   The 32-year-old Wisconsin woman had visited a pig barn at a
county fair that had been the site of a flu-like illness in the
animals, the CDC reported Thursday.
   She fell ill days later, and although she gave birth to a healthy
baby on Sept. 17, she died on Sept. 21. Under CDC policy, neither
the woman nor the site of the infection was released.
   CDC researcher Nancy Arden said there has been no indication of
further spread in the Wisconsin case.
   Federal officials in the mid-1970s launched a swine flu
vaccination program in the wake of a cluster of cases at Fort Dix,
N.J.
