<1ST_LINE>u i PM-Israel 1stLd-Writethru a0481 11-04 0693</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Israel, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0481,0717</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Shamir In Best Position To Form Government</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: New thruout to UPDATE with final vote count, details of
negotiations for coalition, Palestinian declaration published. TRIMS
to tighten. No pickup.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By RONI RABIN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JERUSALEM (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Prime Minister Yitzhak Shamir's right-wing Likud
bloc appeared to be in the best position to form a new government
after the final vote count was announced today in Israel's
parliamentary elections.
   The count released by the Central Elections Committee indicated
Likud won 40 seats in the 120-member Knesset, or parliament, and the
left-leaning Labor Party won 39 seats, spokeswoman Sarah Yitzhaki
said.
   The result of Tuesday's vote means neither party has the majority
needed to form a government and both parties have been wooing the
right-wing religious bloc in an effort to gain control of the
Knesset.
   The National Religious Party, which has five seats in the
Knesset, has pledged its support to Likud, Israeli radio said.
   Shamir held bargaining meetings Thursday with two other
right-wing religious parties, Moledet (Homeland) and Tzomet
(Crossroads), whose support he needs.
   Tzomet and Moledet, which won two seats each, favor annexing the
Israeli-occupied West Bank and Gaza Strip. Moledet's founder,
retired Gen. Rehavam Zeevi, also favors the expulsion of all Arabs
from Israel.
   Shamir said he would allow more Jewish settlements to be built in
the disputed lands but rejected the potential coalition partners'
demands for annexation and expulsion of the Palestinian residents.
   Zeevi has asked Likud to hold a referendum on the annexation
issue as a precondition for his joining a Shamir-led coalition,
Israel radio said.
   A Likud Cabinet minister raised the prospect that the Labor Party
might be invited to join in a government because the religious
parties that hold the balance of power were pressing too hard for
Orthodox causes.
   Labor and Likud now share power in a contentious coalition
government.
   ``The religious parties are presenting many demands and difficult
conditions. We will not be able to respond to them all,'' Moshe
Katzav, welfare and labor minister, told the newspaper Hadashot.
   The religious parties have asked to ban driving, movies and
soccer on the Jewish Sabbath and are demanding that conversion to
Judaism be recognized only if it is performed by an Orthodox rabbi.
   Israeli newspapers have said that the ascension of Orthodox
legislators worried Israel's non-religious Jews.
   The daily Maariv carried a poll that showed 60 percent of
Israelis were concerned about the rising power of the Orthodox. The
poll also indicated, however, that 65 opposed a ``unity government''
of Labor and Likud such as has governed since 1984 following an
inconclusive election.
   The liberal daily Haaretz, meanwhile, quoted sources in Shamir's
office as saying the prime minister was seeking the ouster of Labor
leader Shimon Peres as a price for forming a unity government with
the opposition party.
   Labor party officials who demanded anonymity said a rebellion
against Peres was brewing within his party's ranks after Labor's
poor showing.
   However, Likud minister Katzav said Peres could be invited to
join the government if he dropped his endorsement of Arab calls for
an international peace conference on the Middle East.
   Seats won by other right-wing parties in the election were:
Tehiya, 3; Tzomet, 2 and Moledet, 2.
   Seats won by leftist parties: Shinui, 2; Mapam, 3 and and
Citizens' Rights Movement, 5.
   Seats won by the religious parties: Shas, 6; Torah Flag, 2;
Agudat Israel, 5 and National Religious Party, 5.
   Seats won by Arab-oriented parties: Communists, 4; Progressive
List for Peace, 1 and Arab Democratic Party, 1.
   In another development, the pro-PLO newspaper Al Fajr today
published a draft declaration of independence for a Palestinian
state, which called for founding a state on the basis of U.N.
Security Council resolution 181 of 1947. The U.N. resolution is an
implicit recognition of Israel because it calls for both an Arab and
a Jewish state.
   On Thursday, 11 Palestinians were shot and wounded in clashes
with soldiers in the West Bank and Gaza Strip, Arab hospital
officials said. The nearly 11-month-old uprising against Israeli
control of the lands has claimed the lives of 306 Palestinians and
10 Israelis.
</TEXT>
