<FILEID>AP-NR-11-04-88 0955EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a PM-PTLInvestigation     11-04 0428</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-PTL Investigation,0442</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Bakker, Top Associates Notified They Are Grand Jury Targets</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHARLOTTE, N.C. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Prosecutors examining PTL's finances have
notified Jim Bakker and several former associates they are targets
of a grand jury investigation, an indication indictments may be
imminent, a newspaper reported today.
   ``A target of the grand jury investigation is a person as to whom
the prosecutor or the grand jury has substantial evidence linking
him to the commission of a crime and who, in the judgment of the
prosecutor, is a putative defendant,'' federal prosecutor Charles
Alexander wrote, The Charlotte Observer reported.
   The newspaper said Bakker, PTL chief builder Roe Messner; and
Richard Dortch, Bakker's former top deputy, received the letter. All
three have been invited to testify before the grand jury the week of
Nov. 28.
   Alexander's Oct. 24 letter to Bakker cites Justice Department
guidelines in inviting Bakker to testify, including a requirement he
give up his right against self-incrimination and consent to a full
examination under oath.
   ``Any and all testimony which you provide can be used against you
by the grand jury and in subsequent legal proceedings. ... This
letter is not a subpoena, and you are not compelled to appear,'' the
newspaper quoted the letter as saying.
   Alexander has refused even to acknowledge the grand jury's
existence. He declined comment Thursday.
   Bakker said in a statement that he would not appear before the
grand jury.
   Bakker resigned from PTL in March 1987 in a sex-and-money
scandal. The grand jury has been investigating the evangelical
empire for possible mail and wire fraud, conspiracy and tax
violations since August 1987.
   Bakker has denied any wrongdoing and said in August that if he is
indicted, ``it'll be because somebody framed us and set us up.''
   Bakker attorney Jim Toms said that despite the target letter, he
doesn't think prosecutors have decided to indict Bakker. Toms said
he hopes to meet with prosecutors ``to reach a just and equitable
solution to this distressing situation.''
   ``I do sense they are to the point where they know pretty well
where they want to head,'' Toms said, ``and it's time to open a
dialogue.''
   Bill Diehl, who represents Dortch, said the letter is a clear
signal prosecutors are going to indict the targets. ``It's a done
deal,'' he said.
   Former federal prosecutor Kenneth Andresen, who represents
Bakker's former secretary, agreed. He noted the investigation has
gone on for 16 months.
   ``If prosecutors don't think they've uncovered evidence of
wrongdoing, there's no need to give the targets an opportunity to
explain their conduct,'' he said.
</TEXT>
