<1ST_LINE>r a PM-Reagan 1stHold-for-ReleaseLd-Writethru a0558 11-04 0804</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Reagan, 1st Hold-for-Release Ld-Writethru, a0558,770</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>For release 11 a.m. EST</NOTE>
<HEAD>Precede WASHINGTON</HEAD>
<HEAD>Reagan Endorses Anti-Genocide Bill</HEAD>
<NOTE>EDS: Changes dateline to CHICAGO; inserts 6 grafs, FOR RELEASE
11:50 a.m. EST, after 5th graf pvs, The president.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By W. DALE NELSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Reagan today paused on the campaign
trail to approve legislation providing for U.S. participation in an
anti-genocide treaty signed by Harry Truman in 1948 but long blocked
by conservatives.
   ``I am delighted to fulfill the promise made by Harry Truman to
all the peoples of the world _ and especially the Jewish people,''
Reagan said in a statement released at the White House in advance of
his action.
   Reagan recalled the Nazi death camps that claimed millions of
Jews, Slavs, Gypsies and others in World War II, and noted that
similar horrors have occurred in Cambodia, the Ukraine and Ethiopia.
   These events ``only renew our rage and righteous fury and make
this moment all the more significant for me and all Americans,''
Reagan said.
   The president signed the bill at O'Hare International Airport
outside Chicago while on his way to a rally for Vice President Bush
and his running mate, Dan Quayle.
</TEXT>
<HEAD>Following 6 grafs FOR RELEASE 11:50 a.m. EST</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   As he left the White House, Reagan was asked about criticiam that
the GOP has engaged in a negative campaign.
   ``It's a little bit like what Harry Truman once said, `We've just
been telling the truth, and they think it's negative,''' he replied.
   Bush ``is the guy to lead us forward,'' Reagan said in remarks
prepared for delivery in Palos Hills, Ill, where he was speaking at
a Bush rally.
   Reagan said that ``the last eight years have been good years, but
I've got a hunch that, when George Bush gets in the saddle ... we
ain't seen nothing yet.''
   ``I know the fellow at the top of the other ticket is going
around saying he's on your side. Well, I know who's on your side
because he's been on my side _ it's George Bush. ... So, if you want
to know who's on the side of the little guy, well, I'll tell you _
it's the big guy, the big guy from Texas,'' Reagan said in a
referenc to Bush.
   ``And, as for the other fellow _ he's been going around lately
comparing himself with some of the great Democrats of the past, men
like FDR and JFK, but I have to tell you, if he's Harry Truman, I'm
Roger Rabbit,'' Reagan went on.
</TEXT>
<HEAD>
^Preceding 6 grafs FOR RELEASE 11:50 a.m. EST</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   After the rally at Moraine Valley Community College, Reagan was
traveling to New Jersey for a Republican Party fund-raiser in
Voorhees Township.
   The genocide treaty was ratified by the Senate in 1986, handing a
personal triumph to Sen. William Proxmire, D-Wis., who made than
3,000 Senate speeches over 19 years urging ratification. Proxmire is
retiring from the Senate this year.
   After the ratification, implementing legislation was still needed
to give the treaty the force of American law. It is this
legislation, passed by the Senate Oct. 14, that Reagan agreed to
sign.
   Like the treaty itself, the legislation was opposed by many
conservatives. It makes genocide a crime under U.S. law and imposes
life imprisonment as the maximum punishment. Genocide is defined in
the treaty as the intentional destruction of national, ethnic,
racial or religious groups, in whole or in part.
   On Saturday, Reagan travels to the Detroit area for a Bush-Quayle
rally at Macomb Community College and to Mesquite, Texas, near
Dallas, for a GOP gathering in a rodeo arena.
   After that, his plans were uncertain, spokesman Marlin Fitzwater
said.
   Fitzwater at first said Reagan would return from Texas to
Washington and spend Sunday at the White House, possibly going out
for another one-day pre-election foray on Monday.
   Late Thursday, the president's spokesman said that was still
under consideration, but officials also were looking at the
possibility of Reagan flying on from Dallas to California, a crucial
state with 47 electoral votes, and returning to Washington on
election eve.
   ``No place is sealed up,'' Fitzwater said. ``We're running like
we're 10 points behind, going every place.''
   Reagan has made seven campaign appearances in California since
Bush became the Republican nominee for president.
   He spoke in Long Beach and Irvine Aug. 23, in Thousand Oaks and
Santa Barbara Aug. 27, in San Diego Oct. 27 and in Fullerton and San
Bernardino on Wednesday.
   Fitzwater said Reagan would watch election returns at the White
House on Tuesday night. Asked whether the president would make any
public appearances or statements, he said, ``At this point, we just
don't have his plans available.''
   He said he did not believe Reagan would deliver a television
speech on Bush's behalf before the election.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
