<1ST_LINE>r a PM-OfficialEnglish     11-04 0206</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Official English,0212</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Appeal Judges Study Challenge to Ballot Measure</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MIAMI (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Opponents of a measure that would make English the
state's official language won support from the U.S. Justice
Department in their effort to persuade a federal court to remove the
measure from Tuesday's ballot.
   A three-judge panel of the 11th U.S. Circuit Court of Appeals on
Thursday heard arguments and said it probably would rule before the
vote on Amendment 11.
   The Justice Department argued that the petition drive that put
the measure on the ballot violated the Voting Rights Act by not
distributing petitions in Spanish as well as English in six heavily
Hispanic counties.
   At Thursday's hearing, Mark Dienstag, attorney for the group
Florida English, which collected more than 500,000 signatures,
attacked the government's position.
   ``The Justice Department brief is incompetent and misleading,''
Dienstag said. ``(They) chose to ignore all the cases we're talking
about which created the body of law surrounding the Voting Rights
Act.''
   Following the hearing, Don Middlebrooks, attorney for Speak Up
Now, which challenged the ballot measure, said the Justice
Department decision could be a boost.
   ``Generally courts give some deference to the agency responsible
for enforcing the act, and that's the Justice Department,''
Middlebrooks said.
</TEXT>
