<1ST_LINE>r a PM-BRF--DisneyContract     11-04 0143</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-BRF--Disney Contract,0150</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Union Members Reject Contract Over Wages</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LAKE BUENA VISTA, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Union members at Walt Disney World
have overwhelmingly rejected a three-year contract covering 9,000
employees.
   ``This has never happened, not in 17 years,'' said Harvey Totzke,
president of the six-union Service Trades Council, whose negotiators
had recommended approval.
   The pact was defeated 1,558 to 96 on Thursday. Negotiators were
to return to the bargaining table today. The old contract has been
extended until midnight Monday.
   The union council includes food servers, custodians, store
clerks, stagehands, bus drivers, monorail and watercraft pilots,
meat cutters and those who portray the Disney characters at the
amusement park.
   The agreement would have provided for a 5 percent raise in its
first year and 4 percent increases in each of its last two years.
   Union leaders said many members wanted bigger raises.
</TEXT>
