<1ST_LINE>r a PM-ContaminatedHouse     11-04 0211</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Contaminated House,0217</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Unknown Contaminant Eating Away At Clothing and Furniture</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   DAYTON, Ohio AP) _ A mysterious substance is eating away at the
clothing and furniture at a house, investigators say.
   Firefighters who entered the home of Ethel Black on Thursday
reported throat irritation and a burning sensation on their skin,
but the four occupants, who noticed the phenomenon Saturday,
apparently suffered no ill effects.
   Lt. Bruce DeVelbiss of the Montgomery County Hazardous Materials
Team picked up a pair of jeans to reveal a tear in the legs. Using
his finger like a knife, he easily sliced through the material.
   ``All the fabric in the house is like that,'' he said. ``I've
never seen anything like it in my 14 years here.''
   ``The odor smells acidic and leaves a metallic taste in your
mouth,'' said District Fire Chief Jerry Dyer. But he said tests
showed the house to have a high alkaline concentration, not acid.
   Dyer said that he is trying to locate an air sampler and that the
clothing would be analyzed by laboratories. ``We will strongly
suggest to the occupants that they don't return until someone can
come with a finding on what it is,'' he said.
   Firefighters checked neighboring houses but found no other
evidence of contamination.
</TEXT>
