<FILEID>AP-NR-11-04-88 1148EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r w PM-DefenseProbe 1stLd-Writethru a0413 11-04 0615</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Defense Probe, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0413,600</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Source Says Parkin To Be Charged In Pentagon Procurement Case</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Subs last 2 grafs, In a, with 00 new grafs, confirmation.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By JOAN MOWER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Federal prosecutors have indicated that defense
consultant William Parkin will be among the first people charged in
the massive Pentagon bribery case, a source says.
   The source, speaking Thursday on condition of anonymity, said
Parkin has been told he ``will be indicted unless he comes in and
cuts a deal, which he is not going to do.''
   Parkin has told reporters that he believes he broke no laws in
running his Alexandria, Va., consulting business. Although the
source would not reveal details of the plea bargain offer, he said
the terms were stiff.
   Last week, Henry E. Hudson, the U.S. attorney in Alexandria, Va.,
said the first indictments in the investigation into the
$150-billion-a-year defense procurement business could come later
this month.
   The 2-year-old investigation centers on allegations that
consultants paid bribes to Defense Department officials to gather
inside information that was useful to companies bidding on the
multimillion-dollar projects.
   Sharon Dibbley, a spokeswoman for Hudson, said the prosecutor
would not comment on reports that plea-bargain arrangements had been
offered. Earlier, however, government and defense sources indicated
that Hudson's assistants had been kept waiting for responses from
some potential defendants to offers of plea bargains.
   Prosecutors are known to be looking at a broad variety of charges
in the investigation, including bribery, fraud, conspiracy, theft of
government property and tax violations.
   Hudson is running the bribery investigation that came to light in
June when FBI agents staged raids at more than 40 locations around
the country. Justice Department officials who spoke on condition of
anonymity predicted that about a half dozen people will be indicted
initially by a grand jury. Hudson said indictments could continue
over a year.
   Attempts to reach Parkin for comment were unsuccessful. No one
answered his telephone on two occasions, and his lawyer, Gerard
Treanor, declined to comment.
   In interviews with The Wall Street Journal last summer, Parkin
said he paid Fred Lackner, a California-based consultant, more than
$15,000 to obtain inside information on a Navy contract for
anti-aircraft equipment.
   Lackner said he received some information from Stuart Berlin, a
Navy engineer, but he said the information was public knowledge.
   The Journal, quoting unnamed sources, reported Thursday that
prosecutors also would seek an indictment against Lackner, who could
not be reached for comment. Lackner also was offered a plea
bargaining deal, the paper said.
   Lackner's attorney, William Dougherty, was out of the country and
was unavailable for comment.
   Parkin has told reporters that he and Lackner shared consulting
fees from Teledyne Electronics of Newbury Park, Calif.
   One source familiar with the case has said the Teledyne aspects
were the furthest along in the investigation.
   This source, speaking anonymously, also said Jack Sherman, a
Marine Corps official, was believed to have reached or be near
reaching a plea bargain with prosecutors.
   The Journal's sources said prosecutors have evidence that Sherman
accepted more than $40,000 in cash from defense consultants and
their associates in a one-year period. Sherman's lawyer, Louis
Koutoulakos, did not return telephone messages.
   In a related development, the Defense Contract Audit Agency has
found the Pentagon's procurement regulations are so vague that major
defense contractors have been allowed to bill the government for
millions of dollars for outside consultants without justifying or
explaining their work.
   In a review of 12 of the top 100 defense contractors, the
auditors labeled as ``questionable'' claims for $43 million out of
the $236.5 million they charged to the government over the past year
for consultant services.
</TEXT>
