<1ST_LINE>r w PM-NaziDeport     11-04 0226</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Nazi Deport,220</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Immigration Judge Orders Illinois Man Deported Because of Nazi Past</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An immigration judge has ordered that a
Winnetka, Ill., man be deported to Australia because he persecuted
Jews and other civilians while serving in a Nazi execution squad
during World War II, the Justice Department announced today.
   Konrads Kalejs has until Nov. 14 to appeal Tuesday's decision by
immigration judge Anthony D. Petrone of Chicago.
   In a case brought by the Justice Department's Nazi-hunting unit,
the Office of Special Investigations, Petrone found that Kalejs
served in Nazi-occupied Latvia as a company commander in the Arajs
Kommando. Kalejs was found to have commanded guards at the Nazi
concentration camps of Salaspils in Latvia and Porkhov in Russia
where thousands of civilians died.
   Along with the Kalejs case, OSI is prosecuting cases against
Edgards Inde of Minneapolis, Minn.; Valdis Didrichsons of Seattle;
and Mikelis Kirsteins of Syracuse, N.Y., who are alleged to have
served with Kalejs.
   Petrone found that Kalejs concealed his service in the Arajs
Kommando when applying to enter the United States from Australia.
Kalejs, who came to this country in 1959, remains an Australian
citizen. Petrone ruled that Kalejs' involvement in acts of
persecution rendered him ineligible to immigrate to the United
States.
   Kalejs also maintains a residence in St. Petersburg, Fla., said
Justice Department spokesman John Russell.
</TEXT>
