<2ND_LINE>PM-Student Depression, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0569,0346</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Researchers: More Than 10 Percent of Medical Students Suffer
Depression</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: SUBS 4th graf pvs, `At any ...' to CORRECT that study did not
say students could be diagnosed as clinically depressed.</NOTE>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   One in eight medical students suffers from major
symptoms of depression because of the ``pressure-cooker'' atmosphere
in medical school, scientists report.
   ``The study documents what many medical educators have long
assumed, which is that medical school is a depressing place to be if
you're a medical student,'' Peter Zeldow, associate professor of
psychiatry at Chicago's Northwestern University Medical School, said
Thursday.
   The four-year study, reported in today's Journal of the American
Medical Association, followed a class of 121 students at Rush
Medical College in Chicago.
   At any point in four years of medical school, at least 12 percent
of the doctors-in-training showed signs of depression. At the end of
the second year, the figure rose to about 25 percent and then
receded.
   By contrast, about 5 percent of the U.S. population suffers from
depression, the researchers said.
   The students' symptoms of depression included sleep disturbance,
pessimism, sense of failure, suicidal wishes and loss of sex drive.
   ``The majority of medical students are quite unhappy or
miserable, whether they are suffering from depression or not,''
Zeldow said.
   The study's authors, Zeldow and David Clark, associate professor
of psychiatry at Rush, pointed to medical school itself as a major
cause of the depression.
   ``It's just a pressure cooker and if we dropped any cross section
of the population into it they would get depressed,'' Clark said.
   ``The curricula they provide are too dense with information,''
Zeldow said. ``There's no doubt inadequate attention is paid to the
emotional needs of the students.''
   The type of people in medical school is also a factor, Clark said.
   ``The qualities that make you a conscientious, fanatical student
have a cost,'' Clark said.
   The researchers differed on whether medical students' depression
would influence the care they give patients when they become
practicing physicians
</TEXT>
