<2ND_LINE>PM-Iran-US,0348</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Iranians Mark Anniversary of U.S. Embassy Seizure</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NICOSIA, Cyprus (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Iranians marched in the streets of Tehran
today shouting ``Death to America!'' to mark the ninth anniversary
of the takeover of the U.S. Embassy by militants who held 52
Americans hostage for 444 days.
   Tehran Radio, monitored in Nicosia, said the crowds converged on
Tehran University for a rally and prayers on the ``anniversary of
the takeover of the den of spies and the struggle against global
arrogance.''
   It did not give an estimate of crowd size but broadcast tapes of
people shouting in Farsi: ``Death to America!''
   On Nov. 4, 1979, militants stormed the U.S. Embassy in Tehran and
seized 65 hostages. They released 13 hostages within 16 days but
held 52 for 14 months.
   The militants claimed the embassy was used for spying.
   A similar march was held Wednesday outside the former embassy
compound, which Revolutionary Guard troops took over after the
hostages were freed.
   Officials decided to mount that march two days before the
anniversary so it would not interfere with prayers on Friday, the
Moslem sabbath. Today's demonstrators marched to a prayer service
held every Friday.
   Hashemi Rafsanjani, Parliament speaker and commander-in-chief,
led today's prayers. He called for unity among Moslems against
``global arrogance,'' a term often used for policies of the United
States.
   Iranian officials have made such appeals since a U.N.-sponsored
cease-fire halted their eight-year war with Iraq on Aug. 20. The
calls are part of a campaign to restore normal relations between
Iran and neighboring Arab states.
   Also speaking at today's ceremony was Sheik Mohammed Hussein
Fadlallah, spiritual guide of Lebanon's pro-Iranian Hezbollah, or
Party of God. That group is believed to be an umbrella for Moslem
fundamentalists holding 14 foreign hostages, including nine
Americans, in Lebanon.
   In his speech, Fadlallah said militants in Lebanon would continue
to fight Israeli soldiers in south Lebanon, Tehran Radio said.
Israel maintains its own security zone up to 10 miles into
neighboring Lebanon and sometimes clashes with local militias.
</TEXT>
