<HEAD>Precede FAIRFIELD, Conn.</HEAD>
<HEAD>Bush Denounces Firm For Using His Name In Approaching Haiti</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: TOP 13 grafs new with Bush interview; pickup 3rd graf, `Bank
overdraft;' drops last 5 grafs to trim.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By RITA BEAMISH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CINCINNATI (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   George Bush today assailed a long-time
associate's public relations firm for trying to capitalize on ties
to the vice president. ``I denounce it,'' Bush said.
   The vice president said in an interview that he had spoken to
Fred Bush, a top Republican fund-raiser who is not related to him,
about the solicitation to the Haitian government made by Fred Bush's
partner, Michael Govan.
   ``I denounce it. I don't like it. I think it's wrong,'' Bush
said, giving his first comment on the matter during an interview
aboard Air Force Two en route to Cincinnati.
   Asked why voters should believe he would fill a Bush
administration with people who were not intent on influence
peddling, Bush replied, ``They know I've been in public life for 20
years, and no one has ever made any allegations about impropriety on
my part, because they know how strongly I feel about ethics in
government.''
   The GOP presidential nominee, who rarely mentions the White House
ethics office he proposed early in the campaign, said he sitll
intends to set up one if elected.
   On another matter, Bush said he would favor taking steps toward a
free trade agreement with Mexico, along the lines of the one with
Canada, but he siad he would not favor that arrangement with Japan
at this point.
   ``Mexico might be a very good place for the next major step of
that nature. Japan is a little more complicated,'' he said.
   On the Haiti matter, Fred Bush has said his partner acted over
his veto and without his knowledge in seeking a contract for Bush &
Company to represent Haiti. He called it a ``rotten, rotten thing to
happen'' to him and to the Bush campaign.
   The firm's letter touted Fred Bush's connections to the vice
president.
   A former vice presidential staffer, Fred Bush was deputy finance
director of the presidential campaign and is now a fund-raising
consultant working with the Republican National Committee on the
general election.
   At a rally in Fairfield, Conn., earlier today, Bush brandished a
headline that labeled the Massachusetts budget situation ``a mess.''
   Seeking to undermine rival Michael Dukakis' support in the
governor's home territory, Bush accused Dukakis of ``borrowing like
mad'' and ``kiting checks.''
   ``Bank overdraft $373,000,'' Bush said, reading from Wednesday's
front page of the Boston Herald, as he addressed a rally at
Fairfield University in neighboring Connecticut. The Herald headline
read ``What a Mess.''
   ``And that's what's happening in what used to be called the
Massachusetts miracle. Regrettably it turns out to be a mirage,''
Bush said.
   The news story referred to a $49 million shortfll in state
revenue during October. State officials said this week that a plan
to slash state spending to head off a potential budget deficit was
in the offing.
   Bush said Dukakis got into the situation ``by overspending. How
did he get out of it, or try to? By raising taxes a total of $180
million this year alone. ... Now he's borrowing like mad, writing
checks that he doesn't even have enough money in the bank to cover.''
   ``He may want to be on your side, but I don't think the American
people want to be on his side,'' Bush said.
   Bush's regional campaign director, Ron Kaufman, said the campaign
hoped to capitalize on new polling that shows Bush trailing by only
7 points in Dukakis' home state. ``All we've been doing in
Massachusetts in this campaign is holding up a mirror,'' Kaufman
told reporters.
   He said the campaign is mailing ads to Democrats and independent
voters in counties where President Reagan won in 1984, focusing on
the state's economic situation.
   In Connecticut, Kaufman said Bush leads by nine percentage points.
   The GOP presidential nominee is hopscotching back and forth among
a handful of states where the race is close, focusing on the Midwest
and ``going to places where we think it's a little bit soft,'' said
Bush's chief of staff Craig Fuller.
   Those places included Illinois, Ohio and New Jersey on Thursday.
Today's schedule calls for campaigning in Connecticut, Ohio,
Michigan and back to New Jersey.
   ``At this stage in the campaign George Bush has secured a broad
base of supporters and is trying to broaden it still further by
indicating that his views and his values are consistent with
mainstream America,'' Fuller said.
   Thus, while Bush spent earlier weeks painting Dukakis as a
liberal who is out of step with the mainstream, he now is taking the
next step to portray himself as the mainstream candidate.
   Bush uses the word dozens of times a day in rally after rally.
   ``I represent the mainstream, the mainstream views and values and
these are your views and values and we are the change and we are the
mainstream,'' Bush told a rally at Farleigh Dickinson University in
Hackensack, N.J..
   ``It is the people of America who will decide what victory means.
What I am asking the people to give me on November 8 is not just a
political victory but a mandate from the mainstream,'' he added.
   The outreach to those beyond the Republican faithful includes
invoking the names of popular Democratic presidents Franklin D.
Roosevelt, Harry Truman and John F. Kennedy.
   Bush told a rally at Bloom Township High School outside Chicago
that those presidents ``were talking mainstream values,'' but that
Dukakis has too narrow a vision to encompass their mantle.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
