<1ST_LINE>r a PM-SalineLawsuit     11-04 0179</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Saline Lawsuit,0188</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Family Files Lawsuit In Student's Lab Death</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SEATTLE (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The family of a college student who died after
drinking nearly a quart of a toxic solution as part of a class
experiment has sued for $2.5 million.
   A student who fell ill but survived sought damages of $10,000 in
the negligence suit filed Thursday in state court against Pierce
College, two hospitals, the state and the manufacturer and
distributor of the solution.
   The 27 students in the anatomy and physiology class June 1 were
conducting an experiment, which called for drinking simple saline
solution to test urinary output.
   Two volunteers, Dawn Collins, 29, and Shellie McCallen, 18, drank
the liquid.
   Instead of swallowing simple saline solution, the women were
given isotonic buffered saline solution containing the toxic sodium
azide.
   Ms. Collins lost consciousness, vomited and suffered diarrhea.
She died June 5.
   The college has denied irresponsible behavior.
   Geoffrey Fenton, a spokesman for the product's distributor,
Baxter Healthcare Corp. of Deerfield, Ill., said the solution is
clearly marked for external use and meets federal standards.
</TEXT>
