<1ST_LINE>r a PM-DudBullets     11-04 0290</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Dud Bullets,0299</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Dead Bullets May Have Saved Public Housing Director's Life</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BATON ROUGE, La. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Six dud bullets may have saved the life
of the city's public housing chief, police said.
   A woman who had been threatening tenants with a handgun Thursday
pointed it at Housing Authority Executive Director Larry Cole when
he went out to deal with her, and pulled the trigger several times.
The gun merely clicked.
   Cole said he figured the gun was unloaded, but police discovered
later that the six-shot .22-caliber revolver was fully loaded and in
good condition _ only the ammunition was bad.
   ``That's the only thing they can see that kept the gun from
discharging and him from getting shot,'' said police Sgt. Carl
Thompson. Each bullet had three or four dents in it from the hammer,
so the trigger had been pulled at least 18 times, he said.
   Police knew of no motive for the incident, in which Cole
confronted a woman threatening tenants standing on their balconies
at a housing complex.
   ``I kept telling her to put the gun down and step back,'' he
said. ``She was about 25 yards away, and she was drunk. So I figured
the odds were pretty good that I wouldn't get shot.''
   Eventually, he said, the gun slipped from her hand.
   Police charged Elaine Harris, 33, with attempted murder. She was
jailed on $100,000 bail. Cole said the woman told him she was not a
tenant of the housing project and had recently had been released
from a state mental hospital.
   ``It's just part of the job. It was not a big thing,'' Cole said.
``You've got to get the attention away from the tenants. I was more
concerned about my tenants.''
</TEXT>
