<2ND_LINE>PM-India-Punjab, 3rd Ld-Writethru,a0580,0430</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Bombs Kill At Least 26 In Punjab</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: LEADS with 7 grafs to update death toll to 26. Pick up 7th
pvs, ``We have...</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By DEEPAK SHARMA</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>AMRITSAR, India (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Seven bombs, including some concealed in
sewing machines, killed 26 people and wounded 50 in the Punjab town
of Batala today, police said.
   ``We suspect Sikh terrorists are behind the explosions,'' Batala
police chief S.M. Sharma said.
   Late Thursday, 11 people were killed when Sikh gunmen ambushed a
bus in northern Punjab, police said.
   A police spokesman in Punjab's state capital Chandigarh said 26
people were killed when the bombs exploded in rapid succession at a
crowed market place in a Hindu neighborhood.
   ``There were seven explosions. They were so powerful that limbs
of victims flew all over the place,'' said the spokesman, who cannot
be identified under briefing rules, said.
   Sharma said some of the explosives were concealed in two sewing
machines which were left on bicycles 200 yards apart.
   ``They were very powerful. Some of the injured are in critical
condition,'' Sharma said in a telephone interview. Sharma said the
victims were 22 Hindus, three Sikhs and a Christian.
   ``We have imposed a curfew in the area and more police are being
set to counter any retaliation'' in case of a Hindu backlash of
violence, Sharma said.
   The police spokesman in Chandigarh said the state's borders with
Haryana and Jammu-Kashmir were sealed after the blasts. ``We have
also announced a new state-wide alert,'' he said.
   He said police and paramilitary troops were searching the Batala
area. No arrests were reported.
   Batala, 30 miles north of the Sikh holy city of Amritsar, has a
population of 150,000. Hindus outnumber Sikhs in the town and
control the trade.
   Late Thursday, Sikh attackers fired on a bus after the driver
ignored their warnings to stop near Gujarpura, 30 miles northeast of
Amritsar, police said.
   Six people were killed inside the bus and five were slain after
they jumped out of the bus and tried to flee, a police spokesman
said. Six people were injured.
   The attackers, armed with AK-47 semi-automatic assault rifles,
escaped in a jeep, authorities said.
   Sikh radicals are fighting for an independent nation in Punjab
state. They claim they are discriminated against by Hindus, India's
religious majority, and need a separate homeland to preserve their
religion and culture.
   Sikhs make up about two percent of India's 880 million people,
but they are a majority in Punjab.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP881104-0131 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-11-04-88 1315EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u a PM-ChopperCrash     11-04 0195</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Chopper Crash,0202</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Two Rescued, Four Missing After Helicopter Crashes In Gulf</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LAKE CHARLES, La. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A helicopter carrying oil company
workers crashed in the Gulf of Mexico early today, and four people
were missing and believed dead, officials said. Two other passengers
were rescued by a workboat.
   A search was under way for the missing after the helicopter went
down near an oil rig about 120 miles south of Cameron, Mobil Oil
Exploration & Producing Southeast said in a statement.
   The two rescued men were in serious condition at St. Patrick's
Hospital with leg and chest injuries, said spokeswoman Debbie Serra.
   Michael O'Malley, a Mobil spokesman in Dallas, said four
passengers were Mobil employees and one was a welder employed by a
contractor.
   Chuck Johnson, executive vice president of ERA Helicopters, which
owned and operated the craft, said the ERA pilot was among those
missing.
   He said the pilot's radio calls did not indicate any trouble.
``It was right on takeoff,'' he said. ``We don't believe weather was
a factor in this. The weather was good out there. We had a 25-knot
wind.''
   He said the National Transportation Safety Board would
investigate.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
