<1ST_LINE>u a PM-EditorResigns 1stLd-Writethru a0617 11-04 0393</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Editor Resigns, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0617,0401</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Editor of Journal and Constitution Resigns</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: LEADS with seven grafs to UPDATE with Kovach statement; PICKS
UP 6th graf pvs, `Kovach's plans ...'</NOTE>
<DATELINE>ATLANTA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Bill Kovach, editor since 1986 of The Atlanta
Journal and The Atlanta Constitution, resigned today in a dispute
with the newspapers' management.
   Kovach's abrupt departure came nearly two years after he left the
post of Washington bureau chief of The New York Times to take over
the newspapers. His appointment was widely seen as part of an
attempt by the papers to achieve national prominence.
   Publisher Jay Smith said ``an irreconcilable difference in
management styles'' emerged in a discussion earlier today and
prompted Kovach's departure.
   However, Smith said he felt he and Kovach were in accord
philosophically over the direction the newspapers have taken under
Kovach.
   ``I am proud of the progress we have made under Bill,'' Smith
said. ``It is my commitment that we will continue to grow, continue
to find better ways to serve readers and continue to add to the
stature of the newspapers and Atlanta.''
   Kovach said in a statement that his resignation ``was the
culmination of two years of effort to develop a set of shared values
and mutual trust with the senior managers of the company.''
   ``Unfortunately I was unable to do that. It became clear this
week that no such relationship existed,'' he said. ``The continuing
challenge to realize the real potential of the Atlanta newspapers is
too great to attempt under those conditions.''
   Kovach's plans were not immediately known.
   His resignation was announced to the Journal-Constitution
newsroom by Assistant Managing Editor Wendell ``Sonny'' Rawls, who
followed Kovach from The New York Times.
   The news stunned reporters who in 1986 had greeted word of his
appointment with jubilation.
   Kovach grew up in Tennessee reading the Atlanta papers, then
under the leadership of civil rights advocate Ralph McGill.
   He said he took the editorship of the Cox Newspapers' flagship to
``strengthen McGill's newspaper and to practice journalism the way I
envisioned it.''
   He stressed hard news and aggressiveness, and among his successes
was a series outlining how some Atlanta banks were refusing loans to
residents of predominantly black neighborhoods.
   The Democratic National Convention gave the newspapers a chance
to shine to a national audience, and their coverage was favorably
commented on.
</TEXT>
