<1ST_LINE>u w AM-US-Afghanistan Bjt   11-04 0589</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-US-Afghanistan, Bjt,580</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>US Distressed by Suspension of Soviet Troop Withdrawal</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BARRY SCHWEID</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Diplomatic Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Reagan registered disappointment
Friday over a Soviet decision to suspend troop withdrawals from
Afghanistan.
   Administration officials called the move disturbing and accused
Moscow of raising tensions in the war-torn country, but they
stressed that the Soviets could still meet their commitment to pull
out by Feb. 15.
   During a political campaign stop in Chicago, the president noted
that the Soviets had renewed that pledge even while announcing the
suspension in Moscow.
   At the end of a week of U.S. complaints about new Soviet weapons
shipments to Afghanistan, White House press secretary Marlin
Fitzwater said Soviet actions ``can only increase tensions in the
region and raise speculation that they are't going to live up to the
Geneva accords.''
   The Soviets pulled out by Aug. 15 half the 100,000 or more troops
they had in Afghanistan. The accords require the others to quit the
country by Feb. 15, but it leaves the timetable up to the Soviets.
   In Moscow, a top Foreign Ministry official said the withdrawal
had been suspended because of strong attacks by anti-government
rebels.
   ``The Soviet troops are being withdrawn due to the good will of
the Soviet government,'' First Deputy Foreign Minister Alexander
Bessmertnykh told a news conference. ``They will be withdrawn in
honorable conditions.''
   But, Bessmertnykh said, the current atmosphere of heavy attacks
by rebels with arms supplied by the United States, Pakistan and
other countries ``does not provide conditions for such a withdrawal
of Soviet troops.''
   Reagan, asked about the statement, said:
   ``I think we are all disappointed by that. At the same time, I
think we should recognize that this is something they have said is
necessary and they have repledged to bring the troops out by Feb.
15.''
   When asked if the United States planned to take any steps as a
result of the Soviet announcement, the president said, ``We haven't
had a chance to sit down and talk it over.''
   Fitzwater, who was traveling with Reagan, said Soviet actions
``raise speculation that they aren't going to live up to the Geneva
accords.'' He added, ``We expect them to ... and hope that is what
their intentions are.''
   State Department spokesman Charles E. Redman called the
suspension ``disturbing.'' He also said the Soviets had fired a few
more SS-1 Scud missiles at rebel forces near the border with
Pakistan.
   Redman said the United States had urged the Mujahedeen rebels not
to ``launch actions'' that might delay the withdrawal of Soviet
forces. But, he said, the escalation of violence was bound to
``harden the attitudes'' of the guerrillas.
   He said Bernhanuddin Rabbani, leader of the Islamic Society rebel
group, would arrive in Washington on Monday and meet with Reagan and
Secretary of State George P. Shultz on Wednesday.
   A senior administration official, meanwhile, said that before the
withdrawal suspension the Soviets had discussed starting the pullout
on Nov. 15.
   ``To say they are suspending now raises a question about what
they mean,'' the official said. ``Are they going to resume on Nov.
15, or later?''
   He said the United States continues to urge the Soviets ``to
follow the timetable they have set for themselves, and to meet their
obligations to pull out by the 15th of February.''
   The official added: ``We continue to believe they will do so.
They are engaged more in bluster and efforts to persuade the
Pakistanis to rein in the Mujahedeen and to buck up their own
clients.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
