<FILEID>AP-NR-11-04-88 1426EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Poland-Workers     11-04 0674</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Poland-Workers,0695</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Workers Get Spiritual Lift from Prime Minister's Trip</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Poland-Thatcher</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DEBORAH G. SEWARD</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>GDANSK, Poland (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Discouraged workers facing layoffs in less
than a month had their spirits lifted Friday when British Prime
Minister Margaret Thatcher visited the birthplace of the banned
Solidarity trade union.
   Workers inside pressed against the closed gates of the Lenin
shipyard to get a glimpse of Mrs. Thatcher, the first Western head
of state to travel to Gdansk to meet with Solidarity leader Lech
Walesa.
   ``We love Mrs. Thatcher! We love Mrs. Thatcher!'' shouted the
hard-hatted workers who had climbed atop buildings for a better view
of her placing a wreath at a monument near the gates honoring
workers killed in 1970 food price riots.
   Mrs. Thatcher arrived in the midst of a struggle for the future
of the famous shipyard, where Solidarity sprang to life in August
1980. The government announced it is to be closed beginning Dec. 1.
   ``The shipyard is ours! Lenin is yours!'' the crowd shouted,
referring to the name of the yard. ``Mrs. Thatcher, don't let the
shipyard be closed,'' one banner implored.
   Solidarity has said it will fight the closure, contending the
decision was made for political reasons, not economic ones as the
government says.
   The officially recognized union and management have formed for
the first time a common front with the yard's illegal Solidarity
organization in order to oppose the decision.
   Despite various police barriers, Solidarity supporters were able
to reach the front of the monument for Mrs. Thatcher's visit, mixing
with crowds that had been bused in from official organizations.
Reporters estimated 20,000 people turned out to see her.
   Inside the shipyard, workers climbed on the gates and on the
roofs of administrative buildings in defiance of a warning by strike
committee leader Alojzy Szablewski not to be too aggressive and risk
police response.
   As soon as Mrs. Thatcher emerged from her limousine, the crowd
and the workers began to shout ``Solidarity! Solidarity!'' and
``There is no freedom without Solidarity!''
   Walesa accompanied Mrs. Thatcher to the 130-foot monument
consisting of three soaring steel crosses, which Solidarity erected
in its heyday in 1980 to commemorate the scores of workers killed by
police on the Baltic coast during the 1970 riots.
   Workers went on a rampage in that year after authorities raised
food prices just before Christmas. Security forces answered with
gunfire, killing a still unknown number of people.
   Visibly moved at her reception, Mrs. Thatcher waved to the crowd
around the monument and Walesa helped her mount a small stepladder
so she could reach over a metal barrier and shake hands with a few
of the people.
   The authorities had done their best to spruce up the Baltic port
and discourage unofficial crowds from forming. Streets were washed
Thursday night even though a light snow already had washed away much
of the grime.
   Scores of police trucks and jeeps clogged the narrow side streets
near the monument and hundreds of police patrolled the port. Still
the crowd followed Mrs. Thatcher's car to St. Brygida's church where
she had lunch with Walesa and union leaders.
   ``Solidarity Gdansk welcomes Mrs. Thatcher,'' said a large sign
on the church.
   Spectators said they stood behind Mrs. Thatcher's position on
human rights, but they were less enthusiastic about her attitude
toward trade unions.
   ``She is a courageous woman. She would give us nothing. But we
still have to respect her,'' said one of the workers inside the yard.
   Others admired her firm will, saying her style of leadership was
needed in Poland.
   ``If Poles are wise they will learn a lot from this visit,
because she is the Iron Lady who knows how to govern,'' said Bernard
Kowalewski, an invalid and retiree.
   Mrs. Thatcher got a roar of applause for her short speech of
thanks in St. Brygida's that was carried over loudspeakers.
   After she departed, the crowd tried to march back to the
monument, but police already had sealed off the streets. They
dispersed peacefully after several minutes.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
