<1ST_LINE>r a AM-People     11-04 0893</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-People,0930</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>People in the News</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto NY44</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEWARK, N.J. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Pop singer Whitney Houston, whose songs have
earned hundreds of millions of dollars, is a hometown girl at heart.
   Ms. Houston, a native of Newark, has decided to help rehabilitate
her birthplace by investing in a $100 million housing development
geared toward low- and middle-income residents, her father and a
city official said Thursday.
   ``Here's a young lady that's become very successful ... and she's
coming back to her roots, to where her heritage is from and she's
saying, `I did not forget you, Newark,''' said Henry Martinez, City
Council president and a supporter of the project.
   He said the council is considering calling the project Houston
Estates.
   ``It's her city,'' said her father and business manager, John
Houston. ``She's concerned. A lot of her friends are there.''
   Also born there were her mother, Cissie Houston, and her cousin,
Dionne Warwick, well-known singers in their own right.
   The project involves rehabilitating old structures and building
new ones on about 180 acres of the east ward of Newark.
   It involves about 2,000 housing units, including 600 to 800 units
to be set aside for low-income renters, senior citizens and
handicapped people. The project also includes recreational and
shopping areas.
   Ms. Houston, 25, might end up paying as much as 40 percent of the
total investment cost, her father said.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>YORK, England (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Cathedral bells rang out Friday as Queen
Elizabeth II arrived in this northern city to celebrate the
restoration of York Minster after a devastating fire four years ago.
   The queen participated in a morning service to bless a new roof
over the south transept and the reconstructed 16th-century Rose
Window nearly lost in the blaze begun by lightning on July 9.
   Before an audience of 1,500 in the large, 500-year-old Gothic
cathedral, the queen unveiled a plaque to ``remember with
gratitude'' those who helped in the $5.3 million restoration job.
   Fire at one point had threatened to spread across the building,
but the collapse of the vaulted transept roof onto the stone floor
saved the cathedral from destruction.
   Craftsmen used 160 ancient English oak trees donated from across
the country to build a new carved wooden roof.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>NASHVILLE, Tenn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Actor Jim Varney, the long-faced rube who
says ``Hey Vern'' in a variety of television commercials, says he
drew inspiration from Charlie Chaplin and Buster Keaton.
   ``Physical comedy is a comedy that works in any language, and
Chaplin knew that,'' Varney said in an interview. ``His success was
based on the fact that he never opened his mouth to get a laugh. I
think people like physical comedy, which is why cartoons are so
successful.''
   Varney, portraying rubber-necked Ernest P. Worrell, stars in the
Saturday morning CBS-TV show, ``Hey Vern, It's Ernest!''
   His second movie, ``Ernest Saves Christmas,'' will be released
next weekend. He said the motion picture includes physical comedy
like ``walking into walls and falling off ladders.''
   ``I was inspired a lot by Chaplin and Buster Keaton,'' he said.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Art Carney, who won three Emmys as Jackie
Gleason's sewer worker buddy in ``The Honeymooners'' and a Best
Actor Oscar for ``Harry and Tonto,'' quietly celebrated his 70th
birthday Friday, a spokesman said.
   ``He's treating it like any other day,'' said the spokesman, who
asked not to be identified because Carney is publicity-shy.
   Carney planned to spend the day quietly with his wife, Jean, at
their Connecticut home, he said.
   Carney rose to fame as Gleason's wisecracking neighbor Ed Norton,
a lovable sewer worker, winning three Emmy awards for the character
in both ``The Jackie Gleason Show'' and ``The Honeymooners'' in the
1950s.
   He continued to work in television and films, winning an Oscar in
1974 for his role as a roving widower traveling with his cat in
``Harry and Tonto.'' Some of his other films included ``A Guide for
the Married Man'' and ``House Calls.''
   Carney recently completed a guest spot on the TV series ``The
Cavanaughs.'' He can also be seen still strutting his Norton swagger
in a current Coca-Cola commercial.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>HUMBOLDT, Tenn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The husband of country music singer Tammy
Wynette has sternly warned reporters not to ask about the couple's
bankruptcy case.
   ``If you ask any questions about any legal situations, you're
history,'' George Richey said during a news conference Wednesday. He
later apologized for being curt.
   Miss Wynette and country singer T.G. Heppard were in this west
Tennessee town to make a promotional appearance at a car dealership.
   Miss Wynette, ``the first lady of country music,'' and Richey
filed a bankruptcy petition in Nashville Sept. 20. She is best known
for her song ``Stand by Your Man.''
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>NASHVILLE, Tenn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Oak Ridge Boys country music group,
who just had a No. 1 record about a river, will be singing on one
later this month.
   The quartet will tape a cable TV special Nov. 16 on a riverboat
on the Cumberland River, spokeswoman Laura Caron said Friday.
   The group will tape the 30-minute special for The Nashville
Network on the General Jackson riverboat. The show, ``The Oak Ridge
Boys' Christmas Special,'' will air Dec. 13.
   The Oak Ridge Boys' hits include ``Elvira'' and ``Gonna Take a
Lot of River,'' which was No. 1 on the country music charts last
month.
</TEXT>
