<1ST_LINE>r p AM-Bentsen     11-04 0505</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Bentsen,500</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Bentsen Tours Space Program; Errs on Unmanned Mission</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Political Rdp Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By STEVEN KOMAROW</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>HOUSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Democratic vice presidential candidate Lloyd
Bentsen on Friday visited a science program founded after the
explosion of the space shuttle Challenger to highlight the
Democratic ticket's commitment to the space program.
   But Bentsen, the man Democratic nominee Michael Dukakis has said
would head a new cabinet-level council on space, incorrectly told an
audience of school children that the next shuttle mission would be
unmanned.
   Bentsen was campaigning in Houston on his way to California, with
a stop in New Mexico en route.
   Space is big business in Texas, where the Democrats still hope to
pick up 29 electoral votes.
   The Texas senator toured the Challenger Center at the Houston
Museum of Natural Science. The center was founded, in the wake of
the Challenger tragedy that claimed the lives of its seven-member
crew, to boost interest in science and technology among the young.
   Bentsen stopped first at a mock space station to watch fourth
graders operate robots, and work on a science project with special
gloves mounted through a transparent panel.
   In a rare instance where the ``character'' issue could be
scientifically measured, a girl held wires to Bentsen's finger to
measure the electric activity on his skin, in what was explained to
be a stress test. He measured only 1.6 on a scale where five is
normal.
   ``That means I'm cool,'' Bentsen concluded.
   Afterward, in the museum auditorium, Bentsen took questions from
an audience of school children who seemed most interested in whether
he was having a good time.
   ``How did you get to be vice president,'' one asked.
   ``I haven't done it yet,'' he answered.
   ``Is if fun to be a vice president?'' said another.
   ``I don't know yet,'' he replied. ``I'll tell you, I've had fun
running for vice president.''
   Explaining the progress of the space shuttle program, he said,
``They tell me that later this month we're going to put another one
up in space called Atlantis,'' he said. ``But that not going to have
any people on it.''
   Actually, the Atlantis will carry a crew of five on its
classified military mission. The next unmanned shuttle mission will
be launched by the Soviets.
   Bentsen's press secretary, Mike McCurry, said the error was on a
briefing paper given to Bentsen just before the event. The Texas
senator was unsure if the information was correct, but referred to
it anyway, McCurry said.
   Bentsen took a poll of the children, and about half said they
wanted to be astronauts. He told them other jobs would be good too,
including public service.
   He told them to tell their parents to vote next Tuesday. ``They
must go and be part of it,'' he said.
   The kids raised their hands to indicate they would tell their
folks to go to the polls, including Bentsen's grandson, Lloyd M.
Bentsen IV.
   ``You're going to do that too? That's good,'' said Lloyd M.
Bentsen Jr.
</TEXT>
