<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Germany-France     11-04 0284</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Germany-France,0294</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Kohl, Mitterrand Discuss Unified Policy Toward Soviet Union</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By GIRARD C. STEICHEN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BONN, West Germany (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   French President Francois Mitterrand
and West German Chancellor Helmut Kohl met Friday for talks that
focused on developing common policies toward the Soviet Union.
   At a joint news conference, Kohl told reporters he briefed
Mitterrand on his meetings with Soviet President Mikhail S.
Gorbachev in September in Moscow. Mitterrand is scheduled to visit
Moscow later this month.
   Kohl said earlier this week that the two countries should work
together to develop a ``joint European policy'' toward the Soviet
bloc because of ``new developments in the East ... that are filling
us with hope.''
   On Friday, the second day of the 52nd summit between a French and
West German leader, Mitterrand characterized relations between the
two nations as ``good and healthy.''
   Kohl said the two leaders also discussed preparations for an
upcoming meeting of European Economic Community leaders on the Greek
island of Rhodes.
   Kohl assured Mitterrand of his government's support for French
efforts to reduce its trade deficit, Ost said. He said West German
advisers will help in these efforts, but did not elaborate.
   Kohl said his country and France also are planning a joint
military brigade, which should be in place in two years.
   The West German chancellor also held talks with French Premier
Michel Rocard.
   The two men discussed obstacles that remain to the EEC plan to
remove trade barriers among its member countries by 1992, as well as
environmental protection and cooperation in high-technology, Ost
said.
   West German Environment Minister Klaus Toepfer said Friday that
an agreement had been reached to set up a joint environmental
advisory council.
</TEXT>
