<FILEID>AP-NR-11-04-88 1448EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u p AM-Bush Bjt   11-04 0875</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Bush, Bjt,850</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Bush: `It's Wrong' for Associates to Try to Use Political
Connections</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TOM RAUM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CINCINNATI (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Vice President George Bush said Friday ``I
think it's wrong'' that a consulting firm run by a long-time
associate used its political connections to try to drum up new
business.
   In an interview with The Associated Press, Bush also said he is
weary of campaigning and would rather be home playing horseshoes but
denied that Americans are turned off by negative campaigning.
   ``The idea that this campaign is so different from others _ I
don't believe it. I don't think the American people believe it, all
this stuff about being turned off. You can always go out and find
people to say that. Our people don't say that when I get off this
airplane,'' Bush said in an interview aboard Air Force Two.
   Bush expressed dismay at the disclosure that a consulting firm
headed by Frederick M. Bush (no relation) had sought business with
the new government of Haiti citing its ability to influence a new
GOP administration.
   ``I denounce it, I don't like it, I think it's wrong,'' the vice
president said.
   Frederick Bush also disavowed the effort, saying it had been
initiated without his knowledge by his partner, Michael Govan.
   Asked how Frederick Bush could have allowed it to happen, George
Bush said: ``Ask him how he could allow it to happen.''
   ``How could the chief education adviser to Mr. Dukakis end up in
jail?'' he added, referring to Gerald Indelicato, convicted in July
of skimming money from an adult education program he ran.
   Bush said the lobbying episode should not be taken as an
indication of things to come if he is elected. Voters, he said,
``know I've been in public life for 20 years, and no one has ever
made any allegations about impropriety on my part because they know
how strongly I feel about ethics in government.''
   The vice president has said he would establish an ethics office
in the White House if elected.
   At rallies on Friday, Bush attacked rival Michael Dukakis'
handling of Massachusetts' fiscal management and suggested that the
Democrat might have to seek another tax increase to finance the
state's budget shortfall.
   At a speech at Fairfield University in Stamford and at a rainy
downtown rally here, Bush held aloft a copy of the Boston Herald,
whose front-page headline read: ``What a Mess'' in referring to the
state's budget crisis.
   In the AP interview, Bush said he expected his gesture would get
more attention than just talking about the issues.
   ``This man has been claiming there is a miracle in Massachusetts.
I have to hold up a little graphic to get peoples' attention. ... I
think that's fair, it's factual. ... It's a little shot people can
see. Does that mean I shouldn't do it? Not as long as it's accurate,
and it is. So I don't have any regrets about it.''
   The vice president, interviewed on his plane between events in
Connecticut and Ohio, dismissed suggestions that his campaign was
easing off in anticipation of victory.
   ``We can't do any more, we just can't,'' Bush said, claiming he
was still waging an exhausting campaign. He said he'd ``rather be
home more. Play horsehoes. ... I get tired. You know, we've been
doing this a long time.''
   ``But it's important to do,'' he added. ``And you learn. I'll be
a better president because I've done that (campaigning).''
   Bush said he was ``real proud'' of the way his campaign has been
conducted with the election now only four days off.
   ``I can only hark back to when (the news media) were writing
entirely different views of my chances and my character and where I
stood. I think it's dramatically changed.''
   ``I'm just going to keep on going'' until Election Day, Bush
said. ``I'm reasonably upbeat but not overconfident.''
   Also in the AP interview, Bush said:
   _ If elected, he would support a free trade pact with Mexico
similar to the one recently negotiated with Canada, calling Mexico
``a very good place for the next major step of that nature.'' But he
said he opposes such an arrangement at this time with Japan.
   ``Japan is a little more complicated and I would have to be
satisfied that _ going that route, that we had total access to the
Japanese markets,'' Bush said.
   _ Predicted a surprise of next Tuesday's election might be
stronger-than-expected support for him from young blacks and
Hispanics he said were disenchanted with the Democratic Party
because of its treatment of Jesse Jackson. ``I think they feel
they've been taken for granted,'' he said.
   Asked why he wasn't spending more time campaigning in areas where
blacks and other minorities live, Bush said, ``Historically, I think
everybody knows this is a very difficult area for Republicans to get
a lot of votes. And I'm trying to get a lot of votes.''
   _ Praised Friday's unemployent figures showing the jobless rate
to have dropped to 5.3 percent, a 14-year low.
   He said it was further evidence that a recession is not at hand.
And, Bush added, ``If my programs are adopted, that would be a very
good guarantee there wouldn't be a recession.''
</TEXT>
