<1ST_LINE>d a AM-BRF--BareConviction     11-04 0144</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-BRF--Bare Conviction,0147</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Man Barely Gets Convicted</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHILLICOTHE, Ohio (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Robbie Chaney had to bare his belly in
court before he was convicted of aggravated robbery.
   A Ross County common pleas court jury looked at his stomach and
agreed Thursday it went with the man who walked into a fast food
restaurant Aug. 17 and demanded money.
   The exposure was important because the man who tried to rob the
restaurant had his shirt pulled up and over his head, exposing his
midsection.
   Restaurant worker Sherry Arledge told the court that shortly
before the robbery she refused to serve a shirtless man. During the
attempted stick-up, she said, she recognized the man's stomach as
that of the shirtless man. She later identified that man as Chaney.
   Chaney, 29, of Chillicothe, faces five to 25 years for aggravated
robbery when he sentenced Dec. 12.
</TEXT>
