<1ST_LINE>u i AM-Israel 1stLd-Writethru a0630 11-04 0701</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Israel, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0630,0714</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Final Count Gives Likud 40 Seats; Shamir Presses Ahead on Coalition</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: SUBS 7th graf `Israeli soldiers ...' to UPDATE casualties.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By KARIN LAUB</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JERUSALEM (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Final election results issued Friday gave
Yitzhak Shamir's Likud bloc 40 parliament seats and the prime
minister pressed ahead to form a majority coalition with rightist
and religious parties.
   His aides brushed aside calls for a new version of the 4-year-old
``national unity'' coalition with the center-left Labor Party of
Foreign Minister Shimon Peres, which won 39 of the 120 Knesset
seats. The fractious Likud-Labor arrangement was made after the
indecisive 1984 election.
   Al Fajr, a newspaper that supports the Palestine Liberation
Organization, published a draft declaration of independence for a
Palestinian state in the occupied territories, which is expected to
be approved at a meeting later this month of the Palestine National
Council, the PLO legislature.
   How to make peace with the Arabs and end the 11-month-old
rebellion among the 1.5 million Palestinians of the occupied West
Bank and Gaza Strip were the focus of Tuesday's election, in which
the conservative religious parties gained strength.
   Palestinians say the draft declaration is a step toward peace
because it implicity recognizes Israel's right to exist. Avi Pazner,
a Shamir aide, discounted the document and said: ``We are not asking
the PLO to recognize Israel and we will not give them anything.''
   Shamir opposes giving up land captured in the 1967 war, favors
building more Jewish settlements in occupied territory and rejects
an intrernational conference on Middle East peace demanded by the
Arabs. Labor supports both a conference and trading some land for
peace.
   Israeli soldiers shot and wounded 18 Palestinians Friday in the
West Bank Gaza, Arab hospital officials reported.
   Since the uprising began Dec. 8, 1987, more than 300 Palestinans
and 10 Israelis have been killed. At least 7,000 Palestinians have
been wounded.
   Traditionally, Israel's president asks the leader of the largest
party in the Knesset to form a government. Shamir has held
preliminary coalition talks with four religious and three far-right
parties that won a total of 25 seats. Likud must add 21 seats to its
own 40 to obtain a majority.
   Peres also courted the religous parties, but his chances of
forming a majority are seen as slim. Some in his party said he
should end negotiations and accept an opposition role because
competition for support of the religious parties strengthens their
bargaining position without benefiting Labor.
   Among the demands of religious parties, which have a total of 18
Knesset seats, are changes in the law defining who is a Jew for the
purposes of granting automatic citizenship, and banning driving,
movies and soccer games on the sabbath.
   A Likud member of the Cabinet, Moshe Katzav, also expressed
concern about religious pressure.
   ``The religious are presenting many demands and difficult
conditions,'' the newspaper Hadashot quoted him as saying. ``We will
not be able to respond to them all.''
   Katzav raised the prospect of inviting Labor into a Likud
government as a junior partner to weaken reduce the clout of
religious parties, but said Labor would have to drop its support of
an international peace conference.
   Peres appeared to dismiss the possibility of another coalition
with Likud. ``We will not join any government that has no peace
plan,'' he said on Israel radio.
   Pazner, the Shamir aide, said such a government ``is not
something realistic right now. Labor would not agree to join as a
junior partner.''
   A poll published in the daily Maariv indicated 65 percent of
Israelis opposed another ``national unity'' government and 60
percent were concerned about the rising power of the Orthodox
religious.
   Al Fajr's report said the Palestinian declaration of independence
will be presented to the Palestine National Council on Nov. 14. It
calls for a Palestinian stat based on U.N. Security Resolution 181
of 1947, which calls for both a Jewish and an Arab state.
   Israel rejects the 1947 partition plan, which gives the occupied
lands and key areas of what is now Israel to the Palestinians. The
plan also calls for international control of Jerusalem, which Israel
has annexed and declared to be its capital.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
