<FILEID>AP-NR-11-04-88 1748EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Maikovskis     11-04 0358</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Maikovskis,0368</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>News Reports Tipped West Germans to Convicted War Criminal</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By GIRARD C. STEICHEN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BONN, West Germany (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Prosecutors ordered the arrest of a man
convicted of Nazi war crimes by the Soviet Union after they learned
through news reports he had fled to West Germany from the United
States, a prosecutor said Friday.
   Boleslav Maikovskis is in investigative custody in a prison in
Bochum, although no charges have been filed in West Germany.
   ``We heard the news reports on the weekend, and the investigation
was started the next Monday,'' said Klaus Schacht, the Dortmund war
crimes prosecutor handling the West German investigation of
Maikovskis.
   ``Until then, we didn't know he was here,'' Schacht told The
Associated Press in a telephone interview.
   Maikovskis, 84, was picked up at his Muenster apartment on Oct.
19, two days after the investigation began, Schacht said. He had
lived in Mineola, N.Y., and West German authorities say he came here
in November 1987.
   The Soviet Union in 1965 sentenced Maikovskis to death in
absentia for his role in burning down a village and participating in
the murder of more than 130 men, women and children in his native
Latvia. The charges say the deaths occurred while he commanded a
pro-Nazi police force during World War II.
   On Thursday, West German officials defended issuing an entry visa
to Maikovskis, saying he had valid travel documents and had not been
charged in the United States. Bonn officials said the visa was
issued for a three-month stay to allow Maikovskis to pursue legal
matters.
   He also applied for political asylum in West Germany, which
allowed him to remain here while the case was pending.
   Last month, the U.S. Justice Department's Office of Special
Investigations said it had lost track of Maikovskis and had just
discovered he left the country.
   The United States began trying to deport him in 1976, but the
case was delayed by several appeals. His latest appeal was denied by
the U.S. Supreme Court in 1986.
   West German officials have said they would consider extraditing
Maikovskis to the Soviet Union if it waives the death penalty.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP881104-0154 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-11-04-88 1526EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u i AM-Poland-Thatcher 1stLd-Writethru a0642 11-04 0852</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Poland-Thatcher, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0642,0871</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Tumultuous Reception for Thatcher by Solidarity</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: LEADS with 8 grafs with Thatcher leaving, farewell comment,
government response. Picks up 6th pvs, `Shipyard workers...' Delete
22nd graf, `She has..' to conform.</NOTE>
<NOTE>With LaserPhoto</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By MAUREEN JOHNSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>GDANSK, Poland (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An estimated 20,000 Poles gave a tumultuous
and emotional welcome Friday to British Prime Minister Margaret
Thatcher, who met Lech Walesa at the doomed Lenin shipyard and said
she felt ``the spirit of Poland.''
   Crowds shouted slogans against communism and Poland's premier as
Mrs. Thatcher _ the first Western leader to meet Walesa at the
shipyard _ came to Gdansk after telling the government it must
negotiate with the banned trade union Solidarity before it can
receive long-term Western aid.
   Mrs. Thatcher later returned to Warsaw for a final round of talks
with Polish leader Gen. Wojciech Jaruzelski at the end of a
three-day visit. She then boarded a Royal Air Force jet for London.
   Her emotional reception in Gdansk was heightened by her tough
attitude to Jaruzelski and by the government's annnouncement this
week that it will close the Lenin shipyard, the birthplace of
Solidarity, on Dec. 1 as part of an economic austerity program.
   ``I came to see and to have a long talk with Mr. Walesa. ... I
knew that I had to come and feel the spirit of Poland for myself,''
said Mrs. Thatcher, referring to the port city of Gdansk that is the
heartland for the long struggle by workers for a free trade union.
   At a farewell news conference, Mrs. Thatcher said if the
government recognizes Solidarity, Britain will respond. ``We shall
not be found wanting when Poland makes the progress toward freedom
and democracy its people clearly seek,'' she said.
   Government spokesman Jerzy Urban said officials were not
convinced. ``We are skeptical of such attempts to define conditions,
and of such promises,'' he said.
   Polish leaders have told Mrs. Thatcher the country is crippled by
a $39 billion foreign debt, but she has said Poland must show
evidence of real economic and political reform before it gets more
aid.
   Shipyard workers in hardhats climbed on surrounding rooftops and
crowds burst into deafening chants of ``Solidarity! Solidarity!'' as
Mrs. Thatcher laid a wreath with Walesa at a towering monument to
scores of workers slain here in 1970 price riots.
   As security police trucks ringed surrounding streets, Mrs.
Thatcher had lunch with Walesa, his Roman Catholic confessor the
Rev. Henryk Jankowski, and 14 other leaders of the union at St.
Brygida's Parish Church near the shipyard.
   Crowds poured into the streets around the church and shipyard and
shouted, ``Viva Thatcher!'' to the British leader who has curbed the
power of trade unions in her own country.
   At the shipyard and monument, a section of the crowd yelled
``Down with Communism!'' and ``Out with Rakowski!'' _ the new Polish
premier Mieczyslaw F. Rakowski, who announced the closing of the
yard Monday.
   Walesa said security police tried to stop the crowds by clogging
streets with police trucks and stopping Solidarity leaders from
getting to the monument until shortly before Mrs. Thatcher arrived.
   ``See how many came despite the efforts to stop them,'' said
Walesa. ``They have filtered through somehow. We will not be
defeated.''
   At a service in St. Brygida's after lunch, the high red-bricked
church and its nearby streets echoed with chants of Solidarity
supporters.
   With Walesa standing beside her in the sacristy, his arm raised
in a V-for-victory sign, against a background of red, white and gold
Solidarity banners, Mrs. Thatcher was visibly moved as the
congregation broke into a traditional national hymn, ``God Watches
Over Poland.''
   ``Thank you for coming out and giving me and everything I believe
in such a warm welcome,'' said Mrs. Thatcher, her eyes glistening.
   A British official, who declined to be identified by name, said
that at the lunch in the rectory _ with the priest's bedroom turned
into a bar _ Walesa and Mrs. Thatcher joked often in between serious
political discussion.
   And at the end, she wished him success in his ``historic
endeavors,'' the official said.
   Before the meeting with Walesa, Mrs. Thatcher visited the
Westerplatte monument on the bay of Gdansk, scene of the first shots
of World War II, accompanied by Jaruzelski. The solemn wreath-laying
ceremony recalled the Polish-British wartime alliance.
   Mrs. Thatcher's evident doubts about the pace of reforms by
Jaruzelski and government attempts at setting up talks on Poland's
future, her public support for Solidarity and her huge welcome in
Gdansk cast doubts over the success of the visit for her communist
hosts.
   Official media in Poland gave the visit heavy coverage, but
pointedly omitted any mention of Mrs. Thatcher's contacts with
Walesa on the national TV news Friday night.
   At a state banquet Thursday night she told Jaruzelski that it was
vital he negotiate with oppostion groups including Solidarity.
   The Solidarity leadership responded with gratitude.
   ``It was beautiful what she said,'' said historian Bronislaw
Geremek, one of Walesa's closest advisers. ``For this speech Mrs.
Thatcher gets a great deal of thanks from us.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
