<DOCNO> AP881104-0156 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-11-04-88 1530EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u p AM-Quayle     11-04 0666</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Quayle,660</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Quayle Says Massachusetts' Financial Woes Show Dukakis Unable to
Manage</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Political Rdp Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MERRILL HARTSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MONROE, La. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Sen. Dan Quayle on Friday cited a nearly $190
million overdraft in Massachusetts current bank account as evidence
that Democratic presidential nominee Michael Dukakis is ill-equipped
to manage the federal government.
   Campaigning for support in Louisiana, where the energy industry
has been beset by hard times in recent years, Quayle pounced on the
revelation that Massachusetts tax receipts had fallen considerably
below expectations, causing the multimillion-dollar shortfall.
   ``We thought it was bad when Massachusetts had to borrow another
$600 million in the first months of the fiscal year just to stay
afloat,'' the Republican vice presidential candidate told a
flag-waving crowd gathered in a park here.
   Quayle said that ``despite the totally false denials made by
Governor Dukakis in his last debate with George Bush, we knew the
fiscal situation was bad.''
   ``The American people are not only just beginning to find out how
bad it really is, but they are finding, as we are, that the fiscal
situation in Massachusetts is a time bomb set to explode in the
faces of its citizens,'' he said.
   Dukakis, questioned about the state's fiscal problems, told
reporters at New York's LaGuardia Airport: ``We don't have deficit.
What we have is 10 balanced budgets in a row.''
   Quayle delivered the broadside a day after accusing Dukakis of
making ``phony'' tough statements about cracking down on drug
abusers, saying the government had been disengenous because Dukakis
opposes such anti-crime measures as capital punishment for drug
kingpins and mandatory prison sentences for drug-related felonies.
   ``This week, the citizens of Massachusets awoke to find out that
their state's bank accounts have been overdrawn up to $190 million
for the past 30 days,'' he said. ``So it turns out that Governor
Dukakis has been writing hot checks to keep his state's finances
afloat.''
   The state constitution of Massachusetts requires a balanced
budget. But the amount of tax receipts coming into the state's
coffers have been considerably less than anticipated by the office
of state treasurer Robert Crane. Consequently, the balance in the
current accounts fell into arrears by nearly $190 million.
   Governors faced with less than expected state tax revenues often
issue what are called revenue anticipation bonds _ meaning they
borrow money against revenues they expect to come in subsequently
and thus close such gaps in bank accounts.
   But in the Massachusetts situation, state officials evidently
opted to pay the interest on the $190 million overdraft rather than
face a higher prevailing interest rate on the floating of such bonds.
   The state has over $1 billion in separate accounts, but these
monies are untouchable; they involve funds raised through other bond
issues for such things as highway and capital improvement projects.
   Sen. Lloyd Bentsen, the Democratic vice presidential candidate,
had used a ``hot checks'' charge against Quayle during their Oct. 13
debate in Omaha, Neb., saying the Reagan administration had allowed
the federal budget to fall more than $200 billion in arrears.
   ``You know, if you let me write $200 billion worth of hot checks
every year I could give you an illusion of prosperity, too,'' he
told Quayle.
   Under the Reagan administration the federal debt has more than
tripled, to more than $2.63 trillion.
   Quayle said that Dukakis ``likes to talk about a Massachusetts
miracle. But the only miracle involving Massachusetts will be the
one he needs to get out of the mess he's created for his state.''
   En route to the airport from the Louisiana rally Quayle stopped
at a predominantly black elementary school and visited with several
children, engaging in light banter and talking about opportunities
for Americans under Republican rule.
   He was traveling on to Alabama later to address a rally on the
campus of Auburn University before returning to Washington. Quayle
will make campaign appearances Saturday in Maryland and West
Virginia but no schedule had been announced for Sunday.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
