<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Cambodia     11-04 0456</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Cambodia,0470</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Sihanouk, Hun Sen Meet Monday To Negotiate Future for Cambodia</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MICHAEL GOLDSMITH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PARIS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Cambodia's Prince Norodom Sihanouk and
Vietnamese-backed Prime Minister Hun Sen meet in France next week to
try to agree on how to organize a future Cambodia without the Khmer
Rouge.
   Main absentees at the new talks, scheduled for Monday in
Fere-en-Tardenois, 70 miles northeast of Paris, will be the Khmer
Rouge. The movement caused the deaths of a quarter of Cambodia's 8
million people in an agrarian form of communist revolution that
began 1975.
   In 1978, Vietnam invaded Cambodia and ousted the Khmer Rouge.
   The Sihanouk-Hun Sen meeting, the third of its kind here in the
past year, was to begin Saturday in Paris. Hun Sen asked for the
delay, according to a spokesman for Sihanouk who volunteered no
reasons.
   The non-communist international community refuses to recognize
the Vietamese-backed regime that has run Cambodia for 10 years.
   But Sihanouk, who ruled 1941-1970, has made little headway in
arranging an acceptable coalition excluding the Khmer Rouge. He has
resigned ``once and for all'' as leader of the anti-Vietnamese
coalition because it included a Khmer Rouge element.
   The Hun Sen regime has the backing of the Soviet Union while the
Khmer Rouge _ the biggest and most effective force fighting the
Vietnamese _ retain the backing of China.
   Hun Sen and Sihanouk first met in Fere-en-Tardenois last December
and in St.Germain-en-Laye in the New Year. They came ``closer than
ever to agreement,'' said Son Sann, prime minister in Sihanouk's
resistance government.
   In reality the three parties remain far apart. Not even a meeting
between high-level Chinese and Russian diplomats broke the deadlock.
   Sihanouk has met most Western leaders, including President
Reagan, British Prime Minister Margaret Thatcher and French
President Francois Mitterrand. They see in him the main hope for
agreement on an acceptable Cambodian government, which he would lead.
   Sihanouk is demanding the Hun Sen government step down before
free elections, while Hun Sen wants the elections to come before any
change to his regime. Neither side has realistically tackled the
Khmer Rouge problem.
   The Khmer Rouge are believed to have at least 40,000 well-armed
men in the field, compared with Sihanouk's 15,000. When Vietnam's
120,000 regular soldiers leave Cambodia as promised, by 1990, the
Khmer Rouge surely will try to make a comeback.
   To prevent this, the United States gives Sihanouk open and covert
aid of $20 million a year, though reluctantly because it is afraid
of upsetting China. Southeast Asian countries, including Malaya and
Singapore, also help Sihanouk.
   The Khmer Rouge are the only crucial pawn China still holds in
the struggle for Cambodia. To abandon them, the Chinese leadership
expects concessions from Moscow.

</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP881104-0158 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-11-04-88 1815EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i AM-HamadiTrial     11-04 0550</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Hamadi Trial,0571</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Former Hostage Says He Received Mystery Phone Call Before Trial</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By GEORGE BOEHMER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>FRANKFURT, West Germany (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A former TWA hostage said Friday
he received a mysterious telephone call from Beirut about a month
before testifying at the trial of confessed hijacker Mohammed Ali
Hamadi.
   Ralf Traugott, who was aboard the plane hijacked in 1985, also
described how the Shiite Moslem calmly said, ``This is the man we
killed,'' after he read an article about the American Navy diver
slain aboard the TWA jetliner.
   Traugott, 36, a German-born American citizen, said he received a
telephone call about four weeks ago in which a man identified
himself as ``Mr. Hamadi'' and said he was calling from Beirut.
   ``I thought it was kind of strange,'' Traugott said. ``The man on
the other end of the line said `Hello Mr. Ralf.'''
   ``I said, `Who's this?' and he said, `Mr. Hamadi. This is Beirut,
Lebanon calling,''' Traugott said. The man then hung up, he said.
   Hamadi comes from a family of 11 children. One of his brothers,
Abdul-Hadi, is the security chief for Hezbollah, or Party of God, a
radical Shiite Moslem group backed by Iran and believed to be
holding the foreign hostages in Lebanon.
   Hamadi has denied being a member of Hezbollah, but has admitted
to taking part in the hijacking of TWA Flight 847, which was seized
on an Athens-to-Rome flight and diverted to Beirut and Algiers.
Thirty-nine Americans were held hostage for 17 days and U.S. Navy
diver Robert Stethem, 23, of Waldorf, Md., was shot and thrown out
of the plane to die on the tarmac at Beirut airport.
   Hamadi is charged with murder and air piracy.
   Traugott showed the court a Lebanese newspaper, An-Nahar, dated
June 16, 1985.
   The newspaper included photographs of the hijacked plane and of
Stethem's body on the tarmac. Traugott said Hamadi had been reading
the newspaper aboard the plane.
   ``I asked him what was in it,'' Traugott said. ``He said, `This
is the man we killed.' I asked him, `Did you shoot him?'''
   ``He said, `No, my friend shot him,''' Traugott said. ``He said
it very nonchalantly, like it was no big deal.''
   Court documents have identified Hamadi's accomplice as Hassan
Ezzeddine, who is at large.
   When he asked Hamadi why the hijackers shot Stethem, Traugott
said Hamadi replied: ``This man was a Marine.''
   Other witnesses have also testified the hijackers apparently
mistook Stethem for a U.S. Marine.
   Traugott said he did not witness the shooting. ``I don't think
anyone saw the shooting,'' he said.
   The slain diver's parents, Richard and Patricia Stethem, watched
attentively as Traugott described the scene. They have followed the
trial regularly since it started in July.
   Traugott told the court that Hamadi held a gun and a grenade
against his head and told him he was a member of Hezbollah and
trained in Iran.
   When Traugott told him he was not afraid, Hamadi ``twisted the
pistol against my forehead and I said, `OK, I am afraid,''' the
witness said.
   Chief Judge Heiner Mueckenberger opened Friday's session by
announcing Hamadi's parents arrived from their home in Beirut and
were expected to testify Tuesday.
   Hamadi was arrested at Frankfurt airport in January 1987 when
customs officials found liquid explosives in his luggage.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP881104-0159 </DOCNO>
