<FILEID>AP-NR-11-04-88 1957EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r p AM-WildernessPolitics     11-04 0655</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Wilderness Politics,0670</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Reagan Pocket Veto of Wilderness Bill Could Work Against GOP, Dems
Say</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MIKE DENNISON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>HELENA, Mont. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Reagan's decision to pocket veto a
wilderness bill that would have released 4.1 million acres of land
for development could backfire against state GOP candidates, say
hopeful Democrats.
   But Republicans, who sought the veto claiming the bill did not
free up enough land, are looking to harvest votes from Reagan's
action _ only the second such veto in his eight years in office.
   Reagan announced Wednesday he would not sign a bill designating
1.43 million acres of roadless national forest land in Montana as
federally protected wilderness. It was only the second time he has
vetoed a state wilderness bill. He has signed more than 30.
   More than 6 million acres of Montana wilderness have been closed
to development because of federal court decisions in the late 1970s
and early 1980s. A wilderness bill from Congress is needed to
release any of this land for other use; the bill vetoed by Reagan,
by protecting 1.43 million acres, would have freed up the remaining
land.
   The White House denied the veto decision was political. But first
word of the veto came not from the White House but from Conrad
Burns, the GOP challenger to Sen. John Melcher, D-Mont., who
sponsored the wilderness legislation.
   Polls show Burns in a close race with Melcher, and Burns
campaigned heavily in recent days on what he said would have been
the legislation's negative impact on Montana jobs.
   ``As our next senator, I will hold hearings across Montana on
this critical issue and work to pass wilderness legislation that is
in the best interest of all Montanans,'' he said in a statement
released with the veto announcement.
   Burns and the Republican candidates for the state's two
congressional seats all asked Reagan to veto the measure, saying it
would cost jobs by locking up too much land as wilderness and
wilderness study areas, putting miners and loggers out of work.
   Reagan offered the same explanation in his veto message and also
noted the bill designated almost twice the amount of wilderness
recommended by the U.S. Forest Service.
   White House spokesman Marlin Fitzwater said Thursday the veto
resulted from ``a variety of economic and environmental reasons,''
not politics.
   But Democrats and environmentalists said the move was political
manipulation, pointing out that nearly all wilderness bills signed
by Reagan have had more wilderness acreage than recommended by the
Forest Service.
   ``This whole veto is simply part of an effort to reduce the
possibility that there might be more Democrats in the U.S. Senate
next session,'' said Sherm Janke of Bozeman, chairman of the Montana
chapter of the Sierra Club. ``The real reason is to embarrass the
candidacies of those who have supported the wilderness legislation.''
   Some Democrats predicted a backlash, noting the issue of
wilderness preservation in Montana has been debated for a decade,
with this year's bill the first potential resolution.
   ``We're looking at a process that's been going on for 13 years,
and with a lack of a stroke of a pen, Ronald Reagan has just dumped
all that in a dumpster,'' said Ron Richards, a Melcher aide. ``I
would think there's going to be some resentment among some folks.''
   Democrats say releasing the 4.1 million acres is needed to
stabilize Montana's mining and timber industries, which are
recovering from recession in the early 1980s.
   Tom Daubert, press secretary for the Dukakis-Bentsen campaign in
Montana, expressed hope that the veto might convince more Montanans
to vote against Vice President and GOP presidential nominee George
Bush, who Democrats say advised Reagan on the veto.
   ``George Bush has added insult to injury here,'' Daubert said.
``We've had eight years of voodoo economics, and the icing on the
cake is prolonged instability in the mining and timber industries. I
think Montanans know that jobs are at stake here.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP881104-0163 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-11-04-88 2006EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a AM-SkagwayLead     11-04 0356</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Skagway Lead,0366</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>High Lead Levels Found in Alaska Town; Blood Tests Planned</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BRIAN S. AKRE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JUNEAU, Alaska (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Tests on dust and soil in the southeast
Alaska town of Skagway show lead levels 560 times above normal, and
officials are offering free blood tests for all residents.
   Officials stressed Thursday there was no cause for alarm and no
evidence that any of the town's 790 residents were poisoned.
   The lead is believed to be linked to an ore terminal at Skagway
harbor operated by Bowhead Equipment Co. of Seattle and owned by
White Pass Transportation Ltd.
   Bowhead stores and loads ore concentrates, mostly lead and zinc
sulfide, that are mined in the Yukon by Curragh Resources Inc. of
Canada. The powdery ore is shipped from Skagway to Japan, Korea,
Europe and Australia.
   The normal level of lead in Skagway's soil is about 50 parts per
million, said Dick Stokes, southeast regional supervisor for the
state Department of Environmental Conservation. The tests showed
lead levels as high as 28,000 parts per million, said Jim Cronin, a
consulting engineer with a company hired by Bowhead.
   However, officials said they did not know what level of lead in
soil poses a threat.
   ``It's very dependent upon the form of the material, the location
of the material and the potential pathways to human exposure,'' said
Carl Lautenberger of the U.S. Environmental Protection Agency.
   Until 1982 the ore was transported to the terminal by rail. Since
1986, when the terminal reopened, the ore has been taken through
town on trucks.
   Terminal employees have undergone tests for several years to
comply with federal safety rules.
   Children, pregnant women and families of workers at an ore
terminal at Skagway Harbor are most at risk of lead poisoning, said
Dr. Katherine Kelly of the state Health and Social Services
Department.
   Lead poisoning can cause headaches, anemia, colic, paralysis and
cramps. It also can stunt growth in children and cause birth defects.
   Cronin said soil tests also revealed high levels of zinc, which
is less of a health concern, and lower levels of mercury, cadmium,
copper and silver.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
