<1ST_LINE>r p AM-JacksonThreat     11-04 0364</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Jackson Threat,0374</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Woman Sentenced in Threat to Jesse Jackson</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LORI DODGE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ST. LOUIS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The ex-wife of a man sentenced to two years in
prison for threatening the life of Jesse Jackson received a 20-month
sentence Friday in connection with the case.
   Tammy Williams, 27, of Washington, Mo., had pleaded guilty to a
charge of possessing an unregistered automatic weapon in exchange
for the government dropping charges of intimidating and threatening
a witness.
   U.S. District Judge Edward Filippine placed Mrs. Williams on
three years' supervised release following her prison term and
ordered to pay $50. He also ordered her to enter a substance abuse
program during that period.
   Filippine said Mrs. Williams, jailed since May, would be credited
with the time she has already served.
   In seeking leniency, defense lawyer Cynthia Short told the court
that Mrs. Williams had divorced Londell Williams, effective Oct. 31.
   ``I think that signifies her willingness and desire to start
again,'' Short said. The lawyer asked that her client be sentenced
at the low end of the scale so that she could ``put the last six
months behind her.''
   ``I ask that you return me to my children as soon as possible so
I can raise them, because they are without parents right now,'' Mrs.
Williams told Filippine.
   Mrs. Williams faced a maximum penalty of 24 months in prison and
$30,000 in fines.
   Her former husband was sentenced Monday to 24 months in prison
and ordered to pay $100 on charges of threatening Jackson's life and
possessing the automatic rifle, which authorities found buried in a
wooded area near Washington. Williams, 30, had pleaded guilty to
those charges in August.
   Williams, who has said that he grew up with ``prejudices against
anything that isn't white,'' allegedly told a government informant
that he planned to kill Jackson, who was then seeking the Democratic
presidential nomination.
   In a taped conversation with the informant, Williams said the
black civil rights leader should be killed because he was ``trying
to make a fool out of us white people.''
   The Williamses were arrested May 13 at their apartment in
Washington, about 50 miles west of St. Louis.
</TEXT>
