<1ST_LINE>r a AM-Fernald-EPA     11-04 0275</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Fernald-EPA,0284</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Ohio Congressman Wants Fernald Site on Superfund List</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CINCINNATI (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An Ohio congressman on Friday asked the U.S.
Environmental Protection Agency to add the Fernald uranium
processing plant to the nation's Superfund cleanup program of toxic
waste sites.
   Democratic Rep. Thomas Luken, a persistent critic of the Fernald
plant, said putting it on the cleanup list may be the only way to
pressure its owner, the U.S. Department of Energy, into cleaning up
radioactive contamination at the plant's 1,050-acre site in Fernald,
18 miles northwest of Cincinnati.
   The plant, formally known as the Feed Materials Production
Center, processes uranium for the government's production of nuclear
weapons, which are produced elsewhere.
   Nearly 13 million pounds of uranium-containing waste have been
dumped into the environment since the plant opened in 1951,
according to the Ohio Environmental Protection Agency. The DOE has
admitted the dumping and says it plans to clean up the area.
   ``To make Fernald a Superfund site may be the only way we can get
the ball rolling on cleaning up the Fernald site,'' Luken said.
   The request will be directed to EPA Administrator Lee Thomas.
   In Washington, Energy Department spokeswoman Gail Bradshaw said
her department was unaware of Luken's request. She said other Energy
Department sites have already been added to the Superfund list.
   ``I don't think we'd have any comment other than it is our intent
to bring them all into compliance,'' Ms. Bradshaw said of Luken's
proposal.
   Residents near the Fernald plant and the state of Ohio have
separate lawsuits pending, alleging that the plant has polluted its
environment with radioactive materials and created a public health
threat.
</TEXT>
