<1ST_LINE>u i AM-Britain-Thatcher     11-04 0475</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Britain-Thatcher,0487</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>British Press Praise Thatcher Boldness</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Poland-Thatcher, Bjt</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Prime Minister Margaret Thatcher's huge reception
from the Polish people and her outspoken calls to recognize
Solidarity and pull down the Berlin Wall won praise and front-page
headlines in Britain.
   Mrs. Thatcher's boldness, and in particular her statement that
economic cooperation with the West would come only when basic human
rights were a way of life in Poland, surprised even her supporters
in the media.
   The pro-Thatcher Times of London called her statement in Warsaw
on Thursday ``remarkarble,'' saying it showed ``greater boldness
than expected.'' The Daily Telegraph called it ``forthright'' and
The Independent said it was ``a remarkably hard-line speech to the
Polish government.''
   The tabloid Daily Express, which supports Mrs. Thatcher's
Conservative government, had a front-page headline saying:
``Thatcher Freedom Speech Is Censored.''
   It said by the time her speech was beamed to the Polish people on
television, ``out had gone all the references to the Berlin Wall,
the Helsinki agreement, human rights, Solidarity and Warsaw Pact
chemical weapons.''
   The Daily Mirror, which supports the socialist opposition Labor
Party, had a brief story on page 2, focusing on Mrs. Thatcher
shopping in a Warsaw market. It then reported here comments on
Western aid.
   The Times said: ``Mrs. Thatcher's words were clearly aimed at a
much wider audience. It was an important address on East-West
relations significantly timed at the moment when the U.S.
presidential election leaves her as the dominant voice in the West.''
   Under the headline ``Thatcher Preaches Polish Pluralism,'' the
liberal Guardian said: ``Mrs. Thatcher has decided to deliver a
magisterial lesson to both sides in deeply divided Poland, warning
the government that it must give its people freedom, but preparing
to tell Lech Walesa that strikes offer no solution.''
   The tabloids focused more on her reception. The conservative
Daily Mail said in its front-page headline: ``Thousands Cheer Maggie
on her Polish Pilgrimage.'' The independent daily Today, under the
headline, ``Poles Sob as Maggie Calls for Freedom,'' said:
``Cheering crowds mobbed Premier Maggie Thatcher yesterday as she
made a triumphant visit to Warsaw.''
   The British Broadcasting Corp. quoted Neil Kinnock, leader of the
Labor Party, as saying Friday that Mrs. Thatcher's exhortation for
the Polish government to talk with Solidarity was insincere because
Mrs. Thatcher herself did not talk to any sections of society.
   The Guardian said in an editorial Friday that the Department of
Trade and Industry had suddenly postponed an expected announcement
about the future of a British shipyard under threat of closure.
   A department spokesman, unidentified in keeping with British
practice, said only that discussions were under way with the
shipbuilders.
   The paper said the alleged delay was likely ``a political move to
avoid embarrassment for Mrs. Thatcher'' when she went to Gdansk,
where the government has announced it is closing the Lenin shipyard.
</TEXT>
