<1ST_LINE>r i AM-BRF--MoneyLaundering 1stLd-Writethru a0609 11-04 0300</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-BRF--Money Laundering, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0609,0303</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>$1 Billion Reported Laundered by Drug Ring</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: UPDATES throughout with comments from Swiss authorities. No
pickup.</NOTE>
<DATELINE>ZURICH, Switzerland (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Swiss authorities said Friday that
billions of dollars may have been laundered through Switzerland for
a Middle Eastern drug ring, and they said nine people were arrested.
   A statement from the Ticino state prosecutor's office said those
arrested included six Lebanese, one Syrian, one Swiss of Turkish
origin and one Turk.
   It said two Lebanese were in investigative custody, accused of
falsifying documents, complicity in fraud and violating Swiss
narcotics laws. The others were released on bail. The suspects were
not identified.
   The communique also said authorities seized 220 pounds of heroin
in Bellinzona, capital of Ticino state, in connection with the
money-laundering investigation. It said the drugs were seized Feb.
24, 1987.
   Ticino state prosecutor Dick Marty said authorities have evidence
that ``billions of Swiss francs'' in drug money may have been
laundered by the ring.
   The prosecutor said the money was carried to Switzerland by
couriers from the Middle East and the United States. It said the
investigation was ``unusually complex.''
   The comments came in response to a Swiss newspaper report that a
Lebanese-Turkish ring had $1 billion laundered through Swiss banks
and foreign-controlled companies in Switzerland.
   The Zurich newspaper Tages-Anzeiger said four Lebanese nationals
brought ``suitcases full of cash'' into Switzerland before they were
arrested in July.
   Zurich District Attorney Peter Gasser confirmed that four men
were arrested in Zurich in July. He also said that accounts held
with several big Swiss banks had been ordered frozen and that
``funds of suspicious origin'' were seized. He did not elaborate.
   Money laundering is not yet a criminal offense in Switzerland
unless the funds are used for criminal purposes.
</TEXT>
