<2ND_LINE>AM-Costa Rica-Refugees,0250</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>More Than 500 Nicaraguans Arrive in Costa Rica After Joan</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JUAN MALTES</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SAN JOSE, Costa Rica (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   More than 500 Nicaraguans fleeing the
hurricane-devastated Atlantic coast have sought refuge in Costa Rica
in recent days, the government said Friday.
   ``Immigration officials are expecting a landslide of new
Nicaraguan refugees in the next weeks and that concerns us because
all the refugee camps in Costa Rica are already filled with
Nicaraguans,'' said Luis Alberto Cordero, an aide to President Oscar
Arias.
   Hurricane Joan destroyed the port of Bluefields as it blasted
into Nicaragua on Oct. 24, killing more than 100 people, leaving
another 200,000 homeless and striking another blow at Nicaragua's
already devastated economy.
   Cordero said the new arrivals are mainly from the Bluefields
area, which is about 200 miles north of the Costa Rican port of
Puerto Limon. He did not say whether they came by land or by sea.
   More than 10,000 Nicaraguans live in Costa Rican refugee camps
run by the U.N. High Commissioner for Refugees. But there are
actually more than 200,000 Nicaraguans in Costa Rica, according to
Carlos Jose Arce, chief of the Costa Rican immigration office.
   ``We are facing one of the strongest floods of inmigrants and we
are not prepared to receive them, because we have our own
problems,'' Cordero said.
   Hurricane Joan's torrential rains also hit Costa Rica, destroying
at least 1,500 towns and villages and flooding many more.
</TEXT>
