<1ST_LINE>r a AM-Tourist-DeathPenalty     11-04 0354</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Tourist-Death Penalty,0364</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>German Tourist Gets Death Penalty In Insurance Slaying Of
Girlfriend</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MIAMI (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A West German was sentenced Friday to die in
Florida's electric chair for the murder of his girlfriend in Miami
Beach more than a year ago.
   After hearing his sentence, 44-year-old Dieter Riechmann told
Dade Circuit Judge Harold Solomon: ``I was found guilty but there
was not one shred of evidence that proved my guilt. I don't accept
any kind of penalty _ the death penalty or imprisonment. ... I am
sure the verdict will not stand up under appeal.''
   Riechmann was found guilty of first-degree murder on Aug. 12 in
the shooting of Kirsten Kischnick, 31, on Oct. 25, 1987.
   Prosecutors said the murder was committed to collect more than $1
million in insurance.
   Riechmann had claimed that a pedestrian shot Ms. Kischnick in the
head with a .38-caliber pistol after the two stopped their car to
ask directions in downtown Miami.
   He said he then drove frantically around Miami and finally to
Miami Beach looking for a policeman. But police and prosecutors
doubted the story.
   The state noted that a .38-caliber weapon similar to the one used
in the killing was found in Riechmann's luggage.
   On Aug. 30, by a 9-3 vote, the jury recommended the death penalty.
   In a plea for his client's life, attorney Edward Carhart said
that in the penalty phase of the trial, evidence was presented that
the motive for the crime was insurance, but there was no proof that
there was ``cold calculation and premeditation'' and that there was
``a question that he did it for the insurance.''
   Carhart also said he was ``troubled by the fact that the jury
didn't realize the serious possibility that a mistake has been
made.''
   He then asked the judge to overrule the jury's recommendation and
sentence Riechmann to life imprisonment with no possibility of
parole.
   In sentencing Riechmann to death, Solomon said he had carefully
considered the testimony.
   ``I find that the aggravating circumstances outweigh the
mitigating circumstances,'' he said, ``and that the crime was
committed in a cold, calculating and premeditated manner.''
</TEXT>
