<FILEID>AP-NR-11-04-88 2001EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r p AM-Dukakis-Hostages     11-04 0310</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Dukakis-Hostages,310</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Dukakis Says He Would Talk to Terrorists</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Democratic presidential candidate Michael
Dukakis said Friday there's nothing wrong with talking to terrorists
holding U.S. hostages as long as no concessions are made.
   The Reagan administration has said it will not negotiate directly
with groups holding Americans hostage in Lebanon, although public
investigation of the Iran-Contra affair showed that secret deals
were made with Iranian officials who apparently had influence with
the kidnappers.
   ``I've never said that you don't negotiate,'' Dukakis said in an
interview on NBC's ``Today.'' ``You talk, you make every effort to
get those hostages back home, but you never make concessions to the
hostage takers.''
   ``Mike Dukakis is going to work as hard as he possibly can,'' he
said. ``First to have an anti-terrorism policy that's real and,
secondly, to do everything he can to get those hostages and reunite
those families, but never, never do the kind of thing that we did
when we traded arms to the ayatollah.''
   He said the decision to trade arms to Iran during the Reagan-Bush
administration was ``one of the worst things that ever happened.''
   ``You can't make concessions to terrorists if you're serious
about fighting terrorism and stopping this hostage taking,'' Dukakis
said.
   Bush, in his presidential campaign, has spoken of a need to
strike back at terrorists. He said in the first presidential debate
that the administration has made ``vast improvements in our
anti-terrorism'' since the arms-for-hostages dealing.
   On efforts for peace between Israel and its Arab neighbors,
Dukakis said he might travel to the Middle East as president ``if I
thought it would make a difference,'' but he expressed a preference
for leaving such talks to his secretary of state.
   ``There has been no progress for eight years, since the Camp
David Accords,'' he said. ``We're going to make it a priority.''
</TEXT>
