<FILEID>AP-NR-11-04-88 2001EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i AM-CrystalNight     11-04 0383</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Crystal Night,0393</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Germans Responsible For Crystal Night Never Punished, Lawyer Says</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TERRENCE PETTY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BONN, West Germany (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Many former Nazis are still living who
never were ``brought to account'' for ransacking Jewish synagogues
and businesses in a 1938 pogrom known as ``Crystal Night,'' an
expert on war crimes said.
   ``You will find hardly anyone who has been prosecuted who
participated in Crystal Night,'' Robert M.W. Kempner was quoted as
saying in a newsletter published Friday by the opposition Social
Democratic Party.
   ``Many people who were involved are living among us and receiving
social assistance,'' said the 89-year-old Kempner, a deputy
prosecutor at the 1945-46 postwar trial of Nazi war criminals in
Nuremberg.
   On the night of Nov. 9-10, 1938, Nazi sympathizers destroyed more
than 250 synagogues and 7,500 businesses across Germany. Dozens of
Jews died in the pogrom, known as ``Crystal Night'' for the
shattered glass left on the streets. ``Many of those responsible for
the pogrom were not brought to account,'' Kempner was quoted as
saying.
   He did not say whether he knew of any individuals who were
involved in the pogrom and are still alive.
   Kempner, a lawyer who worked in the German Interior Ministry and
lost his job after Nazi leader Adolf Hitler came to power in 1933,
left Germany in 1935 and moved to the United States. He returned
after World War II, participated in the Nuremberg trials as a
prosecutor and now has a residence in Frankfurt.
   Also on Friday, the Social Democratic Party announced that two
leading West German politicians plan to visit East Germany and
Poland to commemorate the 50th anniversary of Crystal Night.
   Gerhard Jahn, a Social Democrat and member of Parliament, is to
participate in the Nov. 9 anniversary observance of Crystal Night to
be held in the East German Parliament. Jahn was invited by the East
German government, the Social Democrats said.
   The main Crystal Night anniversary in West Germany will take
place in Frankfurt on the same day and will be attended by President
Richard von Weizsaecker and Chancellor Helmut Kohl.
   Another leading Social Democrat, Annemarie Renger, is to lay a
wreath on Monday at the site of the Nazi concentration camp in
Auschwitz.
   An estimated 6 million Jews were killed in the Nazi Holocaust.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
