<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Yugoslavia     11-04 0227</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Yugoslavia,0234</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Four Leaders Resign in Troubled Province</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By IVAN STEFANOVIC</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BELGRADE, Yugoslavia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Four high-ranking officials resigned
Friday from their posts in a province where Serbian nationalists are
demanding a purge of the Communist leadership, an official report
said.
   The resignations brought to five the number of members of
Kosovo's ruling Presidium that have stepped down after a meeting
Wednesday. At that session, Communist leaders of the republic of
Serbia, which includes Kosovo, argued over Serbian demands.
   Serbian Communist party leader Slobodan Milosevic blames Kosovo's
leadership for tension between the province's ethnic Albanian
majority and its Slav minority. Milosevic is trying to amend
Yugoslavia's constitution to give Serbia more control over Kosovo,
which is nominally autonomous.
   Mass rallies over the past few months, combined with labor
strikes over economic demands, have brought down the leadership in
Serbia's other province, Vojvodina.
   The news agency Tanjug said Milan Gvozdic, a Slav, stepped down
from Kosovo's 13-man Presidium. Two ethnic Albanians, Ekrem Arifi
and Rahman Dedai, and another Slav, Vojislav Zajic, later announced
their resignations, Tanjug said.
   Presidium member Uros Seslija, also a Slav, resigned Thursday
night.
   Tanjug did not say why they resigned, but indicated further
resignations could be expected. It was unclear if it was refering to
Azem Vlasi, Kosovo's most prominent ethnic Albanian leader and the
main target of Serbian complaints.
</TEXT>
