<1ST_LINE>r w AM-Shultz-Award     11-04 0237</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Shultz-Award,230</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Secretary of State Honored for Stand on Human Rights</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A major Jewish organization, B'nai B'rith, on
Friday presented a menorah to Secretary of State George P. Shultz in
recognition of his support for human rights and opposition to
terrorism.
   Shultz accepted the award from Seymour Reich, the president of
B'nai B'rith, at a State Department ceremony.
   Reich said the menorah, an ancient Jewish symbol of freedom,
``symbolizes for us all that you have done as secretary of state in
behalf of human rights everywhere, in behalf of seeking peace, not
only in the Middle East but throughout the world, of facing the
Soviets and determining it was appropriate to engage in an INF
(Intermediate-Range Nuclear Forces) treaty.''
   Also, the B'nai B'rith president said, ``We are very proud of
your stand on terrorism, something that you have condemned publicly
and courageously and emotionally.''
   Shultz said he would add the menorah to the one in his home that
he lights at Christmas, Easter and on other holidays.
   ``I have lived with a menorah practically all my life,'' Shultz
said.
   He explained that his mother kept in her dining room a menorah
she had inherited from an uncle, an Episcopalian priest who
displayed the Jewish symbol as an expression of his ecumenical
convictions.
   B'nai B'rith is a service organization that maintains ties with
Jews in 41 countries and supports civil liberties for minority
groups.
</TEXT>
