<1ST_LINE>r i AM-PrinceCharles-Ruling     11-04 0168</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Prince Charles-Ruling,0173</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Death of Prince Charles' Ski Companion Ruled Accident</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A coroner's inquest ruled Friday that Maj. Hugh
Lindsay died accidentally in an avalanche in the Swiss Alps that
nearly engulfed Prince Charles and others in their ski group in
March.
   The inquest said that although the group probably caused the
avalanche as it skied off the main trail, no individual was at fault.
   Lindsay, a 34-year-old career army officer and former aide to
Queen Elizabeth II, was skiing with the party at the Swiss resort of
Klosters on March 10 when the avalanche happened.
   Charles, the 39-year-old heir to the British throne, and several
others skiied clear and escaped injury.
   But Lindsay and another skier, Patti Palmer-Tomkinson, were swept
away. She suffered broken legs and lung injuries.
   Coroner John Burton recorded the verdict after a 40-minute
inquest in which he read an official Swiss report. It said Lindsay
was probably killed by a block of ice that hit him on the head.
</TEXT>
