<1ST_LINE>u p AM-Reagan 1stLd-Writethru a0637 11-04 0769</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Reagan, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0637,770</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Precede PALOS HILLS, Ill.</HEAD>
<HEAD>Reagan Urges Support for Bush; Signs Genocide Treaty</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Political Rdp Bjt</HEAD>
<NOTE>EDs: TOP 9 grafs new to UPDATE with Reagan's comments at New Jersey
event; picks up 10 graf pvs, bgng, `The Democrats,' EDITS to
tighten.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By SUSANNE M. SCHAFER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>VOORHEES TOWNSHIP, N.J. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Reagan accused the
Democrats Friday of ``a new lack of civility'' and portrayed Michael
Dukakis as an inept governor who runs a state that is ``getting
sloppier and sloppier by the day.''
   The president campaigned for votes on behalf of the GOP ticket in
the battleground states of Illinois and New Jersey, mixing
get-out-the vote pitches with a Chicago bill-signing ceremony making
genocide a crime.
   In an afternoon stop at the Main Street Mall in this suburban
southern New Jersey community, Reagan bemoaned the mud-slingling
that has marked the Senate campaign between Sen. Frank R.
Lautenberg, who is seeking a second term, and his Republican
challenger Pete Dawkins.
   The match has been one of the most rancorous in the nation _
Dawkins has accused the senator of being a left-winger with a record
of little achievement while Lautenberg painted his rival, a one-time
Army brigadier general, as a carpetbagger.
   Reagan described both Dukakis and Lautenberg as ``far-out''
liberals who oppose a strong defense, tough judges and budget cuts.
   Reagan added: ``We've seen a lack of civility creeping into the
way the opposition in Congress operates.''
   Reagan made no mention of the charges voiced repeatedly by
Dukakis and his running mate, Sen. Lloyd Bentsen, D-Texas, that Bush
has pursued a campaign based on distortions and lies.
   In the same speech, Reagan did not mention Dukakis by name, but
he charged the Massachusetts governor with allowing his state to
rank ``an abysmal 30th'' in the annual rate of job growth in 1986
and 1987, and with overdrawing his state's bank ``by as much as $190
million for a month.''
   ``The Massachusetts mess is getting sloppier and sloppier by the
day,'' Reagan said. ``... You tell me, who's on your side, that
liberal governor or George Bush?''
   Earlier in the day, Reagan turned one of Dukakis' favorite
slogans to GOP use in a speech to several hundred GOP partisans at
Moraine Valley Community College about 20 miles from downtown
Chicago.
   The Democrats, Reagan argued, ``say they're on your side, but
that's just an empty promise. They promise _ but you know we
deliver.''
   ``If you want to know who's on the side of the little guy, well,
I'll tell you, it's the big guy, the big guy from Texas,'' Reagan
said.
   In his prepared remarks about the genocide treaty, Reagan made no
mention of the fact that U.S. participation in the pact had been
held up for nearly 40 years, primarily by a group of hard-core
conservatives unwilling to submit, as they argued, to a treaty that
sublimated American interests to an international pact.
   Others argued the language of the pact contained uncertainties
that could undermine the Constitution.
   While the United States signed the Genocide Convention in 1949,
legislation implementing the pact didn't pass the U.S. Senate until
last month.
   The bill makes genocide a crime, punishable by life in prison,
and defines it as the intentional destruction of national, ethnic,
racial or religious groups, in whole or in part.
   ``We gather today to bear witness to the past and learn from its
awful example to make sure we are not condemned to relive its
crimes,'' Reagan said at an impromptu signing ceremony staged at
Chicago's O'Hare International Airport.
   Instead of holding the ceremony in Washington on Thursday, as
White House officials had once indicated might be the case, Reagan's
schedulers opted for the Chicago site, only miles from the suburb of
Skokie, Ill., the community rocked by turmoil when right-wing Nazi
enthusiasts won the right to march in the streets of heavily Jewish
neighborhoods.
   The treaty marked a triumph for Sen. William Proxmire, D-Wis.,
who had given more than 3,000 speeches over the past 19 years in
favor of the treaty. Fitzwater said the White House invited Proxmire
to the ceremony, but the senator was unable to attend.
   On Saturday, Reagan travels to the Detroit area for a Bush-Quayle
rally at Macomb Community College and to Mesquite, Texas, near
Dallas, for a GOP gathering in a rodeo arena.
   White House spokesman Marlin Fitzwater said the president also
will make a one-day, cross-country trip on Monday for two events in
Southern California, a state with the largest electoral prize of 47
votes. The locations have not yet been announced, Fitzwater said.
</TEXT>
