<1ST_LINE>r a AM-FuneralHome     11-04 0193</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Funeral Home,0197</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Funeral Director Pleads In Charges Over Mishandling Corpses</HEAD>
<DATELINE>JACKSONVILLE, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A funeral director accused of
mishandling 49 corpses, some of which were stacked for years in a
closet, pleaded guilty Friday to felony charges and was sentenced to
a year and a day in prison.
   Circuit Judge Lawrence P. Haddock also ordered him to surrender
his license.
   Lewis J. Howell, owner of the Howell Morning Glory Funeral
Chapel, pleaded guilty to three counts of grand theft as part of an
agreement with the district attorney's office. He was accused of
accepting money for burials that were never carried out and of
accepting money from the city for cremations that were never
performed.
   Prosecutors dropped two other grand theft counts and 36
misdemeanor counts of fraud.
   Howell wasn't ordered to make restitution because he doesn't have
the money, said E. McRae Mathis, assistant state attorney.
   In June, inspectors discovered 41 bodies at the funeral home.
Several were in a hearse parked outside, but most were found inside
the building, which lacks refrigeration equipment. None had been
embalmed, and some had been there so long only the bones remained.
</TEXT>
