<FILEID>AP-NR-11-04-88 1942EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a AM-PTL     11-04 0413</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-PTL,0429</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Attorney: Bakker Not Surprised To Learn He's Target of Grand Jury</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PAUL NOWELL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CHARLOTTE, N.C. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   PTL founder Jim Bakker was not surprised
when prosecutors sent him a letter telling him he was the target of
a 15-month federal grand jury investigation into the television
ministry's finances, an attorney said Friday.
   ``Obviously, when you're notified in writing, it's a cause of
concern,'' Ryan Hovis said when asked for his client's response to
the Oct. 24 letter from federal prosecutor Charles Alexander.
   ``This is not news to us, it's been known for the better part of
a year (that Bakker was a target),'' he said, adding it was not a
foregone conclusion that he would be indicted.
   The grand jury has been impaneled since August 1987 to
investigate allegations of mail and wire fraud, conspiracy and
criminal tax violations.
   Since that time, prosecutors have subpoenaed thousands of
documents to try to learn how Bakker operated the PTL and how he and
his aides spent millions of dollars in contributions from 1980-87.
   Bakker resigned as PTL president in March 1987 in the midst of a
sex-and-money scandal.
   Prosecutors are trying to determine whether Bakker and his
associates raised money on television and through the mail for one
purpose and spent it on another. They also want to know whether any
of the money was used for personal benefit.
   The Charlotte Observer reported Friday that PTL chief builder Roe
Messner and Richard Dortch, Bakker's former top aide, also received
letters informing them too were being investigated. Bakker, Messner
and Dortch were invited to appear before the 23-member grand jury
later this month. The letters said they were not compelled to
appear, but if they did, their testimony could be used against them.
   Hovis said he advised Bakker not to testify.
   Alexander, who has repeatedly denied the existence of the grand
jury investigation, was in Washington, D.C., on Friday, his
secretary said. He did not return phone calls.
   Bakker also did not return phone calls Friday.
   ``After careful review with my lawyers, I am respectfully
declining the invitation to appear before the PTL grand jury,'' he
said in an earlier statement.
   In August, Bakker denied any wrongdoing and said he doubted he
would be indicted.
   ``If I am, I'll be shocked,'' he said. ``If there is an
indictment, it'll be because somebody framed us and set us up.''
   Attorneys for Messner and Dortch did not return calls Friday
afternoon.
</TEXT>
