<FILEID>AP-NR-11-04-88 2045EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r w AM-Fed-MonetaryPolicy     11-04 0601</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Fed-Monetary Policy,590</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>FOMC Decided to Keep Interest Rates Unchanged in September</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARTIN CRUTSINGER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Policymakers at the Federal Reserve, viewing
evidence that U.S. economic growth was slowing, decided at their
September meeting to leave interest rates unchanged, according to
minutes of the session released Friday.
   The Federal Open Market Committee, which establishes monetary
policy for the central bank, voted 12-0 to make no further moves to
tighten credit conditions.
   But officials let it be known that the central bank still
considered higher inflation a greater threat to the economy than a
possible recession.
   The Fed, whose main economic job is to guard against inflation,
began a series of credit-tightening steps late last March that
culminated in August with a one-half percentage point increase in
its discount rate, the interest it charges to make bank loans. The
discount rate now stands at 6.5 percent.
   But since that increase, many economists believe the central bank
has been willing to sit back and see if the credit-tightening moves
already initiated would be enough to dampen demand and cool any
dangers of overheating.
   The minutes of the Sept. 20 minute showed that Fed officials were
still taking a wait-and-see approach. The Fed officials said they
were encouraged by indications that economic growth was slowing from
the robust pace in the first half of the year.
   Indeed, the government has since reported that the overall
economy, as measured by the gross national product, expanded at a
modest 2.2 percent annual rate from July through September, down
from a 3.2 percent rate in the first half of the year.
   But even with signs that the economy was slowing, Fed officials
argued that it was too soon to declare a victory in the fight
against inflation.
   ``All of the members indicated that the balance of risks in the
economy were such that they favored or could accept a market
directive that would more readily accommodate a move toward firming
than an adjustment toward easing in the weeks ahead,'' the minutes
said.
   The FOMC minutes are used to direct the open market operations of
the Federal Reserve Bank in New York. Through the purchase of
government securities from banks, the Fed influences the amount of
reserves the banks have to make bank loans and thus the price of
those loans _ interest rates.
   While the vote for leaving monetary policy unchanged was
unanimous, the minutes indicated there was some dispute over just
how much further the Fed should go in fighting inflation.
   Some members of the policymaking group ``were less persuaded that
inflationary pressures would intensify, especially given the degree
of policy restraint that already had been implemented over the past
several months,'' the minutes said.
   These officials argued that the troubled condition of many banks
and savings and loan institutions could be adversely affected by
further increases in interest rates.
   Many economists expect that the Fed will begin pushing interest
rates up again sometime after Tuesday's election. They said the
report Friday that unemployment dropped to 5.3 percent in October,
matching a 14-year low, would renew concerns at the central bank
concerning tight labor markets and rising wage demands.
   ``Because the employment report was clearly strong, there is
little reason to believe that the Fed will back off any time soon
from its current policy of monetary restraint,'' said Thomas
Carpenter, chief economist for ASB Capital Management, a Washington,
D.C., investment firm.
   Fed officials met again this week to discuss monetary policy. The
minutes of that meeting will not be released until after the next
FOMC meeting on Dec. 13-14.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
