<2ND_LINE>AM-Burma,0355</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Burmese Military Authorities Reject Call For Interim Government</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SEIN WIN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>RANGOON, Burma (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The military government on Friday dismissed
political party demands that an interim government be formed to
supervise a proposed general election.
   Government spokesman Kyaw Sann told a news briefing, ``Some
parties are demanding formation of an interim government to hold a
free and fair election. With 104 parties now registered, with whom
do they intend to form an interim government? This government,
independent of party politics, is the best interim government for
the country.
   ``We will definitely hold a free and fair general election as
soon as law and order is restored.''.
   He said that from 1958-60, the army served as a caretaker
government, held a free election and handed power to a civilian
government.
   ``Some parties are even advocating armed revolution and liaising
between above-ground and underground elements. We are prepared to
meet such a challenge,'' he said, without elaborating.
   Pro-democracy groups began calling for a provisional government
after street protests toppled hard-line ruler President Sein Lwin on
Aug. 12.
   Opposition leaders believed they were close to getting
concessions from new President Maung Maung, but military commander
Gen. Saw Maung seized power in a Sept. 18 coup and ordered his
troops to fire on protesters in a bloody crackdown on dissent.
Hundreds were killed.
   Saw Maung promised that elections pledged by Maung Maung would be
held, but set no date. He allowed formation of political parties,
ending a quarter century in which only one legal party existed in
Burma.
   No foreign countries have officially recognized Saw Maung's
government.
   In London on Friday, Britain's minister for overseas development,
Chris Patten, told the House of Commons that Britain has frozen $1.8
million in development aid to Burma as a result of the political
situation in the Southeast Asian country.
   Patten said the Burmese military regime's pledge to hold
democratic multiparty elections should be honored ``as soon as
possible.'' He also said the military government was continuing to
purge those involved in August and September demonstrations.
</TEXT>
