<1ST_LINE>r p AM-OfficialEnglish     11-04 0229</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Official English,0234</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Appellate Panel Keeps Official English Measure on Ballot</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MIAMI (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A federal appellate panel refused Friday to take off
the ballot a proposal to make English the state's official language,
rejecting the argument that the citizens' initiative violated voting
rights law.
   Opponents of the initiative, backed by a Justice Department
brief, had asked the three judges at a hearing Thursday to block
Tuesday's vote on the measure. They contended that official English
backers violated the Voting Rights Act by not distributing their
petitions in Spanish in heavily Hispanic precincts.
   The 2-1 appellate ruling, announced by the 11th U.S. Circuit
Court of Appeals in Atlanta, upheld a lower court decision keeping
the proposal, Amendment 11, on the ballot.
   Florida English, the initiative's sponsor, contended that the
petitions were a private action and not subject to the Voting Rights
Act's provisions ensuring that the government provide equal access
to the ballot box for all citizens.
   That was the conclusion of U.S. District Judge James W. Kehoe in
his ruling last week, and was also the decision of a federal appeals
court hearing a similar Colorado case.
   Florida English collected more than 500,000 signatures to put the
initiative on the ballot, and according to the latest polls, it is
favored by a large majority of the state's voters. Many top state
officials are campaigning against it, however.
</TEXT>
