<HEAD>NBC Weatherman Makes Appearance After Hoax Preparations</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ST. MARYS, Ga. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   ``Today'' show weatherman Willard Scott
fulfilled a promise, even though he didn't make the promise, with a
half-day visit Friday that made up for a hoax.
   ``What do you say, gang?'' Scott called out to about 100
autograph hounds at a bookstore in the town of about 3,500.
   After about 30 minutes in the store, the jovial television
personality emerged with his lapels draped with Georgia Bulldogs
stickers and buttons. ``Yeah, I'm a bulldog, a hot dog,'' he said.
   Asked if he predicted the warm, overcast weather, he replied:
``Well, at least it isn't snowing.''
   In late July a woman visited the St. Marys-Kingsland area for 10
days and said she was with NBC.
   Local officials said she began making plans for Scott and NBC
newsman John Palmer to do a documentary on the community impact of
the Navy's Kings Bay submarine base.
   Residents were looking forward to greeting Scott.
   But NBC officials said the woman did not work for the network.
The plan was a hoax.
   Of the mystery woman, Scott said: ``Little did she know that she
was dealing with King Kong when she made a promise in my name. I've
never let anybody make a promise in my name that I didn't fulfill in
some way.''
   St. Marys Mayor Ward Hernandez said the town ``enjoyed having
Willard down with us'' and said Scott was considering a return visit.
