<HEAD>Police Find, Defuse Second Bomb Near General Electric Office</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SAN JUAN, Puerto Rico (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Police found and defused a homemade
bomb near General Electric Co.'s administrative office Friday, three
days after a bomb explosion slightly damaged the building.
   Jesus Garcia, head of the police department's explosives
division, said the bomb found Friday near a building adjacent to the
General Electric office was much more dangerous than a pipe bomb
that exploded Tuesday, shattering windows in the company's downtown
building.
   An obscure pro-independence group claimed responsibility for
Tuesday's explosion, which caused no injuries.
   No group claimed responsibility for the device found Friday, but
police said both bombs where placed at the same time.
   ``This device, based on our evaluations, was placed the same
night as the one that exploded in the facilities of General
Electric,'' Garcia said, adding that the second bomb ``could have
exploded at any time if it was bumped or disturbed.''
   On Wednesday, a group calling itself the Pedro Albizu Campos
Revolutionary Forces claimed responsibility for the explosion. The
group is named after a Puerto Rican nationalist of the 1930s.
   A communique from the group left near a San Juan news agency said
the act was ``in support of the just struggle of our people against
the criminal Yankee corporations that daily contaminate and poison
our waters ... slowly killing us.''
   Puerto Rico, an island of 3.3 million mostly Spanish-speaking
people, has been a U.S. territory since 1898 and a commonwealth
since 1952. Puerto Ricans are U.S. citizens, but they pay no U.S.
taxes and cannot vote for president.
</TEXT>
