<1ST_LINE>r i AM-SoccerRiotTrial     11-04 0377</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Soccer Riot Trial,0386</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Italian Claims British Soccer Fans Intended To Kill</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BRUSSELS, Belgium (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An Italian survivor of the Heysel
stadium riots said in a statement read Friday at the trial of 24
Britons charged with manslaughter, ``I was convinced they really
intended to kill someone.''
   Stefano Galliciani said British fans rampaged across terraces at
the stadium wielding sticks, bottles and iron bars.
   Galliciani had come to the Brussels stadium on May 29, 1985 to
support Juventus Turin, playing in the European soccer cup final
against Liverpool. Before the game started, 39 people, mostly
Italians, died in a stampede which has been blamed on a charge into
their ranks by British supporters.
   Twenty-four Liverpool men are on trial, charged with
manslaughter. Two more stayed in England, where they are facing
other charges.
   Galliciani identified Stephen McDonald, a 21-year-old apprentice
electrician, from newspaper pictures as one leading suspect, saying
``I was shocked by the hate and ferocity with which he attacked
people who were just trying to escape.''
   McDonald denied he took part in any violence.
   ``I did not go to Belgium with the intention of causing any
trouble,'' he told the court. ``I was distressed at the tragedy that
happened. But I don't feel responsibility. I feel sympathy for the
Italian families.''
   McDonald earlier told British police he just tried to help
English supporters under attack from Italians.
   He told Judge Pierre Verlynde he found himself among Italian
supporters and suggested to another Liverpool fan, Terry Wilson,
that they move into the Liverpool section because Italian fans were
staring at them. ``I felt threatened and uneasy,'' McDonald said.
   The third week of the trial ended Friday with no clearer evidence
that any British supporter was directly and personally responsible
for the death of the Italians. The Britons were charged after being
identified on videotapes made at the 1985 match. The trial is
expected to last until Christmas.
   Belgian law does not acknowledge collective guilt.
   Three Belgian officials and two police officers are also on trial
for criminal neglect in organizing the match. So are two European
Soccer Union officials.
   The Heysel tragedy was the bloodiest event in the history of
European sports. It created such a shock in Belgium that the
government later resigned.
</TEXT>
