<FILEID>AP-NR-11-04-88 1805EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u i AM-Obit-Martin     11-04 0446</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Obit-Martin,0459</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>World War II Bombing Ace Dies</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Air Marshal Sir Harold Martin, one of the daredevil
pilots who made the famous ``dam buster'' raid on Germany in World
War II, has died at age 70, his family announced Friday.
   His family said the war hero, whose decorations included three
separate awards of the Distinguished Flying Cross, the highest Royal
Air Force honor, died Thursday at his home in London. No cause of
death was given.
   Martin and his comrades, all experts at low-level bombing, flew
into a wall of enemy fire at a height of only 60 feet in 1943 and
dropped bouncing bombs in a night raid intended to breach dams and
flood the industrial Ruhr Valley.
   Their exploits were recorded in the 1954 movie named ``The Dam
Busters'' for the nickname of RAF Squadron 617.
   Martin was born in Australia and as a young man was ruled unfit
to fly in that country because he suffered from asthma.
   He came to Britain and became a bomber pilot, first with a
squadron of Australian Hampden bombers operating with the RAF, then
with an RAF squadron flying Lancasters. Martin quickly realized the
value of flying low to evade enemy fighters and set about perfecting
low-level skills.
   In 1943, he joined Squadron 617, the Dam Busters team assembled
by the late Wing Commander Guy Gibson to attack the heavily defended
Mohne, Eder and Sorpe dams.
   Martin helped train the team in dangerous maneuvers that included
dodging power lines and treetops, and on May 15, 1943, flew one of
the 18 Lancaster bombers that made the raid.
   The planes carried bombs invented by scientist Barnes Wallis that
were designed to be dropped exactly 60 feet, bounce across the water
to avoid anti-mine nets, then sink against the dam and explode.
   In the attack on the Mohne dam, Martin's bomb struck accurately
but German gunners hit his plane. Two shells exploded in a wing fuel
tank, but it was empty and the plane flew on.
   Despite repeated attacks, the Mohne dam appeared to have held,
but then water began pouring through a widening breach and Martin
was heard shouting: ``Hell, it's gone! It's gone!''
   The Mohne and Eder dams were breached and the Sorpe dam damaged,
causing widespread destruction but not the hoped-for mortal blow to
power and water supplies.
   Later in the war, Martin became a master of low-level night raids
on airfields and of low-level marking, dropping flares to indicate
targets for heavy-omber attacks.
   Martin was RAF commander in West Germany and chief of NATO's 2nd
Allied Tactical Air Force in 1970-73 and retired in 1974.
   His wife and two daughters survive.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP881104-0195 </DOCNO>
