<FILEID>AP-NR-11-04-88 1843EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u i AM-India-Punjab     11-04 0398</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-India-Punjab,0411</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Sikh Militants Kill 42</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DEEPAK SHARMA</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>AMRITSAR, India (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Sikh militants killed 42 people and
wounded 54 Friday in a series of bombings at a crowded market and an
attack on a farm in Punjab state, police and news reports said.
   A police spokesman in the state capital of Chandigarh said 26
people were killed and 50 wounded when seven bombs exploded in rapid
succession at the crowded market of a Hindu neighborhood in Batala,
north of Amritsar. He blamed the blasts on Sikhs.
   Five hours later, six Sikh gunmen in a truck opened fire, killing
16 workers and wounding four at a seed farm near Lawdohwal in the
Ludhiana district about 80 miles southeast of Amritsar, the United
News of India and the Press Trust of India reported.
   The Sikh militants' campaign of violence for a separate nation
has claimed at least 2,206 lives in Punjab state this year.
   Friday's attacks came four days before Diwali, a major Hindu
holiday. Authorities have stepped up security for fear of an
escalation of sectarian attacks timed to disrupt festivities.
   The police spokesman in Chandigarh, speaking on condition of
anonymity, said the bombs in Batala were so powerful that many of
the victims were dismembered.
   Batala police chief S.M. Sharma said some of the explosives were
concealed in two sewing machines which were left on bicycles 200
yards apart.
   He said 4,000 paramilitary troops were deployed in the Batala
area in case of a Hindu backlash of violence.
   ``We have imposed curfew in the area. The situation is very, very
tense,'' Sharma said. He said 22 Hindus, three Sikhs and a Christian
were killed in the blasts.
   The police spokesman said the state's borders with Haryana and
Jammu-Kashmir were sealed after the blasts and a state-wide alert
had been announced. No arrests were reported.
   Batala, 32 miles north of the Sikh holy city of Amritsar, has a
population of about 150,000. Hindus outnumber Sikhs in the town and
control the trade.
   Sikh radicals in Punjab claim they are discriminated against by
Hindus, India's religious majority, and need a separate homeland to
preserve their religion and culture.
   Sikhs make up about two percent of India's 880 million people,
but they are a majority in Punjab.
   On Thursday, Sikh radicals ambushed a bus and killed 11
passengers at Gujarpura, 27 miles northeast of Amritsar.
</TEXT>
