<DOCNO> AP881104-0197 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-11-04-88 1846EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u p AM-PresidentialPolls     11-04 0283</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Presidential Polls,260</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>In CBS Poll, Dukakis Draws Closer</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Political Rdp Bjt</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Michael Dukakis pulled to within seven points of
George Bush in a national survey Friday, trimming the Republican's
lead from double digits earlier in the week.
   With four days before the presidential election, Dukakis narrowed
the gap by improving his standing among older Americans and by
attracting two-thirds of the voters who decided this week, the CBS
News poll found.
   There was room for other changes: Of the 1,343 probable voters
who were surveyed from Tuesday through Thursday, 24 percent either
said they could change their minds, only leaned toward a candidate
or were undecided.
   The poll put the race at 51-44 percent, including leaners. That
was down from a 12-point Bush lead, 53-41 percent, in a CBS News
poll done Oct. 29 through Monday.
   The election is Tuesday.
   Only about 4 percent of the probable voters made up their minds
in the last few days, but two-thirds of them went for Dukakis, the
poll found.
   The Democrat trailed just by 47-45 percent among probable voters
aged 45 and over; younger voters favored Bush by 54-42 percent.
   Bush and his running mate, Sen. Dan Quayle, won support from 87
percent of the Republicans in the poll, 55 percent of independents
and 22 percent of Democrats. Dukakis and his running mate, Sen.
Lloyd Bentsen, were backed by 73 percent of the Democrats polled, 34
percent of independents and 11 percent of the Republicans.
   Eleven percent of the independents were undecided, as were 5
percent of the Democrats and 2 percent of the Republicans.
   The poll's margin of error was plus or minus three percentage
points.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
