<1ST_LINE>r i AM-HotelShootout     11-04 0586</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Hotel Shootout,0606</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Union Brawl Points Up Mexican Governing Party's Problems</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CANDICE HUGHES</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MEXICO CITY (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Rival union factions turned a leading tourist
hotel into a blazing battleground _ the second such incident this
week _ in what was seen Friday as a dramatic sign of struggle inside
Mexico's weakened governing party.
   One man died of a gunshot wound to the head and seven were
injured Thursday night in a huge brawl and shootout at Mexico City's
37-story Hotel Presidente Chapultepec that left the lobby a sea of
shattered glass and broken palm trees.
   Authorities said 189 people were arrested. They estimated up to
600 unionists took part in the fracas.
   Hotel officials and police said no guests or employees were hurt.
   ``The workers movement is trying to enhance its political
position using disorder and violence,'' Jose Maria Alverde, a
leading businessman in the capital, was quoted as saying by the
Excelsior news service.
   Witnesses and officials said gangs from rival union factions
charged into the hotel lobby through separate entrances at about
9:30 p.m. Thursday.
   The unionists lobbed firebombs, fired shots, broke plate glass,
rampaged through offices and struggled with police.
   Guests ran for their rooms. Hotel employees took cover or tried
to barricade the shattered entrances with furniture.
   ``There was a lot of screaming. We heard gunshots. We looked up
and the lobby was filled with white smoke,'' said Paul Gregory, a
lighting designer from New York City.
   Police and Red Cross officials had said Thursday that two people
had died, but on Friday the official toll from the prosecutor's
office was revised to one dead and the number of injured was put at
seven.
   The hotel on Chapultepec Park is one of the city's finest.
   The battle came four days after a union clash at the Acapulco
Plaza resort hotel in Acapulco left two dead. Violence there flared
after the national Mexican Workers Federation tried to replace a
local union leader.
   ``Nobody is in control anymore. Everybody is fighting for his own
survival,'' political analyst Adolfo Aguilar said.
   The confrontation pits members of the Mexican Workers Federation
against one of its own affiliates, the Revolutionary Federation of
Workers and Campesinos. The Revolutionary Federation holds the
musician's contract at the Presidente Chapultepec.
   The unions are key blocs in the governing Institutional
Revolutionary Party, or PRI, which was shaken by heavy losses in the
July 6 election. The Workers Federation lost strength in Congress
and union leaders fear that reforms promised by President-elect
Carlos Salinas de Gortari, who takes office Dec. 1, will further sap
their power.
   Jockeying for power and membership within the unions was viewed
as one result.
   ``It is a sign of deterioration, that the confrontation is
worsening,'' said analyst Aguilar in a telephone interview from
Washington, where he is on a Carnegie Foundation fellowship.
   Fidel Velasquez, 88-year-old head of the Workers Federation,
denied his group was at fault, saying the union had ``abolished its
programs of violence.'' He did not say what those programs were.
   ``We will reply blow-for-blow to anything they want to dish
out,'' said Isidoro Mendoza de la Cruz, a congressman and member of
the Revolutionary Federation.
   Cesar Garcia Lara, a spokesman for the national Confederation of
Chambers of Commerce, called on Salinas to curb the unions before
they hurt Mexico's vital tourism industry and tarnish the country's
international image.
   PRI officials had no immediate comment Friday, but they have
repeatedly denied any rift between the new party leadership and the
unions.
</TEXT>
