<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Britain-Religion     11-04 0235</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Britain-Religion,0241</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Church Suspends Lord Chancellor for Attending Mass</HEAD>
<DATELINE>GLASGOW, Scotland (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A Scottish Protestant church suspended
the lord chancellor, Britain's highest-ranking law officer, from his
post as a church elder Friday because he attended the Roman Catholic
funerals of two colleagues.
   Lord Mackay, the lord chancellor, also was barred from taking
Communion.
   The small Free Presbyterian Church of Scotland regards the
Catholic Mass as idolatrous and the pope as the anti-Christ. It
acted after a court of elders heard that Mackay attended two
Catholic funerals.
   Mackay, 61, an elder of the church's Edinburgh kirk, or church,
said that in attending the funerals of Lords Russell and Wheatley,
``I did nothing to indicate support for the doctrine of Roman
Catholicism.''
   ``I went there purely with the purpose of paying my respects to
my dead colleagues and to give public expression of sympathy to
their relatives,'' Mackay said.
   He said he had no regrets about attending the funerals and would
appeal the sentences.
   The lord chancellor is a Cabinet member and presides over the
House of Lords, the unelected upper house of Parliament, including
the Law Lords, the highest court of appeal in the British legal
system.
   Mackay's church has between 4,000 and 5,000 members and 20
congregations. It was formed in 1893 when it broke away from the
Free Church of Scotland, itself a splinter of Scotland's main
denomination, the Church of Scotland.
</TEXT>
