<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Peru     11-04 0268</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Peru,0278</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Six Wounded in Clashes Following Bank Bombings</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LIMA, Peru (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Leftist guerrillas bombed four banks and shot
it out with police Friday in the heaviest urban guerrilla violence
in months, leaving three rebels and three officers wounded, police
said.
   They said rebels from the pro-Cuba Tupac Amaru Revolutionary
Movement exploded six bombs at the state-owned banks in morning
attacks, breaking windows and damaging doors and furniture but
causing no injuries.
   The bombings were carried out in two working-class neighborhoods.
   Later, rebels in cars fired machine guns in two attacks at two
pairs of officers, who returned fire, police said.
   Three rebels in one car were wounded when a patrolman raked the
car with machine-gun fire, but the guerrillas escaped, the police
said.
   The police said the rebels left leaflets protesting government
austerity measures and hailing the 208th anniversary Friday of a
failed rebellion against Spanish rule staged by Tupac Amaru, a rebel
Indian leader and national hero.
   It was the worst rebel violence in Lima since the Tupac Amaru
fired mortars at the U.S. Embassy residence June 9, causing minor
damage but no injuries.
   Attacks by the organization have been infrequent since government
forces arrested key leaders and crushed a guerrilla front in the
eastern jungles a year ago.
   The Tupac Amaru group began its attacks in 1984. It is smaller
and considered less violent than the Shining Path, a fanatical,
Mao-inspired movement that has been fighting since 1980 to overthrow
Peru's elected government. No known links exist between the groups.
   Urban attacks by the Shining Path also have dropped off in recent
months.
</TEXT>
