<2ND_LINE>AM-Turkey-Detentions,0487</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Greek, West German Human Rights Activists Seized by Police</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ANKARA, Turkey (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A group of Greek and West German human
rights activists gathered at an Ankara court Friday and unfurled
banners calling for amnesty for hundreds of prisoners charged with
political crimes.
   Officials said 24 people were detained.
   Twenty of those arrested will be deported Saturday and the four
others will await a court hearing Monday, the semi-official Anatolia
News Agency said.
   It quoted Mehmet Agar, the Ankara chief of security, as saying 12
Greeks and eight West Germans would be deported Saturday, placed
aboard the first flights out of Ankara.
   The agency reported Agar said four Greeks being held until Monday
will be prosecuted on charges of staging a political demonstration
during a trial. If conviced they could be sentenced to at least six
months in jail. Anatolia identified them as Georgios Kuidis,
Nikolaos Beladilas, Georgios Kurtis and Kostantinos Nikiforakis.
   Four other foreigners, two West German paliamentarians, a West
German journalist and Gerasimos Zarkadis, a correspondent for the
Athens News Agency, also were picked up but were released after a
few hours, Anatolia said. It did not identify the West Germans.
   Aristidis Kalegeropoulus Stratis, press attache at the Greek
Embassy, said the activists were in Ankara to observe the Dev-Yol
trials that have been going on for seven years.
   Dev-Yol, or Revolutionary Road, was one of the largest leftist
underground groups before the 1980 military takeover. Most of its
members were arrested after the coup and others fled abroad.
   More than 700 suspected Dev-Yol members are being tried on
charges of political killings and attempting to stage a communist
takeover. Seventy-four face death sentences if convicted.
   Legal authorities say the court will not be able to announce the
verdicts for another year. The defense is now presenting its case.
   In a related development, hundreds of prisoners are participating
in hunger strikes at Turkish jails to protest long legal proceedings
and demand better conditions, it was reported Friday.
   Gulten Sesen, who acts as a spokeswoman for the prisoners'
relatives, told The Associated Press that about 300 inmates in the
central province of Eskisehir began fasting 17 days ago.
   She said at least 250 prisoners in the southeastern province of
Diyarbakir began fasting 13 days ago, and on Wednesday 300 inmates
in Istanbul's Sagmalcilar prison joined the hunger strike.
   She said the prisoners are taking liquids only and among their
demands are more access to lawyers and relatives and permission to
write letters and use musical instruments.
   The Istanbul newspaper Milliyet said Friday that 12
hunger-striking inmates in Eskisehir had been hospitalized.
   About 50 friends and relatives of the fasting inmates held a
sit-in at Parliament to protest what they called ``inhuman
restrictions'' in prisons. Officials reported 20 were detained and
the others were expelled from the building.
</TEXT>
