<2ND_LINE>AM-Delinquent Diplomats,0273</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Crackdown on Diplomats Has Reduced Unpaid Parking Tickets</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Diplomats in London have been more careful about
paying their parking tickets since the government launched a
crackdown that led to the expulsion of a Tunisian envoy in August.
   The Foreign Office said Friday that the diplomatic corps held 42
percent fewer unpaid parking tickets in the first half of 1988
compared to the same period last year.
   But some offenders have been slow to clean up their act.
   A Foreign Office spokesman said Egypt still leads the list for a
second year although it had fewer unpaid traffic tickets this time _
368 in the first half of 1988 compared with 426 in 1987.
   He said the Soviet Union ranks second, with an increase from 271
to 324 tickets, and Poland is third, with an increase from 150 to
213 tickets.
   The spokesman, who spoke on condition of anonymity, said Britain
would be ``underlining our concern'' to the 10 worst offenders, who
accounted for 35 percent of the total unpaid tickets.
   He said diplomats had 5,838 unpaid tickets in the first six
months of 1988, compared with 10,096 in the same period in 1987 and
nearly 67,000 in 1984.
   The drop follows a Foreign Office campaign against law-breaking
diplomats. In August, Britain expelled a Tunisian envoy who failed
to pay hundreds of dollars in parking fines. A standard parking
ticket in London costs $21.
   Three diplomats _ Cuba's ambassador, a Cuban attache and a
Vietnamese envoy _ also were expelled during one week in September
for firearms violations.
</TEXT>
