<1ST_LINE>r a AM-Steinberg-Launders     11-04 0484</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Steinberg-Launders,0499</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Lisa Steinberg's Biological Mother Breaks Silence</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SAMUEL MAULL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The biological mother of Lisa Steinberg, whose
beating death focused national attention on child abuse, said Friday
she is attending the adoptive father's murder trial because she
feels she must, despite her hatred of him.
   Michele Launders, 27, who had Lisa as a teen-ager, gave her up to
Joel Steinberg thinking the lawyer would find her a good home.
Steinberg kept and raised the girl, and is accused of killing the
6-year-old girl with a severe beating last November.
   ``I hate the man. He's not a man to me _ he's not human,'' said
Ms. Launders, breaking her silence to discuss the case.
   Ms. Launders, who lives in an undisclosed Nassau County town,
attends the trial daily. A family friend, retired police officer
Steve Dickson, serves as her armed bodyguard.
   ``It's just something I have to do,'' she said, adding that she
is undergoing psychotherapy, feels tremendous guilt and thinks of
the child every night.
   Steinberg, 47, a disbarred lawyer, is on trial for second-degree
murder. He denies that he hit the child. He says she choked on
vomited food and maintains the bruises on her chest and back
resulted from his trying to revive her.
   When Ms. Launders and Steinberg make eye contact, as they have
several times during the trial, ``I just stare right back,'' she
said. ``I do expect and hope that there will be a conviction; that
would be justice, because I feel he's guilty.''
   She added that 25 years to life in prison, the maximum sentence
that Steinberg faces, would be inadequate.
   Ms. Launders watched Thursday as a 5{-minute videotape revealed
the bruises, open wounds, patches of missing hair and discolored
left leg that Hedda Nussbaum, 46, then Steinberg's live-in
companion, suffered around the time of Lisa's death.
   Prosecutors believe the videotape shows the allegedly violent
conditions in the household and offers an explanation as to why Ms.
Nussbaum did not call for help for at least 10 hours after Lisa
became unconscious.
   ``It was very disturbing. She suffered a lot herself,'' Ms.
Launders said of Ms. Nussbaum.
   ``I don't blame her. But I still feel she (Ms. Nussbaum) could
have prevented it,'' she said of Lisa's death. ``I wouldn't say I
feel sorry for her. She put herself in that situation.''
   Asked about an agreement to drop charges against Ms. Nussbaum in
exchange for her testimony, Ms. Launders said: ``I wasn't happy with
it. But if it will help convict Steinberg, sure.''
   Lisa, whom Steinberg obtained as a newborn, was taken to St.
Vincent's Hospital shortly after 6:30 a.m. on Nov. 2, 1987. She died
three days later of a head injury.
   Ms. Launders, an insurance underwriter, said she has worked only
1{ months in the past year. ``My mind just isn't there yet. I can't
concentrate on work.''
</TEXT>
