<FILEID>AP-NR-11-04-88 2132EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a AM-TV-Today     11-04 0662</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-TV-Today,0679</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>`Today' Devotes Two Days to Election</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By KATHRYN BAKER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Television Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The narrow hallway that leads to the ``Today''
show studio is suddenly filled with guys in blue suits.
   Democratic presidential candidate Michael Dukakis is swept down
the hall within a phalanx of advance men, advisers and Secret
Service agents. Trailing slightly behind the group is his makeup
woman.
   Dukakis' live appearance Friday morning capped two full days of
NBC's ``Today'' show devoted to the presidential election. Friday's
show was on the the Massachusetts governor, Thursday's on the
Republican nominee, Vice President George Bush.
   When it's close to time for Dukakis' interview with host Bryant
Gumbel, the candidate comes into the studio during a commercial
break and chats with weatherman Joe Witte. Then he settles into a
chair opposite Gumbel. Somebody hands him a cup of coffee in a
``Today'' show mug. He and Gumbel exchange small talk while Witte
does the weather, helpfully describing conditions for Dukakis' later
appearance at a rally in Queens as, ``if I remember my tourist
Greek, `kala,' which is `good.'''
   Underdog Dukakis has been blitzing the talk shows in the waning
days of the campaign, though Bush has often been matching him show
for show. Live interviews with the two took up the last half hour of
the respective Thursday and Friday ``Today'' shows.
   ``It's something we felt we had to do as a service to the
voters,'' said ``Today'' executive producer Marty Ryan. ``All the
campaign rhetoric that has gone on, we felt it was important to do
something specific for the voters, not for political junkies or
anything else, but just for voters, you know, what the issues are,
what these people would do, so they had a clear idea of who they
were and what they stood for and what their vote really meant.''
   These were shows not just for the voters, but by the voters, who
asked their own questions of the candidates via videotape. They
wanted to know what Bush would do about the deficit and day-care,
what Dukakis would do to combat terrorism and what job would Jesse
Jackson have in his administration.
   Television has been accused of accentuating style over substance
in its campaign coverage. But the ``Today'' shows were a lesson in
how television can stick to its style and still offer substance.
   There was plenty for political junkies on the ``Today'' shows,
and who's kidding? It's more fun to hear pundits poke fun at
campaign ads than to listen to theories about the deficit.
   For the interviews, Dukakis was in New York. Bush was in a hotel
room in Columbus, Ohio. Typically, the candidates were mostly vague
with their answers, but not for Gumbel's lack of trying.
   Gumbel asked tough follow-ups and couched most questions in the
accessible, ``I am a voter interested in X, why should I vote for
you?''
   Bush said he would reduce the deficit by cutting spending. ``If
you won't tell me what you'll cut, why should I vote for you?''
Gumbel insisted.
   Gumbel asked Dukakis, ``If I sit there and don't think you have
managed your campaign competently, why should I vote for you?''
Dukakis said that being a good president is more than coming up with
good campaign ads. ``But it goes beyond ads,'' Gumbel insisted.
Dukakis was left speechless for a beat.
   But within the comfy confines of the top-rated morning show with
an audience mostly in houseshoes and breakfast nooks, the toughest
question for Dukakis came from a woman in Atlanta: ``My first
question would be, `Is he going to stop Kitty from smoking?'''
   Dukakis grinned sheepishly and shook his head. No campaign
promises here.
   ``I've been trying for a long time,'' he said. ``Somebody asked
me the other day whether or not I was going to have a smoke-free
White House, and I said, not and maintain the kind of domestic
tranquility I've had with my wife for 25 years.''
</TEXT>
