<DOCNO> AP881104-0207 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-11-04-88 2133EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r w AM-WesternLand     11-04 0660</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Western Land,650</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Judge Denies National Wildlife Federation Claim</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By GUY DARST</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   In a major victory for the Reagan
administration, a federal judge ruled Friday that a conservation
organization was not entitled to challenge the removal of use
restrictions on federal land in the West.
   U.S. District Judge John Pratt decided that the National Wildlife
Federation had not shown enough injury to members to give it
standing to sue.
   The Bureau of Land Management, an arm of the Interior Department,
in 1981 began revoking restrictions _ called ``classifications'' or
``withdrawals'' _ that govern almost all the 174 million acres it
administers in the 17 westernmost states of the lower 48.
   Classifications and withdrawals generally amount to the same
thing. They can ban a single activity on a federal parcel, such as
mining; may keep the the parcel in question from being sold or
exchanged; or may impose several restrictions at once.
   The federation filed suit in 1985, alleging among other things
that the department was violating federal law by proceeding without
recommendations to Congress and the president, without preparation
of plans to guide its actions and without public involvement.
   Its members' recreational use of the land would be ``irreparably
injured'' if the government were allowed to proceed, the federation
said.
   Pratt subsequently granted an injunction that froze all
restrictions pending further consideration of the case. On Friday,
he dissolved that injunction and dismissed the case.
   ``We are ecstatic,'' said Bob Johnson, a spokesman for the
bureau. He said officials would immediately began a review of
decisions held up by the injunction.
   Norman Dean, the federation's staff lawyer handling the case,
said he had not seen the decision and could not comment on details.
He added, ``This is not the end of it. It's back to the Court of
Appeals for us.''
   The lifting of the injunction means the government is free to
sell or trade whatever parcels have no restrictions on them, and
miners may stake claims on millions of acres, Dean said.
   In December 1987, the U.S. Circuit Court of Appeals for the
District of Columbia upheld the injunction against an attempt to
dissolve it by the Mountain States Legal Foundation, a
conservatively oriented advocacy group based in Denver, and the
department.
   In so doing, the appeals court ruled that the federation, on
behalf of its members, was entitled to seek the injunction. The
federation need not be as specific in its allegations at such a
preliminary stage as an injunction as it might have to be when a
judge reached the underlying merits of the case, the appeals judges
said.
   To prevail on the merits, the federation must ``allege facts
showing that one or more of its members is among the persons injured
by the challenged agency action.''
   According to Pratt's ruling, the federation faied to make such a
showing.
   Affidavits aimed at establishing standing of the federation to
sue _ submitted by members Peggy Peterson and Roger Erman, whose
hometowns were not given _ were ``vague, conclusory and lacked
factual specificity,'' Pratt wrote.
   ``They do not and cannot show injury in fact with respect to the
two specific areas in Wyoming and Arizona in the vicinity of which
these affiants claim to be located.
   ``More important, standing alone, these two affidavits do not
provide any basis for standing to challenge as violative of (the
law) the legality of each of the 1,250 or so classification
terminations and withdrawal revocations.''
   The Peterson affidavit covered land in the Green River area of
Wyoming and the Erman affidavit concerned land near Grand Canyon.
   For example, ``There is no showing that Peterson's recreational
use and enjoyment extends to the particular 4,500 acres covered by
the decision to terminate classification and to the remainder of the
2 million acres affected by the determination. All she alleges is,
she uses lands `in the vicinity.' The affidavit on its face contains
only a bare allegation of injury.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
