<1ST_LINE>r a AM-Obit-Sauvage     11-04 0152</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Obit-Sauvage,0156</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>French Journalist Dies</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Leo Sauvage, an author and French journalist who
was the New York correspondent for the Paris newspaper Le Figaro for
25 years, has died at age 75.
   Sauvage died Oct. 30 in his Manhattan apartment, according to his
son, Pierre.
   At the time of his death, Sauvage was the drama critic of The New
Leader, a bi-monthly magazine of commentary, where he had been a
contributor since 1961, according to its editor, Myron Kolatch.
   Sauvage was the author of eight books, including ``The Oswald
Affair,'' a critique of the Warren Commission's report on the
assassination of President John F. Kennedy.
   From 1950 to 1975, as New York bureau chief for Le Figaro,
Sauvage was one of the leading interpreters of the United States for
French readers.
   Sauvage is survived by his wife of nearly 50 years, Barbara,
three children and three grandchildren.
</TEXT>
