<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Mexico-Corruption     11-04 0279</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Mexico-Corruption,0289</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Special Commission Clears Former Oil Chief Of Corruption</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MEXICO CITY (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A special congressional commission cleared
former government oil chief Mario Ramon Beteta on Friday of union
allegations that he embezzled about $49 million.
   The Mexico City daily Excelsior said the commission split along
party lines.
   It said the 15 commission members who voted for Beteta's
exoneration belong to the ruling Institutional Revolutionary Party.
Beteta also is a PRI member.
   Of seven commissioners who voted against exoneration, six belong
to opposition parties and the seventh was PRI member Adolfo
Barrientos, head of the oil union that was at odds with Beteta when
he was chief of the government oil monopoly Pemex, the paper said.
   Beteta left Pemex in January to become governor of Mexico state,
which borders Mexico City.
   Barrientos presented the allegations against Beteta on Sept. 27,
hours after Beteta and other political leaders met with
President-elect Carlos Salinas de Gortari and endorsed Salinas' call
for modernizing the PRI.
   Such modernization could include probes into union corruption and
has been opposed by some of PRI's key labor sectors.
   Oilworkers crowded into Chamber of Deputies galleries to cheer
Barrientos when he accused Beteta of defrauding Pemex through a 1985
leasing deal for two Yugoslav-built tankers.
   But the special commission ruled Friday that ``no illicit conduct
existed.''
   The Federal Comptroller's Office cleared Beteta of any wrongdoing
in the deal in a published report it released Thursday, the
government newspaper El Nacional said.
   Beteta became Pemex chief in December 1982 as part of President
Miguel de la Madrid's anti-corruption campaign. He replaced Jorge
Diaz Serrano, who was convicted for embezzling $58.7 million in a
1980 tanker deal.
</TEXT>
