<1ST_LINE>r a AM-HospitalKidnapping     11-04 0479</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Hospital Kidnapping,0494</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Parents Discuss Abduction of Their Newborn</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MELISSA CONTI</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LITTLE ROCK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The young sisters of a newborn abducted from
their mother's arms by a woman posing a nurse want to know where
their brother is and don't understand why he is missing, their
father said Friday.
   More than $16,000 in reward money has been posted for information
leading to the return of Christopher Michael Jones, who was abducted
Tuesday night from Doctors Hospital.
   Willie Jones, the baby's father, said he has told his daughters,
Janelle, 5, and Crystal, 8, that ``the baby was kidnapped and we
believe that Christopher will be returned.''
   ``They want to know why she did it and when will he be back,'' he
said.
   The boy's mother, Annette Thomas-Jones, answered questions Friday
with her husband at her side in a hospital interview with The
Associated Press. She credited her equanimity to her faith in God.
   ``We have a serious belief that Christopher will be O.K.,'' said
Mrs. Thomas-Jones, 32. ``I just trust in him. He's going to bring
Christopher home to us.''
   Mrs. Thomas-Jones said the woman, dressed in a white skirt and a
white sweater, came to her room about 10 p.m. Tuesday and asked to
weigh the baby. She said the woman asked the baby's name and said
she needed to take the blanket and the pacifier with her.
   The woman also said she heard some nurses coming and looked out
into the hallway to make sure no one was there, Mrs. Thomas-Jones
said.
   After the woman left, a real nurse came and was told the baby
already had been taken to the nursery, Mrs. Thomas-Jones said. A
short time later, four hospital administrators told her the baby was
gone.
   ``The lady's going to have a conscience,'' she said of the woman.
``The Lord's going to give her a conscience and that's going to be
the start to his coming home to us.''
   Her husband said that he believed the baby was just lost in the
hospital when he was first told of the child's disappearance.
   ``You go from being ecstatic about the birth of your first son to
being shocked because your son has been kidnapped,'' he said.
   The couple said they were not angry at the woman or the hospital,
but Jones said he was glad hospital officials planned to re-evaluate
their security procedures.
   ``I don't hate this woman. I feel sorry for her,'' Mrs.
Thomas-Jones said.
   All leads in the case have dead-ended, said Officer Jason Shook
of the Little Rock Police Department.
   Dr. Whit Hall of Doctors Hospital said Christopher, who was born
six weeks' premature and weighing only four pounds, could die if not
given proper treatment.
   Police have released a composite sketch of the kidnapper,
described by Mrs. Thomas-Jones as black, 135 pounds, 5-foot-4, with
shoulder-length black hair.
</TEXT>
