<1ST_LINE>u i AM-Soviet-Baltics     11-04 0604</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Soviet-Baltics,0625</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Latvia Joins Estonia in Opposing Gorbachev's Constitutional Reform</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ANN IMSE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Nationalist groups in Estonia and Latvia on Friday
denounced President Mikhail S. Gorbachev's plan for reforming the
Soviet government. Human rights activist Andrei Sakharov called for
guarantees of human rights.
   In Estonia, the ruling Presidium called a special session of the
legislature for next week to consider complaints that the reform
would weaken the self-administration of the 14 non-Russian
republics, according to an editor at the newspaper Sovietskaya
Estonia.
   The Estonia Peoples' Front declared that the reform, which would
create a new national parliament and a powerful presidency, leaves
the republics ``with fewer rights than a province of Czarist
Russia,'' Sovietskaya Estonia said.
   The Estonia People's Front is a political organization created
last spring in an effort to oppose domination of the Baltic republic
by the Kremlin. It claims to have 60,000 members.
   Complaints in Latvia also centered on the loss of local control,
said Janis Dinevich, a leader of the Latvia People's Front in a
telephone interview from Riga.
   The constitutional reform is a key part of Gorbachev's attempt to
drive out members of the old guard and replace them with supporters
of perestroika, his plan for economic restructuring, and glasnost,
greater openness in some areas.
   But the reform is drawing strong opposition from some republics.
   Under the present constitution the 15 republics have their own
constitutions, governments and self-administration not expressly
reserved to the central government.
   Sakharov, who won the Nobel Peace Prize in 1975, said the revised
constitution should provide clear guarantees of human rights.
   ``Society needs dissidents,'' Sakharov said in an article in
Friday's edition of New Times magazine. He also suggested greater
public involvement in overseeing the government.
   ``For example, without the sympathy of the people, we could not
have made decisions like sending troops into Afghanistan,'' Sakharov
wrote.
   He had condemned the Soviet decision to send troops into
Afghanistan in 1979 and that criticism was one reason he was forced
to live in internal exile in the closed city of Gorki for several
years.
   Sovietskaya Estonia said in editions earlier this week that the
Estonia Peoples' Front sent a telegram to Gorbachev saying the
reform drafts ``are a step backward in the development of electoral
democracy,''
   ``Their adoption undoubtedly will lead to unforeseen consequences
for the strengthening of the unity of the U.S.S.R. and the
democratic development of perestroika in our country,'' the telegram
said, according to the report.
   The newspaper said the front called for removing the reform
propoosal from the agenda of the Nov. 29 session of the national
Supreme Soviet, or parliament, which was called to pass the
amendments.
   The duty editor at the paper said the Estonian Presidium on
Friday called for a special session of the republic's legislature
for Nov. 16 to consider the reform plan.
   The editor said Estonian Prime Minister Bruno Saul offered his
resignation Friday. It was not known if any action was taken. Some
Estonians have accused Saul of being pro-Moscow.
   An Estonian journalist, speaking on the condition he not be
identified, said Estonians and Latvians fear the reform would shift
control over the republics' economies and many other critical areas
to the central government.
   He also said under the reform the number of seats the Russian
republic would have in the national parliament would increase from
32 percent to 43 percent.
   The representative of the Latvia Peoples' Front said the reform
issues are too complex for only a month's consideration and the
front wants discussions of the plan in the republics' legislatures
and then a national constitutional convention.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
