<1ST_LINE>r a AM-EditorResigns 1stLd-Writethru a0708 11-04 0526</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Editor Resigns, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0708,0536</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Two Years After Heralded Arrival, Journal-Constitution Editor Quits</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: SUBS 9th graf, `His appointment ... with 5 grafs to UPDATE
with newsroom petition, advertisement lamenting loss; picks up 10th
graf: `Kovach stretched ...</NOTE>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto AX3</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ROBERT BYRD</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ATLANTA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The editor of The Atlanta Journal and The Atlanta
Constitution resigned Friday, citing a lack of ``shared values and
mutual trust'' with the newspapers' senior management.
   Bill Kovach, who left the top post at the Washington bureau of
The New York Times to take over the papers in December 1986, was
welcomed enthusiastically then as he set a goal of making the
Journal and Constitution _ essentially one newspaper, with different
editorial pages _ into ``world-class journalism.''
   The news of his resignation came suddenly, in a brief story at
the bottom of Page One in late editions of the afternoon Journal.
   Publisher Jay Smith said ``an irreconcilable difference in
management styles surfaced in a discussion Friday morning,''
according to the story. Smith said that while he and Kovach were
``in accord philosophically over the direction the newspapers have
taken,'' the management difference caused him to accept the editor's
resignation.
   Kovach, in a statement, said his resignation brought to an end
``two years of effort to develop a set of shared values and mutual
trust with the senior managers of the company. ... It became clear
this week that no such relationship existed.''
   Exactly what precipitated Friday morning's developments was not
clear. Neither the Journal's story nor Kovach's statement went into
detail about the discussion, and representatives of Smith and Kovach
said the men would not discuss the matter with reporters.
   Likewise, there was no word on Kovach's plans, or replacement.
   The resignation was announced to the Journal-Constitution
newsroom by Assistant Managing Editor Wendell ``Sonny'' Rawls, who
followed Kovach from the Times. The news stunned the staff.
   A petition, signed by 119 staffers in the five hours it was
posted in the newsroom, urged Smith and other senior newspaper
executives to reconsider their acceptance of Kovach's resignation
and persuade him to stay.
   ``Many of us have worked here under previous management (led by
former editor James G. Minter) and perhaps we have an even greater
appreciation for his (Kovach's) ability, his sound news judgment and
his enthusiasm,'' the petition said.
   Minter, who became a senior editor when Kovach was hired, retired
earlier this year.
   In addition to the petition, a group of Atlanta newspaper
employees purchased a full-page advertisement in Saturday's combined
editions to protest Kovach's resignation.
   His appointment had been seen in journalism as a sign that Cox
Enterprises Inc. wanted more from its flagship newspaper, which some
felt had been coasting for almost two decades on the reputation of
Ralph McGill, the editor of the morning Constitution whose civil
rights crusades won a Pulitzer Prize in 1959.
   Kovach stressed hard news and aggressiveness. Among the successes
under his leadership was a series outlining how some Atlanta banks
were refusing loans to residents of predominantly black
neighborhoods.
   The Journal-Constitution had five Pulitzer finalists in Kovach's
first year, more than any other newspaper in the country.
</TEXT>
