<1ST_LINE>u p AM-VotingLimit     11-04 0182</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Voting Limit,0186</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Ten-Minute Limit On Voting Booth Blocked</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SAN JOSE, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A state law limiting people to 10 minutes
in the voting booth was struck down Friday by a federal judge, who
citied a long and complex ballot.
   ``A fundamental constitutional right is being denied to a large
part of the California voting population ... and the 10-minute limit
is unreasonable given the size and the complexity of today's
ballot,'' said U.S. District Court Judge Robert P. Aguilar.
   Civil rights activists won the temporary restraining order after
three counties announced that, due to usually lengthy ballots, they
would attempt to enforce some measure of the 67-year-old law for the
first time in memory.
   The Mexican American Legal Defense Fund, the Northern California
Chapter of the American Civil Liberties Union and the Legal Aid
Society of Santa Clara argued that the time limit violated the
federal Voting Rights Act.
   They said it effectively discourages people with languages from
voting.
   Aguilar agreed, saying the time limit served as a virtual
literacy proficiency test, which is specifically outlawed by the act.
</TEXT>
