<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Helsinki-Czechoslovakia     11-04 0378</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Helsinki-Czechoslovakia,0387</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>British Diplomat Deplores Prague's Behavior</HEAD>
<DATELINE>VIENNA, Austria (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Britain on Friday criticized
Czechoslovakia for using police to break up a banned rally in Prague
a week ago and for its treatment of two activists.
   Peter Summerscale, deputy head of the British delegation, told
the 35-nation conference on European security and cooperation that
the police action contradicted ``the purposes which guide the work
of this conference.''
   Hundreds of helmeted riot police used tear gas, water cannon,
batons and dogs to scatter a peaceful crowd of 5,000 on the 70th
anniversary of Czechoslovak independence on Oct. 28.
   ``The fact is that the police brutally dispersed ... peaceful
citizens,'' Summerscale said in his address. ``Why, I must ask, was
force deemed necessary? Why also were 87 people arrested?''
   He also singled out the cases of Ivan Polansky, a Czechoslovak
activist who published underground literature, and Augustin
Navratil, who organized a petition that collected 500,000 signatures
for religious freedom this year.
   A district court in Slovakia sentenced Polansky in June to four
years in jail for subversive activity against the Czechoslovak
republic. The supreme court in Bratislava upheld the sentence in
August.
   ``What books could have been so horrifying, so dangerous as to
merit the attentions of the Czechoslovak authorities in this way?,''
Summerscale asked in his speech.
   Navratil, a Roman Catholic activist, was removed from his home in
central Czechoslovakia on Oct. 28 by two policemen and two doctors
and taken to a nearby psychiatric clinic where he previously had
been ordered to report.
   Navratil was confined ``no matter that his wife, a psychiatric
nurse until her retirement, believes him to pe perfectly sane and .
.. that a Swiss psychiatrist ... did not find him mentaly ill,''
Summerscale said.
   The conference nations reviewing compliance with the 1975
Helsinki Act are the United States, the Soviet Union, Canada and all
European nations except Albania.
   The conference opened in November 1986 to discuss security,
economic and cultural cooperation and human rights in Europe.
   Broad agreement has been reached on a mandate for new East-West
talks on reducing conventional arms. But disagreement persists over
human rights, particularly over political prisoners in the Soviet
Union and a Kremlin proposal to hold a conference on human rights in
Moscow in 1991.
</TEXT>
