<1ST_LINE>r i AM-UN-Soviet     11-04 0555</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-UN-Soviet,0571</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Official Says Soviets Want To Meet Feb. 15 Target For Withdrawal</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Afghanistan, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By VICTORIA GRAHAM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>UNITED NATIONS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A Soviet official said Friday his
government very much wants to meet the Feb. 15 target for withdrawal
of all Soviet troops from Afghanistan.
   The official, who spoke on condition he not be identified, was
asked about the Soviet announcement earlier Friday that the
withdrawal had been suspended.
   Alexander Bessmertnykh, first deputy foreign minister, told
reporters in Moscow the reason for the suspension was that
anti-communist rebels continued to attack civilians, government
troops and withdrawing Soviet forces. He also accused America and
Pakistan of keeping up a constant flow of weapons to the rebels.
   Burhanuddin Rabbani, a rebel leader who was in New York for the
annual U.N. meeting on Afghanistan, said:
   ``We believe that the new threat by the Russians that they will
postpone the withdrawal of their troops is only an excuse. The
Russians knew from the beginning that with the withdrawal of their
troops the puppet regime (of Afghan President Najib) would fall
down, so it is not something new.''
   Rabbani is chairman of the seven-party Islamic Unity of Afghan
Mujahedeen alliance. He was interviewed in a New York City hotel
room.
   ``The Mujahedeen (holy warriors) have announced that if the
Russians do not bombard the villages on their withdrawal, the
Mujahedeen will not create any obstacle for their troops,'' he said.
``As a matter of fact, the Mujahedeen gave permission to the
Russians to leave certain areas in security.''
   He was asked about the Soviets moving MiG-27 ground-attack jets
and SS-1 Scud missiles into Afganiistan. He said such actions ``are
all indications that the Russians are continuing their dangerous war
policy in Afghanistan, which is not only a threat to Afghanistan but
to the region as a whole, and they want to find an excuse for their
war policy.''
   The Soviet official in New York, commenting on the new Soviet
arms shipments, said the Kremlin was sending more powerful weapons
to Afghanistan because Soviet troops and civilians were being
attacked by Afghan rebels, some using U.S.-made Stinger rockets.
   ``Now, unfortunately our troops are attacked and also the
peaceful population of Afghan cities is also attacked and so we have
to do something specific in this military field,'' he said.
   ``The Stinger attacks against our troops required some reaction
from our side.''
   He said the Soviet Union was taking strong measures in hopes of
improving the situation so all of its troops would be out of
Afghanistan by Feb. 15. That is the date stipulated in the
U.N.-sponsored acords signed in April in Geneva by Afghanistan,
Pakistan, the Soviet Union and United States. The Afghan rebels were
not included in the negotiations.
   The Soviet Union sent troops into Afghanistan in December 1979 to
help the Marxist government battle the guerrillas.
   Moscow had an estimated 115,000 military personnel in Afganistan
and began the withdrawal May 15. The Soviets reported half of the
force had been removed by Aug. 15.
   The official did not define what the Soviets meant by the word
``suspended.''
   He said the first phase of withdrawal was completed by Aug. 15
and the ``second phase has not started, but that does not mean we
are not aiming for the date of Feb. 15.''
</TEXT>
