<1ST_LINE>r a AM-BabyWhale     11-04 0236</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Baby Whale,0243</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Killer Whale Gives Birth for Second Time</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ORLANDO, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A performing killer whale at Sea World of
Florida gave birth Friday to her second calf, a 6{-foot-long female
weighing about 350 pounds.
   ``It was a picture-perfect birthing process, and mother and baby
are doing just fine,'' said Jack Pearson, curator of mammals at the
Orlando marine park.
   The birth was the third at Sea World parks by performing killer
whales.
   The mother, named Kandu, also had given birth to Baby Shamu,
which was born September 1985 and is now one of the park's top
performers. A third calf was born last month at a Sea World park in
San Diego.
   Another of the giant mammals at the Orlando park is pregnant and
expected to give birth soon.
   Pearson said Kandu began bonding with her offspring immediately
after the birth in a special 6-million-gallon breeding tank.
   The whale was in labor for a little more than three hours. The
newborn, which has not been named, was expected to begin nursing
several hours after birth.
   Kandu continued to perform before crowds at the park's marine
stadium until Thursday, when trainers noticed some behavioral and
body changes.
   ``She was very slow and didn't eat all her food. She did not
perform but spent a quiet night. This morning, she refused to eat,
which is a tell-tale sign that birth is imminent,'' Pearson said.
</TEXT>
