<HEAD>First Death in Riots</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: ADDS 8 grafs to UPDATE with president visiting relatives of
fishermen, army sticking by story. No pickup.</NOTE>
<DATELINE>CARACAS, Venezuela (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Four days of riots touched off by the
killings of 14 fishermen by Venezuelan troops last week claimed
their first death, an 18- year-old laborer struck by a
demonstrator's rock, press reports said Friday.
   The victim, Javier Antonio Belloso of Maracaibo, 250 miles west
of Caracas, was riding in a public bus Thursday when demonstrators
began throwing rocks, according to El Universal, a Caracas
newspaper. One rock hit Belloso in the head and he died shortly
after, the paper said.
   The riots followed the shooting by Venezuelan border troops last
Saturday of 14 fishermen the military claimed were Colombian
guerrillas.
   Students at major universities in Caracas and elsewhere went on a
rampage, sacking stors and banks, burning vehicles, blocking traffic
and battling police and National Guard units.
   At least 50 students and seven police have been injured,
according to student groups and press reports. No official figures
have been released.
   On Friday the protesters scaled down their demonstrations, but
promised to keep protesting in the face of what they called a
government effort to cover up a massacre and protect the killers.
   President Jaime Lusinchi met Friday with relatives of the 14
fishermen and promised they would receive justice.
   In a press briefing, Lusinchi vowed that a military investigation
would get to the truth about the incident near El Amparo, 360 miles
southwest of Caracas.
   ``This grave incident will be investigated with all seriousness
... you can be confident that justice will be done, that
responsibilities will be handed out and the story will be told as it
happened,'' Lusinchi said.
   Relatives of the fishermen have said the men were not involved
with guerrillas and instead were militants of the governing party,
Accion Democratica, out on a picnic when they were ambushed.
   Appearing at the news conference along with Lusinchi, the
commander of the army brigade involved denied innocent civilians had
been massacred, insisting the army had proof of links with Colombian
guerrillas.
   ``Many, many of them had antecedents not only in Venezuela, but
in Colombia,'' Gen. Humberto Camejo Arias said.
   Camejo said army troops had found on the men maps of oil
installations, a list of cattle ranchers in the area, and six or
seven rifles, including a West German-made G-3 rifle used by the
Colombian military.
   Colombian officials have denied the men were guerrillas.
</TEXT>
