<1ST_LINE>r i AM-EEC-Soviets     11-04 0290</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-EEC-Soviets,0296</2ND_LINE>
<BYLINE>EEC, Soviets Wind Up Round of Trade Talks
^By CHRISTINA MACKENZIE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BRUSSELS, Belgium (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Officials of the European Economic
Community and the Soviet Union held two days of ``very
constructive'' talks on a possible trade and cooperation agreement,
an EEC spokeswoman said Friday.
   The discussions marked the first exploratory contacts between the
12-nation trading bloc and a Soviet delegation led by Ivan Ivanov,
vice president of the Soviet state commission for foreign economic
relations.
   The spokeswoman, who demanded anonymity, said further talks would
be held but no time or place had been set.
   A statement from the trading bloc said the Soviets described
economic reforms under way or planned in the communist nation. In
particular, it said, the officials ``underlined the important role
that foreign commerce should play in the Soviet economy in the
future.''
   The EEC expressed the need for better facilities for business
people working in the Soviet Union, such as help in finding office
space and local staff, the spokeswoman said.
   In previous contacts, the Soviets indicated they would be
interested in a cooperation agreement with the European countries
covering a wide variety of areas, including high technology. The
transfer of such sensitive technology to Moscow is tightly
controlled.
   Before the talks, Willy De Clercq, the community's top trade
official, said an eventual agreement with Moscow could cover
cooperation in such areas as the environment, energy, transportation
and exchange of information and statistics.
   The community, also known as the Common Market, signed in June a
declaration establishing official relations with the Soviet-led
socialist economic bloc, called the Council for Mutual Economic
Assistance.
   Moscow's partners in Comecon are East Germany, Poland,
Czechoslovakia, Hungary, Bulgaria and Romania, plus Vietnam, Cuba
and Mongolia.
</TEXT>
