<2ND_LINE>AM-Starved Baby,0213</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Father Convicted Of Starving Son To Death</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MANISTEE, Mich. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A man who blamed his wife for allowing
their 8-week-old son to starve to death was convicted of involuntary
manslaughter six weeks after his wife was convicted of the same
charge.
   It took a Manistee County Circuit Court jury about two hours
Thursday night to find Edward Giddings, 26, guilty in the death of
Raymond LeRoy Giddings in December 1986.
   Giddings was sent to the Manistee County Jail to await
sentencing, a date for which has not been set. His 23-year-old wife,
Mildred, remains in the Mecosta County Jail awaiting sentencing Dec.
5.
   Involuntary manslaughter is punishable by a maximum sentence of
15 years in prison.
   Doctors who testified at the trials said an autopsy ruled out
medical causes for the infant's death, and contended the child
simply wasn't fed.
   Edward Giddings' attorney, Gordon McLellan, argued that Giddings
did not know his son was starving and that his wife told him she was
feeding the child.
   ``It never dawned on me that she could starve my kid,'' Giddings
testified Thursday. ``She told me she knew what she was doing.''
   The couple has another son, who is living with grandparents in
Washington state.
</TEXT>
