<HEAD>Share Prices Rebound On Tokyo Exchange</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: LEADS throughout with end of Saturday trading. No pickup.</NOTE>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Share prices rebounded on the Tokyo Stock Exchange
despite a decline early Saturday during half-day trading.
   The Nikkei Stock Average of 225 selected issues, a 32.01-point
loser the previous trading day, gained 93.50 points, or 0.33
percent, to close at 28,046.75.
   Dealers said the index recovered from its early 99.21-point loss
because of last-minute selective buying of large capital issues
including steels and real estate issues.
   ``Investors, especially institutional ones, are still strongly
interested in buying stocks with prospects for higher share
prices,'' said one dealer.
   The main economic barometer started lower following a 2.89-point
decline in the Dow Jones industrial average in New York. Dealers
also attributed the early Nikkei loss to a lower-than-expected U.S.
jobless rate.
   The U.S. Labor Department reported Friday that the October
unemployment rate stood at 5.3 percent, 0.1 percentage point lower
than September's 5.4 percent.
   ``But investors were expecting the rate to be somewhere around
5.5 percent,'' said a dealer with Daiwa Securities, speaking on
condition of anonymity.
   Volume on the first section stood at 750 million shares.
   The foreign exchange market is closed Saturdays.
</TEXT>
