<FILEID>AP-NR-11-04-88 2333EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a AM-GorillaMyDreams     11-04 0270</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Gorilla My Dreams,0276</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>It's Not Happening At The Zoo</HEAD>
<DATELINE>GULF BREEZE, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Zookeepers hoping for little gorillas
have brought big gorillas Colossus and Muke together, but so far it
seems that the primate couple is still in the dating phase.
   Colossus, at 6-foot-2 and some 570 pounds is said to be the
largest gorilla in captivity, but he's inexperienced in the gorilla
mating game. He hadn't seen another gorilla since infancy until he
was introduced to Muke.
   Muke (pronounced Moo-key) is one of the largest female gorillas
in captivity at 4-foot-8, and she knows how to throw her 274 pounds
around. She has a reputation for being ornery, said Pat Quinn,
director of The Zoo.
   ``He's exerting his male dominance, but she takes care of
herself,'' Quinn said Thursday. ``He gets a scratch or a snitch from
Muke everytime he gets hold of her. She's not too intimidated by
him.''
   Both gorillas are about 22, and began sharing the large gorilla
yard at The Zoo last month. Muke is on breeding loan from the St.
Louis Zoo.
   If the two don't mate, Colossus' keepers won't take it to heart.
The main purpose of Muke's visit is to socialize Colossus to gorilla
ways, said Quinn. If they appear unlikely to mate, a known breeding
female will be obtained, he said.
   It may just be a matter of time.
   It's a good sign, said Quinn, that Colossus herds Muke into her
separate sleeping quarters, and he pointed out both animals have
become slimmer and trimmer since meeting.
   ``They say when you're in love you lose weight,'' he said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
