<FILEID>AP-NR-11-04-88 2233EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u p AM-Dukakis 3rdLd-Writethru a0800 11-04 0857</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Dukakis, 3rd Ld-Writethru, a0800,870</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>RETRANSMITTING a0808 to correct cycle designator.</HEAD>
<HEAD>Dukakis Says He's Surging, Ridicules Bush's Populist Pledge</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Political Rdp Bjt</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: INSERTS three grafs with Chicago speech after 4th pvs, Also
joining..., EDITS to tighten, and elminates former reference to
hoarseness.
^By JOHN KING</NOTE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Michael Dukakis said Friday his underdog bid for
the White House is gaining steam in the campaign's final days and
accused rival George Bush of taking ``a furlough from the truth'' in
proclaiming support for average Americans.
   ``He's slipping and we're surging,'' the Democratic nominee told
a rally in New York before heading to Kentucky and to Illinois.
   In Chicago he joined four former rivals for his party's
nomination in the Democrats' traditional torchlight parade. Marching
with him were Illinois Sen. Paul Simon, Chicagoan Jesse Jackson,
Tennessee Sen. Al Gore Jr. and former Arizona Gov. Bruce Babbitt.
   Also joining Dukakis was his wife, Kitty, who was hospitalized
earlier this week with a viral infection.
   Dukakis had been growing increasingly hoarse in this final week,
but Friday at a rally after the Chicago parade his voice came back.
He was also responding to a CBS poll that showed George Bush's lead
narrowing to seven points.
   ``In 1960, John Kennedy and Lyndon Johnson went into that last
weekend down eight points in the polls,'' he told an audience that
went to its feet more than a dozen time. ``We're doing better than
that. You can feel that surge and you can feel that excitement.''
   Dukakis aides say that state polls show the race is tightening in
the key battlegrounds of the Midwest and that Dukakis also has drawn
within striking distance in New Jersey, a state he had all but
written off until this week.
   Dukakis campaign vice chairman John Sasso said Dukakis likely
would add a second campaign stop in Texas on Saturday and was
considering returning to Ohio.
   His New York rally in the city's Forest Hills section was a bid
to block recent Bush inroads among white middle-class voters in
traditional Democratic areas.
   Dukakis, who has dedicated the closing month of the campaign to a
populist appeal with the rallying cry ``I'm on your side,''
ridiculed Bush for borrowing the line in a speech Thursday.
   ``Yesterday, if you can believe it, Mr. Bush took a furlough from
the truth by saying that he was on the side of working American
families. Can you believe that?'' an indignant Dukakis told a crowd
of several thousand people. ``Four days before the election, after
all the symbols and slogans, four days before the election, he tells
you he's on your side. Who's he kidding?''
   The Massachusetts governor's derisive use of the word
``furlough'' also was a slap back at Bush. The word has figured
prominently in Bush's speeches and advertisements in references to a
convicted murderer who escaped while on furlough from a
Massachusetts prison and attacked a Maryland couple.
   Dukakis also criticized Bush's call for a capital gains tax cut,
calling it an unfair windfall for the rich.
   ``He wants to help people who already have it made,'' Dukakis
said. ``We're going to help every American family make it.''
   Dukakis resumed that criticism before a crowd of about 1,500
people who braved a steady rain and gusting winds to attend and
airport rally in Lexington, Ky.
   ``We know whose side he's on,'' Dukakis told the enthusiastic
crowd. ``He's for a $30,000 tax break for the wealthiest 1 percent
of the people in this country.''
   And in New York, Dukakis listed as well his proposals for health
care, economic development and a higher minimum wage and assailed
Bush's record on deficit spending, the environment and the drug war.
   ``They want the American people to forget that they stole from
our children in piling up the biggest debt in history,'' Dukakis
said of the Republicans. ``They stole from our future by trashing
our environment.''
   He also said it was time for a Democratic administration to
``take back our government from the influence peddlers and sleaze
merchants.''
   Dukakis invoked the legacy of Harry Truman and Kennedy in
predicting a close win Tuesday.
   ``Twenty-eight years ago, another son of Massachusetts challenged
us to win the race to the moon, and we did,'' Dukakis said. ``As
president, I want to challenge the people of American to one
fundamental goal: drug-free schools in the 1990s.''
   He repeated his promise to halt foreign aid to countries refusing
to cooperate in international efforts to curb drug trafficking,
again using the strong rhetoric he began on Wednesday.
   ``I'll be damned if I'm going to let them send that stuff into
our country and poison our kids and destroy our neighborhoods,''
Dukakis said.
   In an interview Friday with ABC-TV, Dukakis again brought up
drugs when answering a question on why he thought Bush was running a
negative campaign.
   ``The real question is, `Why has he done this?' and I think it's
to divert attention from a failed record on the war against drugs,
from the kind of sleaze and corruption that we've seen in
Washington,'' he said. ``I think that's what's going on.''
</TEXT>
