<1ST_LINE>r i AM-WasteShip     11-04 0225</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Waste Ship,0230</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>West German Freighter Carrying Waste Sails Into Black Sea</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ISTANBUL, Turkey (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A West German ship turned back by Turkey
because it carried waste material returned to the Black Sea on
Friday after a month in Istambul because of rough seas, a port
source said.
   The source, who spoke on condition he not be identified, told The
Associated Press that the Petersberg, accompanied by three Coast
Guard ships, crossed the Bosporus into international waters of the
Black Sea Friday.
   He said he did not know if the ship would go elsewhere or would
drop anchor in international waters, where it had been from mid-July
until Oct. 4.
   Efforts to reach the ship's captain by radio proved unavailing.
   Ayla Yenidunya, a spokeswoman for the Marti shipping agency, said
Marti stopped representing the Hamburg-based Nielsen shipping
company last month. Nielsen had contracted the ship.
   Turkey barred the Petersberg from its waters when it arrived in
May, intending to dump the waste in Turkey.
   The ship manifest listed the 1,300-ton cargo as industrial sand,
but Turkey's Atomic Energy Commission said an examination showed the
cargo to be a mixture of rubble, pitch, mud, sand and rotten plants.
   The waste originated in Vienna. In a Bonn-datelined dispatch,
Turkey's semi-official Anatolia news agency said West Germany asked
Austria on Friday to take the cargo back.
</TEXT>
