<1ST_LINE>r i AM-MothInvasion     11-04 0165</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Moth Invasion,0169</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Moths Dead and Alive Plague Australian Senate</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CANBERRA, Australia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Thousands of moths are dying daily
inside Australia's new Parliament house after being attracted by its
powerful lights, causing a terrible stench and distracting lawmakers
from their work.
   The moths are blocking windows and doorways, littering corridors
and entering the building's air-conditioning system.
   Legislators complained that the tiny flying creatures make it
hard for them to concentrate.
   Minister for Science Barry Jones believes the insects are drawn
to a brightly lit flagpole on Capitol Hill and that the building's
stone-lined walls and recessed windows provide a perfect environment
for the moths, who are killed when they fly into the lights.
   The moths are en route to their summer breeding grounds but
apparently are confused by the bright lights of the building, said
Ebbe Nielsen, a leading Australian moth and butterfly expert.
   An estimated 40 million moths now are in the vicinity of the new
Parliament, which was opened this year.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
