<1ST_LINE>a a PM-BorderRelations ADV10   11-04 0794</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Border Relations, ADV 10,0820</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>$Adv10</NOTE>
<NOTE>For Release Thursday PMs, Nov. 10, and Thereafter</NOTE>
<HEAD>Skirmishes in Detroit-Windsor Relations</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By GRETEL WIKLE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>DETROIT (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The smokestack of Detroit's planned trash-burning
incinerator is but another protrusion among the steeples and water
towers rising in an area just north of downtown.
   But in neighboring Windsor, Ontario, the smokestack ranks high on
a growing list of irritants straining relations between the border
cities.
   Fear that the $438 million incinerator's smokestack will send
clouds of acid rain over Canada troubles Windsor, but it's far from
the only problem for the city across the Detroit River from the
sixth-largest U.S. city.
   In the last several months, the cities' ability to get along also
has been challenged by the behavior of Americans in Windsor, concern
about a spill over of drugs and crime from Detroit and the expansion
of Detroit City Airport.
   Even so, Windsor's 200,000 residents acknowledge the benefits of
being Detroit's foreign neighbor.
   The two cities celebrate their friendship every year with the
Freedom Festival, which coincides with Canada's Dominion Day, July
1, and the Fourth of July.
   It was shortly after last year's festival that the incinerator
issue ignited.
   Numerous protests, including one at the construction site in
which 19 demonstrators were arrested, have kept the attention high.
The province of Ontario has sued Detroit to force the city to add
$10 million to $20 million worth of pollution controls, including
lime scrubbers, which remove acidic gases produced when plastic bags
and table salt burn.
   The legal challenge was dismissed in U.S. District Court in
February, but the Canadians appealed to the 6th U.S. Circuit Court
of Appeals in Cincinnati, and Jim Bradley, the province's
environment minister, said Ontario will appeal to the U.S. Supreme
Court if necessary.
   Detroit Mayor Coleman Young has predicted defeat of the action,
which he calls ill-conceived. He said the demands would require
spending money on pollution equipment that is yet to be proved
effective.
   ``Obviously when and if it's proven we'll be willing to take a
hard look at it because whatever falls in Windsor falls first in
Detroit,'' Young said.
   Said Windsor Mayor David A. Burr: ``We recognize that when he
(Young) makes up his mind on something, it's very difficult to get
something changed.''
   Burr cited the expansion of Detroit City Airport as another
example of Young's stubbornness.
   The Windsor mayor, concerned about increased air traffic and the
potential for a collision over Windsor, said he asked for a joint
meeting of the two cities' governing boards to discuss the airport
issue and other concerns but never received an answer. Young notes
that planes heading for Windsor fly over Detroit, too.
   Detroit does not seem to be exporting its violent crime across
the border. The three homicides in Canada's City of Roses last year
translate to about 1.5 per 100,000 people. That compares with 645 in
Detroit, or about 54 for every 100,000 people.
   ``I don't really think at this point we can see an increase in
crime,'' said Staff Sgt. John Abbey of the Windsor Police Department.
   Earlier this year, when Windsor police began setting up roadside
stations Friday and Saturday nights where randomly selected drivers
are tested for alcohol consumption, the crackdown raised complaints,
but not from the U.S. side.
   Canadian bar owners said it would scare off young American
patrons who cross the border because they can legally drink at 19,
two years younger than in Michigan.
   A U.S. Customs Service program to tighten control over the
cross-border transport of illegal drugs has resulted in scores of
arrests and seizures of vehicles. Most of those arrested have been
Americans returning from Canada.
   In general, the cross-border passage is cooperative, and now
there's a proposal for a pedestrian ferry.
   Alexander Pollock, an architect for Detroit's Community and
Economic Development Department, said the ferry would make access to
Windsor hotels easier for people attending conventions in Detroit.
   It's a welcome idea in Windsor, where two large hotels are being
built.
   Canada bought $19.2 billion in merchandise in 1986 from Michigan
and four other Great Lakes states, said Paul Bondy, director of the
Windsor and Essex County Development Commission.
   In turn, Michigan, Indiana, Illinois, Ohio and Wisconsin bought
$16 billion worth of goods from Canada, Bondy said.
   ``Windsor being a lot closer to downtown Detroit than the suburbs
makes us a direct beneficiary of overflow from conventions,'' said
Sergio Grando, general manager of Windsor's visitor's bureau, adding
that Windsor's shops and restaurants, especially the outdoor cafes
along Ouellette Avenue, draw Americans with their European style.
   The Detroit mayor's response: ``Our prosperity reflects itself in
Windsor, and so cooperation would be to me what we ought to be
about.''
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for Thurs PMs, Nov. 10</NOTE>
</DOC>
