<NOTE>For Release PMs Monday Nov. 7</NOTE>
<HEAD>Sunpower: Manufacturers From Dreary Michigan Shine In Solar Car
Racing</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: John Cunniff is on vacation.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By WILLIAM S. BERGSTROM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   People who race today's thin-skinned, knee-high solar-powered
vehicles don't expect the sun to propel commuter traffic anytime
soon.
   But two of Michigan's corporate giants say other benefits make
solar cars worthwhile.
   Dow Chemcial Co. has been the primary sponsor for the last two
years of a Massachusetts Institute of Technology program that built
the winner of the America Solar Cup race in September in California.
   General Motors Corp.'s Sunraycer won the world's first
transcontinental solar car race, held in November 1987 in Australia.
   Dow and GM aren't talking about mass solar-powered transit, any
more than the Wright brothers with their fragile sand-dune flyer
envisioned cargo and passenger-carrying jumbo jets.
   At today's efficiency levels, solar cars are fair-sky vehicles
ideal for the sun-baked Australian outback or Southern California.
   In Michigan, for example, the glimmer of a winter day when the
sun is mostly a memory would scarcely move the specialized race
vehicles, let alone power the all-out daily four-lane sprint to work
or end-of-the-day dash home.
   GM and Dow are enthused, nevertheless. While neither company
divulges what it spends on the special programs, both said the
benefits go beyond the advertising value of having their names on
cars that skitter to racing wins.
   MIT senior James Worden, 21, heads the Dow-supported design team
that built Solectria V, a 12-foot-long racer that basically
resembles a flat array of solar cells topped by a bubble canopy.
   Dow Automotive Materials Group provided materials, technical help
and money for the car, one of the stars of an ESPN television
feature on solar-car racing.
   Dow spokesman Rick Proskow said the car represents an opportunity
to try out its superthin chromaloy tubing, carbon fiber composites,
epoxies and magnesium and aluminum components.
   It weighs just 340 pounds and can travel more than 70 miles an
hour using a power system that generates only 10 horsepower. It
finished the 159.3-mile California race in just over three hours,
averaging 53.1 miles an hour.
   ``There is a great similarity between the car James Worden drives
and what has been done with similar materials in the general
automotive field,'' said spokeswoman Linda Water, who accompanied
the racing team.
   Worden is improving the car, Water said, though ``James is very
close-mouthed about these things. He keeps his briefcase very close
to him.''
   GM's teardrop-shaped vehicle is 20 feet long and weighs 390
pounds. It chalked up a 2{-day victory in a 5{-day World Solar
Challenge race across Australia in November 1987.
   Making it provided lessons in lightweight structures and
materials, efficient lightweight motors and aerodynamics, Bruce
McCristal, a GM spokesman said.
   The Sunraycer is the most aerodynamic land vehicle that has ever
been tested in GM's wind tunnel, he said.
   It has been taken on tour, appearing at more than 130 different
events, and has proven a powerful lure in piquing interest among
school children in science studies, McCristal said.
   A GM educational program based on the car _ including teachers
manuals, students' workbooks and a computer game that simulates
driving it _ has brought strong response from science teachers
across the country.
   ``There isn't really a commercial payoff,'' Proskow agreed.
``We're certainly not going to go out and sell thousands and
thousands of pounds of resin for solar cars. Not today.''
   But he said Dow also values the educational potential.
   ``It gives us an opportunity to support an alternative type of
power and to support a person in college with a good idea. As a
chemical company we are an inventive group. Technology is important
to Dow,'' he said.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv PMs Monday Nov. 7</NOTE>
