<HEAD>Bush Solid Favorite, But Little Coattails Effect Seen</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MONTGOMERY, Ala. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   George Bush was a solid favorite to pick
up Alabama's nine electoral votes Tuesday, but Republicans had
little hope of making substantial gains in state and local races.
   A record 274 GOP nominees were running for office in Alabama, but
state GOP political director Steve French predicted only modest
coattails from the national ticket even in a landslide.
   Alabama went for President Reagan in 1980 and 1984, and Bush was
the lopsided favorite over Democrat Michael Dukakis in a series of
polls over the past two months.
   The makeup of the state's congressional delegation _ five
Democrats and two Republicans _ was not expected to change. The
closest race was in the 1st District between Republican Rep. Sonny
Callahan and Democratic challenger John Tyson.
</TEXT>
