<HEAD>Dukakis Favored in Democratic Bastion</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Michael Dukakis carried a wide lead over
Republican George Bush into Tuesday's balloting for the District of
Columbia's three electoral votes.
   No polls have been conducted in the nation's capital to gain a
sense of the voting, but the Democratic candidate has carried the
city by a wide margin in each of the last fiv presidential
elections. For example, Walter Mondale received 85 percent of the
vote in 1984, as he was being trounced nationally by President
Reagan.
   Walter Fauntroy, the city's non-voting delegate to Congress, was
expected to easily retain his seat. The Democrat, a black minister
and veteran of the civil rights movement, had only token opposition
to his bid for a tenth term.
