<NOTE>$Adv08</NOTE>
<NOTE>For Release Tues AMs, Nov. 8</NOTE>
<HEAD>Bitter U.S. House Race Highlight of Georgia Ballot</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ATLANTA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A House race called one of the nation's nastiest
came to a close Tuesday with Republican Rep. Pat Swindall fighting
both to save his political career and stay out of jail.
   In the presidential race, Republican George Bush was expected to
win Georgia's 12 electoral votes, despite a late surge of
campaigning on behalf of Democrat Michael Dukakis by popular Sen.
Sam Nunn.
   Swindall was expected to lose his 4th Congressional District seat
to Democratic challenger Ben Jones, a recovered alcoholic who played
``Cooter'' in television's ``Dukes of Hazzard'' series.
   Jones narrowly lost to Swindall in 1986. This year's race was
marked by Swindall's repeated references to Jones' arrest record,
especially an assault conviction. Jones, who says he has not had a
drink since 1977, said the incident dates to his drinking days and
involved shoving his second wife in a bar.
   Last month, Swindall was indicted on federal perjury charges
stemming from his testimony to a grand jury investigating a
money-laundering case. He sought a trial before the election as
polls showed Jones a 2-1 favorite in the suburban Atlanta district,
but the jury was dismissed after Swindall's campaign sent out
leaflets saying he had passed a lie detector test.
   Democrats currently hold eight of the state's 10 U.S. House seats.
</TEXT>
