<NOTE>For Release Tues AMs, Nov. 8</NOTE>
<HEAD>Lottery Top Issue on Thin Idaho Ballot</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BOISE, Idaho (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A spirited fight over a statewide lottery
dominated the attention of Idaho voters, who were virtually certain
to award their four electoral votes to Vice President George Bush.
   Rep. Richard Stallings, outspending GOP businessman Dane Watkins
by three-to-one, was all but assured of becoming the first Democrat
to win three straight congressional elections in the conservative
southern district. Four-term Republican Rep. Larry Craig was favored
to hold onto the state's other U.S. House seat.
   Opponents of a constitutional amendment allowing a state lottery
spent $500,000 in an effort to turn the voters around from 1986,
when a lottery initiative captured 60 percent of the vote. That
measure was voided by the state Supreme Court on grounds as an
attempt to circumvent the constitutional prohibition against any
lottery.
   Supporters pushed the proposition on economic grounds, arguing
that Idahoans were spending money on lotteries in neighboring
Washington, Oregon and Montana that should remain in the state.
   Critics said a lottery would strip the poor of money they need
for necessities and open the door to casino gambling and the moral
ills that go with it.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Advance</NOTE>
