<NOTE>For Release Tues AMs, Nov. 8</NOTE>
<HEAD>GOP Hopes to Pick Up Deep South Senate Seat</HEAD>
<DATELINE>JACKSON, Miss. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Republican Rep. Trent Lott hoped to put
both of Mississippi's Senate seats in the GOP column for the first
time this century, as he battled Democratic Rep. Wayne Dowdy for the
seat of the retiring John Stennis.
   Vice President George Bush appeared to have the state's seven
electoral votes locked up. Democrat Michael Dukakis trailed since
the beginning of the campaign and made little headway among blacks
who supported Jesse Jackson in the March Super Tuesday primary.
   Lott stressed his links to the Reagan administration and Bush in
his bid for the Senate seat. Dowdy, who like Lott surrendered a safe
congressional seat for the race, tried to avoid tying his campaign
to Dukakis. He spent $1.5 million on the election _ half of what
Lott spent.
   Thad Cochran's election in 1978 made him the state's first
Republican senator in more than 100 years. Stennis campaigned for
Dowdy by appealing to voters not to turn both seats over to the GOP.
   Three Democratic congressmen seeking re-election all were
expected to win, including Mike Espy, the state's first black
congressman in more than 100 years. Voters will pick two new
congressmen to fill the seats vacated by Lott and Dowdy.
</TEXT>
