<HEAD>Tight Senate Race, Easy Time for Bush</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CARSON CITY, Nev. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Republican Sen. Chic Hecht battled for a
second term against popular Democratic Gov. Dick Bryan on Tuesday,
the incumbent buoyed by polls that showed him climbing from underdog
to virtually even.
   In the presidential race, state Republican Chairman Steve Wark
predicted George Bush would take Nevada's four electoral votes with
a victory margin as high as 25 percent. But Democrats said
Massachusetts Gov. Michael Dukakis still had a chance.
   The Senate race had opened with Hecht trailing as much as 30
points in opinion polls. But it ended a tossup, with Bryan claiming
a lead of 10 percent or more and Hecht, helped by President Reagan's
last-minute visit, releasing polls showing a 2-point edge for the
governor.
   Bryan suffered late in the campaign when Dukakis reversed himself
and said he accepted Congress' designation of Nevada as the site for
the nation's first high-level nuclear waste repository.
   Democratic Rep. Jim Bilbray and Republican Rep. Barbara
Vucanovich both appeared headed for re-election.
