<HEAD>Strong Anti-Smoking Measure on Ballot as Dukakis Holds Slim Lead</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PORTLAND, Ore. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A proposal for the strictest statewide
anti-smoking law in the nation went before Oregon voters Tuesday, as
did a presidential race rated too close to call.
   The initiative measure would ban smoking in virtually all
workplaces and public accommodations. It made Oregon a key
battleground for tobacco companies, which put $2 million into their
fight to defeat the proposal.
   In the presidential race, Democrat Michael Dukakis held a slim
lead over Republican George Bush in a poll four weeks before the
election. But state GOP Chairman T.J. Bailey predicted Bush would
win 55 percent of the vote to capture the state's seven electoral
votes.
   Oregonians also will vote on measures to repeal Gov. Neil
Goldschmidt's order barring state government discrimination against
homosexuals, require seat belt use by all motorists and increase
cigarette and beer taxes to help finance college sports.
   The three Democrats and two Republicans in the Oregon House
delegation all sought re-election.
   Portland Mayor Bud Clark, an exuberant tavern owner, was favored
to win a second four-year term in a race against a former police
chief.
</TEXT>
