<HEAD>South Carolina Republicans Smelling Victory</HEAD>
<DATELINE>COLUMBIA, S.C. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Two spirited congressional races topped the
ballot in South Carolina, where Republican George Bush's dominance
in the presidential race over Democrat Michael Dukakis was never in
doubt.
   Bush's efforts in the state, which offered eight electoral votes,
were bolstered by Gov. Carroll Campbell, his Southern campaign
chairman, and Aiken native Lee Atwater, his national campaign
manager.
   In the 2nd District, Republican Rep. Floyd Spence came from
near-death and a double-lung transplant in May to lead Columbia
banker and attorney Jim Leventis. Spence, seeking his 10th term,
attacked Leventis as a liberal, while the challenger accused Spence
of being ineffective.
   Fourth District Rep. Liz Patterson, a first-term Democrat, faced
a tough challenge from Republican Knox White, a Greenville attorney
and city councilman. White accused Ms. Patterson of being too
liberal for the district, while the incumbent called herself an
independent thinker running against an opponent with a ``bumper
sticker mentality.'' Republicans were intent on reclaiming the seat
held by Campbell until his successful 1986 run for governor.
   Currently, Democrats hold four of the state's six congressional
seats.
</TEXT>
