<HEAD>Democratic Challenger Ted Wilson Leads Incumbent Governor</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SALT LAKE CITY (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Former Democratic Salt Lake City Mayor Ted
Wilson, riding the crest of voter dissatisfaction with Gov. Norm
Bangerter, carried a shrinking lead in the polls into Tuesday's
election against the Republican incumbent and a tax-cutting
independent.
   Vice President George Bush, meanwhile, was expected to have no
trouble taking Utah's five electoral votes from Democrat Michael
Dukakis, and GOP Sen. Orrin Hatch was the prohibitive favorite for a
third term over Democrat Brian Moss.
   The first-term Bangerter angered voters with a record $166
million tax increase in 1986 and trailed Wilson by as much as 30
percentage points in polls. But he closed the gap to 40 percent to
32 percent in a Salt Lake Tribune poll released Oct. 30. Merrill
Cook, a Republican-turned-independent who has championed three
tax-cutting ballot initiatives, polled 26 percent.
   Those initiatives, which would reduce state and local government
revenue by more than $300 million, appeared headed for defeat.
   Republican Rep. Howard Nielson and Democratic Rep. Wayne Owens
appeared headed for re-election. But the state's third congressman,
GOP Rep. James Hansen, was in a tough fight with Democrat Gunn
McKay, whom Hansen ousted in 1980.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Advance</NOTE>
