<HEAD>Voters Choose Successor to Proxmire, Decide Tight Presidential Race</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MILWAUKEE (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A multimillionaire sports team owner battled the
only woman nominated by a major party for the Senate this year as
Wisconsin voters picked a successor to William Proxmire on Tuesday.
   Democrat Herbert Kohl, the Milwaukee Bucks basketball team owner
whose fortune came from a chain of grocery stores, competed against
state Senate Minority Leader Susan Engeleiter, the Republican
nominee.
   In the presidential race, a sizable lead in public opinion polls
for Democrat Michael Dukakis over Republican George Bush had
evaporated and the state chairmen of both political parties were
predicting their man would claim the prize of 11 electoral votes.
   The Senate race was marked by heavy campaign spending, a sharp
contrast to the low-budget campaigns of Proxmire, a Democrat who
announced his retirement early this year.
   Polls had shown Kohl with a healthy lead, but the race appeared
to tighten and Engeleiter's campaign was boosted the week before the
election by a visit from President Reagan.
   Wisconsin's five Democratic and four Republican congressmen were
expected to win re-election. In the 7th District, Democratic Rep.
David Obey faced Kevin Hermening, a former hostage in Iran, in a
rematch of their 1986 clash.
