<FILEID>AP-NR-11-04-88 0554EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>a a AM-Vets-MissinginAmerica ADV10-2Takes   11-04 1113</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Vets-Missing in America, ADV 10-2 Takes,1138</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>$Adv10</NOTE>
<NOTE>For Release Thurs AMs, Nov. 10, and Thereafter</NOTE>
<HEAD>From Platoon to Prison: Road of Despair for Thousands of Veterans</HEAD>
<HEAD>An AP Extra</HEAD>
<NOTE>With LaserPhoto</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By SHARON COHEN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JACKSON, Mich. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Phil Reibel went to Vietnam, a gentle man
in a time of war. He returned, a violent man in a time of peace.
   So began his odyssey from platoon to prison.
   Today, the Marine veteran passes his days behind gates, his
nights behind bars, doing time for brutally assaulting his son. He's
not sure Vietnam put him there, but he has no doubts the war turned
him inside out.
   ``Before I went to Vietnam, I never had any violent streaks,''
said the bearded, 41-year-old Reibel. ``When I came back, I had
nothing but violent streaks. ... The day I came home and the day
before I left, I was a completely different person.''
   Reibel is among thousands of Vietnam veterans in prisons
nationwide who wonder whether their time as warriors in jungles half
a world away helped turn them into criminals on the streets at home.
   Five years ago and long after he came home, Reibel beat his
teen-age son and pushed him over a stool. The boy's head hit the TV,
temporarily paralyzing him. Reibel's sentence: 6 years, 8 months, to
10 years.
   ``I had no control over myself at that time,'' Reibel said. `` As
far as guilt, shame, I'll have to suffer that forever. ... I'm doing
a life sentence.''
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   Like other Vietnam veterans, Reibel's war story began in a
distant land. A generation later, it's still being written _ back
home, in a prison cell.
   ``They're one of the forgotten legacies of the war,'' said Wayne
Smith, membership services director of Vietnam Veterans of America
and a former Army medic who served time for manslaughter.
   ``There are those who are missing in action, and there are those
who are missing in America ... the incarcerated veteran,'' he said.
``The problem is very real. It's one we don't look at daily because
of the height of the walls. Nevertheless, they're there. There's a
key turned every day.''
   These men have become prisoners of war of another sort. At the
end of 1987, state prisons held 20,876 veterans who served in
Southeast Asia in the Vietnam era, Justice Department records show.
Another survey, taken in 1979, found 12,957 inmates in such prisons.
Federal prison officials have no such breakdown.
   Thousands more Vietnam vets have previously served time or are on
probation or parole, experts say. And a recent survey found 470,000
vets, one in seven, suffer from post traumatic stress disorder, a
psychological condition sometimes marked by flashbacks and
nightmares that has been cited in criminal defenses.
   That condition was linked to two vets who have been executed. One
argued that flashbacks drove him to kill a rookie policeman. The
second man, who killed two people in a robbery, dug foxholes beneath
his house and locked himself in his room after he returned from the
war.
   Some experts suspect a higher proportion of Vietnam veterans
ended up in prison than those who served in other wars, although no
statistics support that.
   The reasons they give for the perceived higher incidence of
imprisonment: the nature of the war _ no clear enemy lines _ and
lack of decompression time.
   ``Vietnam combat veterans were guerilla fighters and (moved) from
the theater of war to their home porch often in less than 36
hours,'' said John Wilson, a Cleveland State University psychology
professor and expert on post traumatic stress.
   ``It's almost like a deep sea diver coming up too quickly and
getting the bends,'' explained Charles Figley, Purdue University
professor of family therapy and psychology.
   Many still thought like warriors. ``A lot of the men were walking
around with jungle-trained survival instincts,'' Wilson said. ``They
were prepared to react to stress incidents as they did in Vietnam.''
   One Michigan inmate, Jim Armstrong, explains: ``You go over there
and you kill as many of them as you can before they kill you. The
whole time in your training ... it was ... kill, kill, kill. What
you don't kill, burn down. So when you come home, it's, `No, man,
don't kill no more. Go back and build Chevrolets.' How can you do
that?''
   Some experts also point out that many young Vietnam soldiers were
poor, with few job skills. When they returned, ``they had two
strikes against them,'' said Michael Boivin, psychology professor at
Spring Arbor College in Michigan.
   ``A lot of these guys were at risk anyway,'' he said. ``I don't
blame Vietnam'' for the criminal acts committed. But for some,
``Vietnam pushed them over the edge.''
   At times, vets say, the war even worked against them in court _
prosecutors portrayed them as Rambos, trained killers, adept with
guns.
   The road from combat soldier to convict is a concern to scholars
and veterans groups, who are conducting studies, testifying before
lawmakers about effects of post war stress and working to establish
halfway houses and a clearinghouse to track these so-called
``forgotten warriors.''
   Vets-turned-inmates do support each other. Of 373 Vietnam
Veterans of America chapters, 24 are in prisons, with 3,000 members.
More are being organized. A Missouri chapter unites inmates with
vets who work at the prison, including the warden, who served five
tours in Vietnam.
   Here in Jackson, two prisons have nearly 200 members in three
chapters. They are grouped by security level.
   In one group, inmates at the State Prison of Southern Michigan,
the world's largest walled prison, speak of a society they say has
victimized them twice _ first branding them murderers, now
stigmatizing them as convicts.
   ``The media and the American people ... (felt) a Vietnam veteran
... was either a babykiller or a walking timebomb,'' said inmate
Armstrong. ``When he lost control once ... they said, `OK, let's put
this timebomb in prison where if he explodes, all he can hurt is
other criminals.'
   ``There's no thought about, well, did the war have anything to do
with it? Should we offer this guy an alternative? Should we put him
in therapy? Should we try to readjust him to society that he didn't
get readjusted to from coming from Vietnam?' No, let's just lock him
up.
   ``We ain't no criminals,'' added Armstrong, who shot his wife in
the jaw during a fight. ``We just made a mistake. ... We as a group
try to figure out how did we end up doing what we did, how did it
happen? Everybody else in (prison) is trying to figure out ... how
did I get caught?''
</TEXT>
<NOTE>MORE</NOTE>
</DOC>
