<DOCNO> AP881104-0265 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-11-04-88 1458EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>a i AM-Burma-Karens ADV14   11-04 0452</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Burma-Karens, ADV 14,0461</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>$Adv14</NOTE>
<NOTE>For Release Mon AMs, Nov. 14, and Thereafter</NOTE>
<HEAD>Karen Guerrillas See Hope for Success in Burma's Upheavals</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Burma-Guerrilla War, b0350-b0351</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DENIS D. GRAY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MANERPLAW, Burma (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   After waging a backwater rebellion for
four decades, Burma's Karens hope the flight of thousands of
students to their remote jungle bases will slot their cause into the
broader struggle against a harsh military government in Rangoon.
   Since the government crushed a popular uprising in September,
more than 5,000 students and others have fled cities in the
heartland to the Thai-Burmese border. Here, the the Karens have
carved out a domain complete with schools, tax collectors, soccer
teams and a fighting force said to number 17,000 guerrillas.
   The Karen National Union, probably the strongest of a dozen
ethnic minority rebel groups, claims to control most of the
1,350-mile frontier and administer roughly 1 million of Burma's 6
million to 7 million Karens. The KNU's weapons are purchased on the
black market of neighboring Thailand with income largely derived
from taxes on massive, cross-border smuggling.
   ``The Burmese population will now have a better view of the
ethnic revolutionary groups because of the students,'' KNU President
Bo Mya said in an interview. ``Together with the students and God's
help we will win the war.''
   Karen leaders also say the recent mass killings of demonstrators
and other human rights violations in Burma may make the
international community and the majority Burmans realize they and
other ethnic minorities have had just cause in fighting the Rangoon
government.
   ``The students will offer some harassment but not enough to make
a difference against a tough, battle-hardened force that has shown
itself to be unified,'' a Western diplomat based in Rangoon said
recently. To date the students have received minimal military
training and malaria has already cut a swath through their ranks.
   The Karens themselves have scored victories in recent months,
taking advantage of the Burmese army's preoccupation with putting
down internal revolt. But the turmoil has also disrupted the massive
cross-border smuggling which funds the KNU.
   KNU territory is administered by 12 departments including those
handling foreign affairs, agriculture and justice. The latter
punishes adultery by 10 years' imprisonment and bans all liquor
sales.
   The strict moral outlook appears to originate from 19th century
American Christian missionaries: KNU leaders are invariably fervent
Baptists or Seventh Day Adventists, attributing their victories to
``God's grace.''
   After Burma was granted independence by Britain in 1948, Karens
rose up in revolt, feeling betrayed by a Rangoon government that was
to have granted ethnic minorities considerable political autonomy
and the right to foster their individual cultures and languages.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for Mon AMs, Nov. 14</NOTE>
</DOC>
