<DOCNO> AP881104-0266 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-11-04-88 0602EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>a a AM-PennRailroad ADV10 1stLd-Writethru 11-04 0825</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Penn Railroad, ADV 10, 1st Ld-Writethru, b0301,0844</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>$Adv10</NOTE>
<NOTE>For Release Thurs AMs, Nov. 10, and Thereafter</NOTE>
<HEAD>From Blueprint to Extortion Note: Learning From Penn RR's Records</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: SUBS 21st graf, bgn, Documents from ..., to CORRECT that PRR
merged in 1968, sted folded</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By ANITA C. HUSLIN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>HARRISBURG, Pa. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   As a century's soot and cobwebs are wiped
from millions of stored-away records, a preservation project is
beginning to document the birth, growth and demise of what some
historians consider America's once most influential company _ the
Pennsylvania Railroad.
   The Pennsylvania Historical and Museum Commission has undertaken
the project with nine other institutions around the nation to save
the company's records, from locomotive blueprints to the personal
correspondence of executives.
   Their goal, according to Robert Dructor, director of the
commission's division of archives and manuscripts, is to organize
the records into a cohesive collection accessible by computer.
   The effort should also help answer questions about the
corporation that was the United States' largest until World War I.
   It started in 1846 as a transportation company but steamrolled
across the Northeast and into the Midwest, consuming competitors,
until it eventually operated steel, oil and coal companies, too.
   While the outlines of the Pennsylvania Railroad's history are
well known, the old documents are revealing intriguing historical
details that fill out the picture.
   One recently discovered 1899 note to the railroad president
threatened to sabotage the rails.
   ``I have blackmailed the PRR Co. for $50,000,'' said the writer,
who signed as Red Mail. ``Don't put me down as a crank or insane, I
am as responsible for what I do as you. I am getting old, poor and
desperate. I may put a limited express over a dump any time.''
   Dructor said archivists have yet to discover whether the
extortionist carried out his threat.
   ``It's still a mystery,'' he said.
   The decline of industry in the Northeast, the growth of the
country's highway systems and development of the commercial air
industry have all been identified as contributors to the
Pennsyvlania Railroad's demise. The paper trail could help show more
precisely how and why, Dructor said.
   Ian S. Fischer, a mechanical engineering professor at New Jersey
Institute of Technology, has delved into some of the documents to
find information about rail freight cars, a long-time fascination
that he hopes, someday, to turn into a book.
   The memoranda, he says, put researchers ``inside things that
happened years ago.'' One example was how freight car designers had
to make changes to accommodate the ``huge demand for industrial
goods by the warring nations of Europe'' just before America entered
World War I.
   The volume of documents is staggering.
   The first phase of the project required the appraisal of some
300,000 cubic feet of records, or about 900 million pages of paper,
Dructor said. Of that, about 8,000 cubic feet were identified to be
saved and approximately 3,600 cubic feet were assigned to the state
archives for processing.
   The two-year project is expected to be completed by February 1990
at a cost of about $260,000, Dructor said. The National Endowment
for the Humanities is providing a $100,000 grant; other
contributions of cash, goods and services completed the funding.
   Documents in the collection range from blueprints and tracings of
Pennsylvania Railroad locomotives, station buildings, bridges and
routes, to photographs of trains, war-era posters, and design
sketches for conductor uniforms. There are also real estate and
accounting books as well as legal papers.
   ``I just couldn't possibly have imagined that there was so much
material going back as far as the 1860s still existing,'' said Joe
Acri, who contacted the state archives looking for details of trains
to help him make accurate models at home.
   After viewing thousands of tracings and blueprints, he said,
``They made drawings of individual nuts, bolts, screws, coat racks,
coat hooks, even the layout of lanterns and tools kept in locomotive
tenders. The detail is phenomenal.''
   Two project archivists and several full-time commission staff
members are sifting the records.
   Documents since 1968, when the railroad merged with the New York
Central to become Penn Central (later Conrail) remain sealed, under
the railroads' policy requiring a 25-year moratorium on opening
corporate papers, Dructor said.
   The documents preceding that time are more than enough to keep
the researchers busy, however. Once completed, they hope the
collection will prove useful to genealogists, archivists and
railroad buffs alike, Dructor said.
   Jean Morris, editor of a magazine for the Western Pennsylvania
Genealogical Society, said the collection could help fill gaps in
family histories of railroad workers.
   ``You can get some insight into the men that worked for the
railroad .. where they lived, how they worked, what jobs they had
with the railroad,'' Mrs. Morris said. ``There are very little
traces of many of them in county records because many of the people
who worked for the railroad moved around so much.''
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for Thurs AMs, Nov. 10</NOTE>
</DOC>
