<FILEID>AP-NR-11-04-88 1322EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>s i BC-Wales-Comeback ADV13   11-04 1199</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Wales-Comeback, ADV 13,1241</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>$Adv13</NOTE>
<NOTE>For Release Sunday, Nov. 13, and Thereafter</NOTE>
<HEAD>Welsh Economy, Weaned off Coal and Steel, Enjoys a Revival</HEAD>
<NOTE>EDS: An accompanying box is BC-Wales-Statistics, b0355.</NOTE>
<HEAD>An AP Extra</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto Planned</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By COTTEN TIMBERLAKE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CARDIFF, Wales (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The scarred and bruised valleys of Wales
are turning green again.
   The proud but downtrodden Celtic nation has painfully weaned
itself from the coal and steel industries that once made it the
energy capital of the world.
   It has wrought a dramatic economic revival based on service
industries and manufacturing that have changed not only the physical
face of Wales but also the way of life of its citizens.
   Many of its 2.8 million people are enjoying a new prosperity, a
new optimism, born of the ecomomic revival of the 1980s.
   The key to its success has been its ability to attract outside
investment and foster local entrepreneurship, both of which are
creating much needed jobs, above ground.
   ``It is probably the fastest changing and fastest growing economy
in Western Europe,'' Peter Walker, the British government's Welsh
secretary, said in an interview. ``I think it's a very exciting
scene.''
   ``All the signs are that the economy is more prosperous than at
any time in the last half century,'' said Roger Mansfield, director
of the University of Wales' Cardiff Business School. ``A complete
change from an industry dominated by coal and steel to a very mixed
economy has opened up a lot of opportunities.''
   The physical transformation is most obvious in its southern
valleys where coal was once king.
   The scarring and bruising were described by the late Welsh writer
Richard Llewellyn in his heart-wrenching, 1939 classic, ``How Green
Was My Valley.''
   ``The first thing I saw was the slag heap,'' said the main
character, a miner's young son called Huw Morgan, about his first
outing after a long convalescence.
   ``Big it had grown, and long and black, without life or sigh,
lying along the bottom of the Valley on both sides of the river. The
green grass, and the reeds and the flowers, all had gone, crushed
beneath it.''
   But today, in a Rhondda Valley spot once covered with coal slag,
you now can find a cluster of luxury homes overlooking two man-made
lakes nestled in green hills.
   This is part of a multimillion-dollar government program to
reclaim and landscape slag heaps all though the valleys.
   ``We're trying to get away from that image of Wales as black and
grimy,'' said Stephen White, a Welsh Development Agency official.
   The revival also is physically visible in the Welsh capital,
Cardiff, where an ambitious, estimated $2.7-billion,
government-supported redevelopment program is under way in the south
side docklands, an area covering 3,000 acres or one third of the
city.
   Meanwhile, men who once went down into the dark mines _ where, as
Huw Morgan well knew, the work was hard and dangerous _ now have
jobs in such places as an insurance company's claims-processing
office or a Japanese-owned television assembly plant.
   Said Lyn Arnold, another Welsh Development Agency official: ``In
most communities, there is somebody doing well, and everybody is
hearing about it.''
   Ian Kelsall, head of the Confederation of British Industry in
Wales, said: ``The shopping centers are flourishing in south Wales,
holiday travel is up. You can see it in membership of golf clubs.''
   Numbers underscore how big a wrench it has been: One man in 100
works in Wales' coal industry today compared with one in three in
the early 1920s.
   Today, the service sector accounts for 65 percent of employment,
manufacturing 24 percent, primary industries such as coal mining 6
percent and construction 5 percent.
   Wales' gross domestic product grew almost 7 percent in 1986, the
most recent year for which the statistics are available, after a
15-percent spurt in 1985. Its manufacturing index stands at 115.9 in
contrast to 100 in 1980.
   The unemployment rate has fallen to 10.3 percent, representing
125,300 people, from a peak of 16.8 percent, or 172,000 people, in
March 1986.
   The turnaround, however, is not without critics.
   They hold that too many Welshmen remain jobless and that the
improvement is confined to the southeast and northeast regions of
Wales, which covers a total area of 8,018 square miles, about the
size of Massachusetts.
   Critics also say Wales' jobs are particularly vulnerable to
cutbacks because they are dependent on inward investment by
companies that are headquartered elsewhere.
   ``It seems a very dangerous situation to have your whole economy
based on outside investment which can be whipped out at any time,''
said Dafydd Williams, general secretary of Plaid Cymru, the Welsh
nationalist party. ``It has been said that most schemes are to take
advantage of cheap labor.''
   The new-found prosperity also has exacerbated a shortage of Welsh
managers, and of skilled workers in general.
   Wales already was running short because the mines didn't create
many managers or teach a wide variety of skills, and because
ambitious Welshmen tended to emigrate in the past.
   The Welsh have consistently supported socialist political parties
and many critics blame Wales' economic problems on Prime Minister
Margaret Thatcher's capitalist economic policies. Nationalists blame
what they see as Wales' loss of independence.
   Wales was brought under English rule by King Edward I in 1282 and
united with England in 1536. Today it sends 38 members to the House
of Commons, eight of whom are Conservative.
   It was the recession of the early 1980s that broke the backs of
the long-declining, overmanned coal and steel industries.
   Wales was harder hit by that downturn than other areas of
Britain, as intertwined pits and foundries were closed.
   Massive layoffs cut the number of coal workers from 30,000 in
1979 to 7,500 today, and the number of steel workers from 55,000 to
20,000, the Welsh Office said.
   Overall employment levels since have been helped by the
significant amount of job-creating inward investment in
manufacturing and services by the Japanese and other foreign
investors, some of whom have been seeking a European foothold before
1992, when the European Economic Community is to become barrier-free.
   Last year, Wales became the favorite location in Britain for
overseas investors, who also have been attracted by financial lures
and by the proximity to London, which is under 150 miles to the east.
   Wales won 302 investments in 1987, or one-fifth of all the
investment that came into Britain, according to the Invest in
Britain Bureau.
   Many jobs have also been created by the emerging Welsh
entrepreneurship.
   ``It used to be said at one time that the Welsh aren't
entrepreneurs, that they are teachers and preachers,'' Kelsall said.
   But, ironically, severance payments gave laid-off miners the
capital to start their own businesses.
   As a result, Wales counted 152,000 self-employed people last
December, compared with 115,000 in 1975, the Welsh Office said.
   These optimists have created a mixed bag of farming and local
service companies, and small manufacturers are starting to export
their products, Arnold said, with pride.
   Walker said: ``Now bright young men are staying in Wales and a
lot of bright young Welshmen who left are coming back.''
   As little Huw Morgan would have said, ``There is lovely.''
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for Sunday, Nov. 13</NOTE>
