<2ND_LINE>PM-Business Highlights, Two Takes,0536</2ND_LINE>
<DATELINE>ATLANTA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   RJR Nabisco Inc.'s management are making a
sweetened $20.7 billion cash-and-stock offer for the food and
tobacco giant, raising the stakes from an earlier record bid from a
powerful New York buyout firm.
   Management and its financial partners said Thursday they would
pay $84 in cash and $8 in securities for each share of RJR Nabisco,
slightly more than the $90-a-share tender offer launched by Kohlberg
Kravis Roberts & Co. and higher than an initial $75 a share buyout
proposed by management.
   Either deal, if successful, would rank as the largest U.S.
takeover ever.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   After months of strong resistance, Macmillan Inc.
threw its support behind British publisher Robert Maxwell's $2.51
billion takeover offer for the publishing and information services
giant.
   The move Thursday paved the way for Maxwell's successful
completion of his tender offer for all of Macmillan's shares and his
biggest step yet toward his goal of creating a global communications
powerhouse.
   It came one day after the Delaware Supreme Court effectively
blocked Macmillan from proceeding with an agreement to sell the
company to an investment group that included the buyout firm
Kohlberg Kravis Roberts & Co. and Macmillan's senior management.
</TEXT>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Long-dormant apparel sales continued reviving during October, but
consumers still spent gingerly on other merchandise, the nation's
largest general retailers report.
   Sears, Roebuck and Co. said Thursday its overall sales were up
7.5 percent last month, while K mart Corp. said its sales rose 5.8
percent and Wal-Mart Stores Inc. reported its sales rose 24 percent.
   But several analysts contended October's results looked better
than they really were, because they were being compared against the
very weak sales of a year earlier.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>DETROIT (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   U.S. automakers say they sold 7.9 percent more
cars and light trucks in late October this year compared with the
same month last year, when consumers were feeling the initial impact
of the stock market crash.
   During the Oct. 21-31 period this year, domestic manufacturers
sold 334,237 cars and light trucks, compared with 344,190 during the
same time last year, the companies said Thursday.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>HONOLULU (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The federal deposit insurance system was never
intended to cover the catastrophic losses now being generated by the
nation's savings and loan institutions, the top federal S&L
regulator says.
   M. Danny Wall, chairman of the Federal Home Loan Bank Board, said
Thursday that when Congress set up deposit insurance in the wake of
the Depression it intended to cover only a ``normal'' level of
losses.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The list of white-collar defendants on Wall
Street continues to grow, with the indictment of a prominent trader
and his firm for alleged stock manipulation in the sale of Fireman's
Fund Corp. shares by American Express Co. more than two years ago.
   The 22-count federal indictment was returned Thursday against
Salim B. Lewis and the brokerage he owns, S.B. Lewis & Co.
   Lewis' lawyer, Stanley Arkin, said his client was innocent and
would fight the charges.
</TEXT>
