<2ND_LINE>PM-Business Highlights, 1st Add,0512</2ND_LINE>
<DATELINE>ATLANTA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   West Point-Pepperell Inc. says it plans to ask a
federal court to block Farley Inc.'s $48-per-share takeover bid.
   In papers filed Thursday with the Securities and Exchange
Commission in Washington, Pepperell claimed Farley's financial
adviser, Drexel Burnham Lambert Inc., ``is violating the terms of a
standstill agreement entered into on March 3, 1988 which prohibits
Drexel from assisting anyone in acquiring, directly or indirectly,
Stevens or its business assets for a term of one year.''
   The allegation refers to Pepperell's acquisition this year along
with Odyssey Partners of J.P. Stevens & Co. Inc., a New York-based
textile company. Drexel advised Odyssey and guaranteed some
financing.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>SPRINGDALE, Ark. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Tyson Foods Inc. has defended its
$52-a-share buyout offer for Holly Farms Corp. as officers of Holly
Farms urged the company's stockholders to reject the roughly $940
million bid.
   The Holly Farms board said Thursday the offer is inadequate.
   But Jim Blair, a spokesman for Tyson, said Holly Farms probably
won't find a better offer.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The major airlines did their best job of
holding down flight delays and mishandled bags in September since
they started reporting flight information 13 months ago, the
Transportation Department says.
   The 13 largest domestic carriers reported that 85.6 percent of
their flights were on time in September, up from 83 percent in
August and the best showing since the department began requiring
large carriers to report the information in September l987, the
department said Thursday.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Reagan has signed legislation to give
consumers more and faster information about the costs of credit
cards.
   The bill signed Thursday will require banks, department stores
and other credit card issuers to supply details to their customers
about interest rates and other charges.
   Banking groups worked for passage of the measure because it would
prevent states from imposing differing disclosure requirements on
their interstate industry. Consumer groups also backed it strongly.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Agriculture Department has proposed new
rules to target the most troublesome meat and poultry processing
plants for close federal inspection while easing up on those that
have good records.
   The industry welcomed the prospective change announced Thursday
as one improving the focus of the inspection program. But consumer
and labor groups assailed it, saying it smacks of a failed policy at
the Labor Department's job safety agency and would help put ``the
fox in charge of the chicken coop.''
</TEXT>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   The stock market rose Thursday in an advance led by blue-chip
issues. The Dow Jones average of 30 industrials ended 13.51 points
higher at 2,170.34.
   Bond prices rose in sluggish trading.
   The dollar rose in U.S. foreign exchange trading.
   Copper futures prices skidded as traders took profits after five
straight days of gains. On other markets, precious metals declined,
livestock and meat futures fell sharply, grains and soybeans
retreated, and energy futures rose.
</TEXT>
