<1ST_LINE>r f PM-OilPrices     11-04 0180</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Oil Prices,0191</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Energy Futures Higher</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Buying prompted mainly by technical factors has
continued pushing energy futures prices higher, analysts say.
   On the New York Mercantile Exchange, the December contract for
unleaded gasoline rose 1.41 cents Thursday to settle at 45.20 cents
per gallon, after rising 0.17 cent on Wednesday. Other contract
months were higher.
   Among other refined petroleum products, wholesale home heating
oil, which rose 0.18 cent a gallon on Wednesday, closed up 0.97 cent
to 44.32 cents.
   The December contract for West Texas Intermediate, the benchmark
U.S. crude, closed at $13.90 a barrel, up 15 cents. The contract
rose 31 cents on Wednesday.
   John O'Connell, senior energy analyst for Refco Inc., attributed
Thursday's gains mainly to technical buying in the absence to any
market-moving news.
   ``I was a little bit surprised of the strength of the market,''
he said. ``I think people are just nervous in front of the (OPEC)
meeting.''
   The Organization of Petroleum Exporting Countries plans to meet
Nov. 17 to discuss cutting its production to boost sagging worldwide
oil prices.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
