<DOCNO> AP881104-0277 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-11-04-88 0119EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r f PM-StockFraud Bjt   11-04 0656</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Stock Fraud, Bjt,0676</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Trader And Firm Indicted; Defense Attorney Calls Charges `Garbage'</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RICK GLADSTONE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A prominent trader with ties to financial giant
American Express Co. is the latest target of a federal crackdown on
Wall Street crime, but his lawyer has denounced the charges and
accused prosecutors of abuse.
   The 22-count indictment announced Thursday against Salim B. Lewis
and the brokerage he owns, S.B. Lewis & Co., charged him with
manipulation and other frauds in connection with American Express's
sale of Fireman's Fund Corp. stock more than two years ago.
   The indictment, which carries enormous potential penalties, is an
indirect outgrowth of the Ivan Boesky insider trading scandal, and
Manhattan U.S. attorney Rudolph W. Giuliani said others might be
charged.
   Stanley Arkin, Lewis's attorney, said his client was innocent and
would fight the charges. Arkin harshly denounced Giuliani's office
for prosecuting the matter.
   ``The allegations are totally off the wall,'' Arkin said.
``Twenty-two counts of this piece of garbage reflect a kind of
mindless abusiveness of the people who brought this case. There's no
possible justification.''
   He added: ``There's a great difference between being a tough
prosecutor and being ruthless, and this over here is ruthlessness,
completely unjustified on any basis.''
   American Express was not named in the indictment, but was
portrayed as the intended beneficiary of the alleged manipulation
scheme. The company quickly denied any wrongdoing and said it has
been cooperating fully with federal investigators.
   Giuliani, whose office has been leading a crackdown on Wall
Street corruption that has resulted in numerous indictments, told
reporters Lewis allegedly conspired with others to manipulate upward
the stock price of Fireman's Fund, an insurance concern partly owned
by American Express.
   The prosecutor said the manipulation took place when American
Express was about to price an offering of Fireman's Fund stock it
wished to sell. One of the objectives, Giuliani said, was ``to make
sure that American Express maximized the proceeds that it received
from that offering.''
   He would not elaborate on whether anyone inside American Express
participated in the alleged scheme.
   Lewis, 49, has a close working relationship with American
Express, one of the nation's biggest financial services firms and
parent of Shearson Lehman Hutton Inc., a leading Wall Street
investment house.
   American Express retained Lewis to conduct major transactions in
the past, At the time of the alleged manipulation, it had a
substantial investment in S.B. Lewis and has about a 20 percent
stake in the firm now.
   The indictment alleged that Lewis requested two unidentified
employees of the Los Angeles-based brokerage firm Jefferies & Co.
buy more than 400,000 shares of Fireman's Fund on the New York and
Pacific stock exchanges on May 8, 1986, in attempt to drive its
price up to $38 a share, substantially above its price at the time.
   The indictment also accused Lewis of promising to reimburse the
Jefferies employees for any losses they might incur and of hiding
his role in the transactions through phony records.
   The day after the alleged manipulation, American Express said it
would sell 8 million shares of Fireman's Fund at $41.50 a share. It
eventually realized a gain of $88 million from that sale.
   Giuliani acknowledged that some information used to obtain the
indictment was provided by Boyd L. Jefferies, the founder of
Jefferies & Co., who settled civil securities-law violations with
the Securities and Exchange Commission last year and has been
cooperating with federal investigators.
   Jefferies originally was implicated by Boesky, the most famous
insider trader in U.S. history. Now imprisoned, Boesky also has been
cooperating with the government in other securities fraud
investigations.
   Lewis and his firm were charged with various counts of
conspiracy, stock manipulation, mail fraud, wire fraud, phony record
keeping and margin violations. For an individual, each count carries
a maximum penalty of five years imprisonment. For a company, the
penalties range from $500,000 to $2.25 million per count.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP881104-0278 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-11-04-88 0127EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r f BC-Macmillan-Chronology     11-04 0640</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Macmillan-Chronology,0665</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Battle for Macmillan Started Last May</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Macmillan Bjt</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Here is a list of important dates in the takeover
fight for the publishing and information services giant, Macmillan
Inc., which agreed Thursday to be acquired by British publisher
Robert Maxwell for about $2.5 billion.
   May 17 _ On the eve of its annual meeting, Macmillan Inc. says it
has received an unsolicited takeover proposal of $64-a-share from a
group led by the Texan Robert M. Bass, who already owns a 9 percent
stake in the company.
   May 18 _ Macmillan Chairman Edward P. Evans tells shareholders
that the company is not for sale, but takes no immediate position on
the Bass offer.
   May 31 _ Macmillan's board proposes a restructuring plan that
would split the company into two companies, publishing and
information services, and give shareholders a stake in each as well
as a cash dividend of $52.35 a share.
   June 4 _ The Bass Group boosts its offer to $73 a share or, as an
alternative, a restructuring that was the same as the company had
proposed except that the cash dividend would be $58 a share.
   June 8 _ Macmillan rejects the Bass Group's proposals to pay $73
a share for the company or participate in its restructuring plan.
   June 10 _ A Delaware Chancery Court judge, acting on a suit filed
by the Bass Group, temporarily blocks Macmillan from proceeding with
its restructuring plan.
   July 14 _ The Delaware Chancery Court judge issues an injunction
against the Macmillan restructuring plan, and the company says it
would appeal.
   July 17 _ The Bass Group sweetens its buyout offer to $75 a
share, and launchs a tender offer.
   July 21 _ Macmillan says it received an unsolicited proposal from
British publisher Robert Maxwell to acquire the company at $80 a
share.
   July 29 _ Macmillan's board rejects the Bass' $75 a share offer,
but authorizes management to explore other transactions.
   Aug. 12 _ Maxwell tells Macmillan he plans to launch a tender
offer at $80 a share, but offers to drop it if the company sells him
the information services company it planned to create for not less
than $1.1 billion.
   Aug. 26 _ Macmillan's board rejects Maxwell's offer as inadequate.
   Sept. 9 _ Maxwell says his company may increase its $80-a-share
bid, or pay $1.4 billion for specified information services
businesses alone.
   Sept. 12 _ Macmillan announces it agreed to a buyout by a group
including the investment banking firm Kohlberg Kravis Roberts & Co.
and Macmillan senior management for $85 a share in cash and
securities.
   Sept. 15 _ Maxwell boosts his offer to $86.80 a share in cash.
   Sept. 16 _ Kohlberg Kravis launches its tender offer. The Bass
Group drops its $75 a share offer.
   Sept. 27 _ After an auction, Macmillan agrees to a bid of $90.05
a share cash and securities by Kohlberg Kravis, snubbing a sweetened
$89 a share cash offer by Maxwell. It also gives Kohlberg Kravis the
right to buy four of its businesses for $865 million should their
merger agreement collapse.
   Sept. 29 _ Maxwell sweetens his bid to $90.25 a share in cash,
and says he would pay $900 million for the same four businesses.
   Oct. 5 _ Macmillan's board recommends that shareholders reject
Maxwell's latest bid because it contains conditions that would
include invalidating the lockup provision on selling four businesses
to Kohlberg Kravis.
   Oct. 17 _ The Delaware Chancery Court denies Maxwell's request
that it throw out the Macmillan's lockup agreement with Kohlberg.
   Nov. 2 _ The Delaware Supreme Court reverses the lower court and
effectively blocks the merger agreement between Macmillan and
Kohlberg, calling the bidding process ``tainted.''
   Nov. 3 _ The Macmillan board throws its support to the Maxwell
tender offer, and Kohlberg drops its tender offer.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
