<1ST_LINE>r f PM-Pepperell Bjt   11-04 0564</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Pepperell, Bjt,0584</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Pepperell Charges Farley, Drexel Violate Agreements, Regulations</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN A. BOLT</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ATLANTA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   West Point-Pepperell Inc. has taken the offensive
in its battle to thwart a takeover by Farley Inc., seeking a federal
court order blocking the $1.4 billion offer.
   Pepperell filed suit in federal court in Georgia seeking to stop
Farley's $48-per-share offer, on the grounds that the company is
financially unable to go through with its offer and that its
financial partner, the investment firm Drexel Burnham Lambert Inc.,
legally can not participate in the deal.
   In papers filed Thursday with the Securities and Exchange
Commission in Washington, Pepperell claimed Drexel was violating
terms of March 3 standstill agreement with Pepperell.
   The agreement prohibits Drexel from ``assisting anyone in
acquiring, directly or indirectly, (J.P.) Stevens (& Co. Inc.) or
its business assets for a term of one year,'' the filing stated.
   Earlier this year, Drexel advised the investor group Odyssey
Partners during its efforts to buy Stevens. Pepperell and Odyssey
eventually jointly acquired the company, with Pepperell retaining
Stevens' bed and bath textile operations.
   ``We were never a party to any standstill agreement, and in our
opinion, the suit is totally lacking in merit,'' said Drexel
spokesman Steven Anreder in New York.
   Jack Albertine, a Farley spokesman in Chicago, said the company
would have no comment until it had studied the allegations.
   The SEC filing also alleged that Farley's offer violates Federal
Reserve Bank regulations because of the amount of debt involved and
says Drexel has failed to identify itself as a ``bidder'' under
security regulations and has not filed necessary documents.
   Also Thursday, West Point said it had delayed until Nov. 15
enacting its ``poison pill'' provisions which grant shareholders
special rights in the event of a takeover bid. Separate trading in
the rights had been scheduled to begin Thursday.
   Thursday's filing with the SEC repeated Pepperell's contention
that Farley's offer ``does not reflect the long-term value
achievable by the company as an independent entity.''
   Pepperell's board on Wednesday said Farley was trying to purchase
the company before its stock price reflected the full value of the
Stevens acquisition.
   The Stevens assets must be held separately until early December
under an agreement with the Federal Trade Commission, company
officials have said.
   Pepperell stock fell $1.37{ to $43.87{ a share Thursday in
composite New York Stock Exchange trading, following a 25-cent a
share drop on Wednesday.
   Also Wednesday, the Pepperell board authorized management to
explore other alternatives for the company, a possible sale of the
company or some of its businesses to a third party.
   ``The company is not currently engaged in negotiations with any
third parties with respect to any such transaction, although it may
commence such negotiations at any time,'' the company's SEC filing
said.
   The company said it would have no statement on any such
negotiation until or if they were completed.
   Pepperell manufactures Arrow shirts and Martex towels, and as a
result of the Stevens acquisition has about 25 percent of the
nation's home fashion textile market.
   Subsidiaries of Farley, a privately owned conglomerate headed by
William Farley, manufacture Fruit of the Loom underwear and Acme
boots.
   Farley notified Pepperell in May it was seeking up to 25 percent
of Pepperell's 29.4 million outstanding shares and, as of last week,
had spent $88 million for 9.8 percent of the stock.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
