<1ST_LINE>r f PM-Drought-SeedPrices     11-04 0556</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Drought-Seed Prices,0571</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Pioneer Seed Corn Prices Rise An Average 11.8 Percent, Drought
Blamed</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By STEVEN P. ROSENFELD</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>DES MOINES, Iowa (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The impact of last summer's drought has
come home again for corn farmers, with the world's largest seed corn
producer announcing a double-digit price hike for 1989 sales to
farmers.
   Pioneer Hi-Bred International Inc. said Thursday the average
increase of 11.8 percent, which it said was mandated by higher
production costs, would come to about $7.39 a bag, something that
would bring the cost of an average bag of corn to about $70.
   But because the company sells a wide variety of seed, some
farmers still will pay less than $70 and some will pay more.
   An executive said the price announcement Thursday should relieve
farmer fears of an even steeper hike in seed costs for next spring's
planting.
   ``This should be good news to those who've heard rumors that
Pioneer seed corn would be selling for well over $100 a bag,''
Charles S. Johnson, senior vice president for the company's North
American operations, said in a prepared statement.
   Based on the average increase announced, a farmer would spend
about $220 more next spring than last for each 100 acres planted if
he used a Pioneer variety that is designed to seed 3.4 acres per bag.
   Pioneer seed corn is sold in packages ranging from 60,000 kernels
a bag to 110,000 kernels, and the company said most increases will
range from $5 to $10 a bag.
   ``The reason for the increase is very heavily related to the
drought,'' Pioneer spokesman Dave Knau said in an interview.
   The blistering summer of 1988 shriveled Pioneer's harvest of corn
grown for farm seed to little more than half of what it had planned
to grow, Knau said. As a result, the company had to plan expensive
winter production _ half of it spread through the states of Arizona,
California, Florida and Texas and half in the South American
countries of Argentina and Chile.
   But he said Pioneer believes the increase will be curbed somewhat
because the outlook for the winter harvest is good and because it
was able to carry over unsold seed corn from previous harvests
equivalent to 57 percent of last spring's sales.
   Johnson said the company is projecting that nearly one-fourth of
its supply for next spring will be in five new hybrids that
``demonstrated a strong performance advantage over the competition
this past growing season, even with the drought.'' Those hybrids are
designated 3751, 3585, 3379, 3343 and 3140.
   Meantime, Pioneer and others are forecasting stepped up sales for
1989 plantings because the government, in response to drought damage
suffered by farmers, will not require corn growers to leave as much
land idle as they did this year to qualify for federal subsidies.
   Knau said the prices for 1989 seed were announced a few weeks
later than usual because company officials had to factor in winter
production. He also said the company may slightly reduce 1989
spending on advertising or on premium giveaways to promote sales,
such as caps and jackets.
   But he said the company will continue offering discounts of 1
percent to 14 percent based on the dollar volume of sales and
discounts ranging from 2 percent to 7 percent for orders paid for in
advance.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP881104-0281 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-11-04-88 0134EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r f PM-AutoSales Bjt   11-04 0659</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Auto Sales, Bjt,0677</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>October Auto Sales Up From Weak, Year-Earlier Month</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By FREDERICK STANDISH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>DETROIT (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Automakers sold 8 percent more cars and light
trucks in the United States last month than in October 1987, partly
because of the stock market crash and partly because of lighter than
normal sales in the year-earlier month.
   U.S. and foreign automakers on Thursday reported selling
1,215,402 vehicles during October of this year, compared with
1,169,067 a year earlier. The percentage change is based on daily
sales rates, because there were 26 sales days in October this year
and 27 during the month last year.
   Weak sales of foreign-made cars and light trucks were more than
offset in October by strong sales of U.S.-made cars and especially
tucks.
   Auto sales, like the rest of the economy, slowed immediately
after the Oct. 19, 1987, stock market crash as consumers held off on
big-ticket purchases. But over time, the crash proved to have little
if any effect on car sales. The 1988 model year ended Sept. 30 was
the third-best on record.
   Also coloring sales comparisons were consumers' reactions to
dealer incentives.
   During August and September 1987, automakers offered big cash
rebates or low financing to lure buyers into showrooms. But those
incentives ended Sept. 30, 1987, and some consumers who planned to
buy cars in October accelerated their plans to take advantage of the
deals.
   The effects of the crash and lackluster buying last year were
most noticeable in comparing sales during the Oct. 21-31 period with
the entire month for both years.
   In late October, General Motors Corp., Ford Motor Co. and
Chrysler Corp. reported car sales rose 6.1 percent, on a daily
basis, with a total of 187,249 sold during the period this year and
196,015 during the same time last year.
   But for the month, which takes into account sales before the
crash, sales for the Big Three jumped 17.5 percent, to 542,373 cars
last month from 479,176 in October last year.
   ``Consumers essentially sat out the latter part of October and
early November (last year) in everything, not just autos,'' said
auto analyst Jeannette Garretty of the Bank of America in San
Francisco.
   Tom Webb, a senior economist with the National Automobile Dealers
Association outside Washington, said the sales swings resulted less
from the crash than from depressed purchasing during October of last
year, compared with the same month this year.
   ``Last year's real depressed sales during the 10-day period was
more of a payback,'' he said, from accelerated buying in August and
September of 1987. But he acknowledged that the crash damaged
consumer confidence for a short time.
   During late October, U.S. automakes sold 7.9 percent more cars
and light trucks compared with the same period last year.
   Domestic manufacturers sold 334,237 cars and light trucks,
compared with 344,190 during the same time last year. The comparison
is based on a daily selling rate, and there were nine selling days
in this year's period and 10 last year.
   Ford reported that during late October, it sold 61,883 cars, up
15.6 percent from the 59,502 cars it sold during the sae period in
1987. The nation's No. 2 automaker said its monthly sales rose 29.3
percent to 179,903 cars last month from 144,499 during October last
year.
   Chrysler's sales went to 30,538 cars during late October this
year, compared with 32,736 last year, a 3.7 percent gain based on
the number of cars sold per sales day. And for the month, Chrysler
said it sold 84,373 cars this year, 13.3 percent more than the
77,359 it sold in October 1987.
   GM said it sold 94,828 cars in late October this year, up, on a
daily sales basis, 1.5 percent from the 103,777 cars the nation's
No. 1 automaker sold during the same period last year. In October,
GM has sold 278,097 cars, 12.2 percent more than the 257,318 cars it
sold during October 1987.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
