<1ST_LINE>u f PM-Dollar-Gold     11-04 0320</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Dollar-Gold,0334</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Dollar Rises, Gold Lower</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The U.S. dollar rose against most major currencies
this morning in moderate European trading as the market cautiously
eyed the upcoming U.S. presidential election.
   Gold prices drifted lower as a rally in platinum, caused by tight
supplies, lost momentum and as the dollar remained steady.
   Foreign exchange dealers predicted the dollar would rise ahead of
the U.S. balloting next Tuesday, although it would trade in a narrow
range.
   ``The market is very cautious right now,'' said a dealer at a
major West German bank in Frankfurt. ``People are liquidating
exposure on the downside, fearing the market might turn around and
head higher before Tuesday is over.''
   But dealers said market players agreed the dollar is bound to
decline after the elections.
   In London, the dollar strengthened against the British pound. It
cost $1.7783 to buy one pound, cheaper for buyers than $1.7805 late
Thursday.
   Other mid-morning dollar rates in Europe compared with late
Thursday's prices, included: 1.7820 West German marks, up from
1.7760; 1.4920 Swiss francs, up from 1.4863; 6.0830 French francs,
up from 6.0565; 2.0098 Dutch guilders, up from 1.9990; 1,325.00
Italian lire, up from 1,317.50; and 1.2220 Canadian dollars, down
from 1.2234.
   In Tokyo, the dollar closed at 124.63 yen, down 0.05 yen from
Wednesday's close. Japanese markets were closed Thursday for a
national holiday. In London, the dollar was trading Friday at 124.45
yen.
   Gold opened in London at a bid price of $422.25 a troy ounce,
unchanged from the late bid price Thursday. At mid-morning, London's
five major bullion dealers fixed a recommended price of $419.50.
   In Zurich, the metal fell to $419.60 bid from $421.85 bid late
Thursday.
   Earlier in Hong Kong, gold closed at a bid $421.86, down from
$422.99 bid at Thursday's close.
   Silver bullion fell in London to a late bid of $6.40 a troy
ounce, down from $6.51 bid late Thursday.
</TEXT>
