<1ST_LINE>u f PM-Japan-Markets     11-04 0190</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Japan-Markets,0200</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Dollar Edges Down Against Yen, Stocks Off</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The U.S. dollar edged down today against the
Japanese yen, while prices fell moderately on the Tokyo Stock
Exchange.
   The dollar closed the week at 124.63 yen, down 0.05 yen from
Wednesday's closing. After opening at 124.72 yen, the U.S. currency
moved between 124.60 and 124.85 yen during the day.
   The Nikkei Stock Average of 225 selected issues, which declined
28.41 points Wednesday, shed another 32.01 points, or 0.11 percent,
to finish at 27,953.25.
   Traders said the Bank of Japan stepped into the market this
morning, buying 30 million to 50 million dollars when the U.S.
currency was trading at about 124.80-124.85 yen.
   But today's central bank action, the fourth such intervention
this week, was ineffective in triggering a dollar rally, with the
U.S. currency continuing to trade around pre-intervention levels.
   The Bank of Japan does not publicly comment on its market
interventions.
   Traders said market participants were awaiting the release of
U.S. employment figures for October, due later Friday.
   Stock and foreign exchange markets in Tokyo were closed Thursday
for Culture Day, a Japanese national holiday.
</TEXT>
