<HEAD>San Diego, Tucson Utilities Call Off Merger Proposal</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SAN DIEGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A proposed $1.9 billion merger between San Diego
Gas & Electric Co. and Tucson Electric Power Co. was called off ``in
the best interests of the respective companies,'' the utilities
announced jointly.
   Officials from both firms said Thursday the deal was terminated
because they could not agree on an approach to defeat efforts by
Southern California Edison Corp. to block the merger.
   SCE, a holding company for the Southern California Edison Co.
utility, made a $2.2 billion hostile bid for SDG&E last month. The
offer was contingent on the San Diego utility not acquiring the
Arizona utility.
   ``These issues led the boards of directors of TEP and SDG&E to
conclude that it was in the best interests of the respective
companies and their stockholders, employees and customers to
terminate the merger agreement,'' SDG&E spokesman Fred Vaughn said.
   Under the terminated agreement, SDG&E and TEP would have
exchanged stock, leaving SDG&E the surviving company.
</TEXT>
