<FILEID>AP-NR-11-04-88 1100EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>a f BC-TickerTalk Adv07   11-04 0463</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Ticker Talk, Adv 07,0480</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>$adv 07</NOTE>
<NOTE>For Release Monday Nov. 7</NOTE>
<HEAD>Market Not Expected to Fete Bush Victory</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARCY GORDON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Wall Street already has cast its vote: for George
Bush.
   But the anticipated victory of its favored candidate doesn't seem
likely to set off any raucous celebrations in the stock market. In
fact, many analysts say, a Bush win in Tuesday's presidential
election could bring a mild downturn on Wednesday.
   The market has been anticipating a Bush victory for quite some
time now, and has calculated that event into its thinking. That sets
up a classic case of ``buy the rumor, then sell the fact'' after the
election if the vice president wins.
   ``What's factored into the market is that Bush will win,'' said
Monte Gordon, vice president and director of research at Dreyfus
Corp.
   Investors who bought stocks earlier on the assumption of a
Republican victory will sell and take their profits on post-election
Wednesday, under this scenario.
   In addition, the market could be hit by the realization that Bush
``isn't going to create a miracle in 24 hours and the economy's
still got problems,'' suggested Bill Raftery, a stock analyst for
Smith Barney, Harris Upham & Co.
   The sell-off isn't expected to be massive, and some market
watchers even anticipate a rally.
   In the event that Michael Dukakis wins, on the other hand, the
market could be shaken more severely.
   Wall Street sees Dukakis, among other things, as a big-spending
liberal Democrat and someone who would be prone to raise taxes _ one
of the market's biggest bugaboos.
   ``The investment community views Bush as an extension of Reagan,
and Reagan was considered healthy for the market,'' said Philip
Puccio, a senior vice president at Dillon, Read & Co.
   A Dukakis White House, by contrast, would be expected to pursue
economic policies similar to those of the Carter administration,
Puccio added. Wall Street was no fan of Jimmy Carter.
   While it sees Bush as a safe bet, the market doesn't believe he
has the election completely sewn up. That's why trading stalled last
week and volume on the New York Stock Exchange slowed to a trickle
amid uncertainty ahead of the election.
   You don't have to scratch hard to find pre-election jitters under
the market's surface.
   On Oct. 19, the one-year anniversary of last year's stock
collapse, the market was knocked off a post-crash high by a rumor
that the Washington Post was about to publish a story potentially
damaging to Bush's campaign. The Post denied it. But traders who had
made profits in the market's earlier rise were primed to sell, and
they did.
   The market dislikes uncertainty _ almost as much as it hates
taxes.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv Monday Nov. 7</NOTE>
</DOC>
