<HEAD>Soybeans Surge On Large Export Sale, Then Turn Mixed</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Soybean futures prices surged at today's opening
on the Chicago Board of Trade on news of a large, unexpected export
sale of soybeans and soybean meal, but later turned mixed.
   Grain futures also opened higher but then turned mostly lower in
early trading.
   The markets were surprised by the Agriculture Department's
announcement late Thursday that the Soviet Union had purchased
535,000 metric tons of U.S. soybeans and that another 540,000 metric
tons of soybeans and soymeal had been sold to undisclosed
destinations, analysts said.
   Rumors of such large export sales usually reach the futures
markets before the sales are officially confirmed.
   ``We didn't see a whole lot of commercial trade yesterday and in
light of that, it was somewhat surprising to see this type of deal
made,'' said Walter Spilka, grain market analyst with Smith Barney,
Harris Upham & Co. in New York.
   Trading activity was much lighter in the grain markets, where
there was little news to sway prices, he said.
   In early trading, wheat was 2\ cents lower to 1 cent higher with
the contract for delivery in December at $4.14} a bushel; corn was
1\ cents to 2} cents lower with December at $2.79} a bushel; oats
were 1\ cents to 2 cents lower with December at $2.20 a bushel;
soybeans were 1} cents lower to 2 cents higher with November at
$7.94 a bushel.
   Livestock and meat futures were mostly higher in early trading on
the Chicago Mercantile Exchange.
   Live cattle were unchanged to .10 cent higher with December at
72.85 cents a pound; feeder cattle were .05 cent lower to .15 cent
higher with November at 81.35 cents a pound; live hogs were .05 cent
lower to .28 cent higher with December at 41.17 cents a pound;
frozen pork bellies were .10 cent lower to .18 cent higher with
February at 45.65 cents a pound.
   Livestock and meat futures settled sharply lower on Thursday.
</TEXT>
