<DOCNO> AP881104-0296 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-11-04-88 1317EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r f BC-Earns-TexasAir     11-04 0466</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Earns-Texas Air,0483</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Texas Air Posts $114.1 Million Loss in Third Quarter</HEAD>
<DATELINE>HOUSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Texas Air Corp. reported Friday a net loss of
$114.1 million during a third quarter that traditionally is strong.
   The nation's largest airline company said its loss in the three
months ended Sept. 30 widened from the $72.8 million it lost in the
third quarter of 1987.
   Third-quarter revenue declined to $2.13 billion from $2.20
billion a year earlier.
   Texas Air is the parent of Continental Airlines and financially
troubled Eastern Airlines. It recently agreed to sell Eastern's
profitable shuttle service to developer Donald Trump for $365
million in cash.
   Houston-based Continental posted a third-quarter profit of $15.2
million, compared with a net loss of $10.2 million a year earlier.
Its revenue for the quarter rose to $1.2 billion from $1.1 billion.
   ``Continental's modest profit signals that financial progress
continues to be made at the company. However, in view of the fact
that the quarter is traditionally one of the company's strongest,
the results are clearly unsatisfactory,'' Texas Air said in a
statement.
   Miami-based Eastern had a net loss of $112.9 million before a
$12.3 million charge for dividends payable to holders of its
preferred shares. That was widened from a loss of $67.4 million,
before a $14 million charge for preferred dividends, a year earlier.
   Eastern's third-quarter revenue declined to $912.7 million from
$1.1 billion.
   ``Eastern's results reflect its labor situation as well as severe
competitive pressures on the revenue side,'' Texas Air said.
``However, Eastern also is showing marked operational improvement,
as indicated by Department of Transportation statistics, which is a
tribute to the outstanding performance of Eastern's employees during
this difficult period.''
   Eastern has been locked in a prolonged bitter battle with its
unions.
   In the first nine months of the year, Texas Air had a net loss of
$494.3 million, widened from a loss of $200.5 million in the same
period of 1987.
   Texas Air's nine-month revenue was unchanged at $6.4 billion.
   Continental's results for the first nine months amounted to a net
loss of $216.3 million, including an adjustment of $131 million in
the second quarter related to its air traffic liability account.
That compares with the first nine months of 1987, when Continental
had a net loss of $179.2 million.
   Nine-month revenue for Continental jumped to $3.4 billion from
$2.9 billion.
   For the same period, Eastern lost $233.7 million, widened from a
loss of $38.2 million a year earlier. Its nine-month revenue fell to
$3.0 billion from $3.4 billion.
   Eastern also announced that it will not renew its contingency
pilot and flight attendant replacement training program with
Continental. Eastern officials said there are no plans to resume the
program, which expires this month, in light of expectations that a
work stoppage is considered unlikely.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
