<FILEID>AP-NR-11-04-88 1655EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r f AM-Chubb-DroughtInsurance     11-04 0506</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Chubb-Drought Insurance,0523</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Company Improves Drought Insurance Offer</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CINCINNATI (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Chubb Corp., facing a class-action lawsuit by
farmers in 10 states who say they were unfairly denied drought
insurance, has offered another $43.7 million in coverage to some
farmers whose applications it had rejected this year.
   The company said Friday it is willing to proceed to reach a
settlement with farmers who applied for drought insurance, but were
rejected and filed suit against Chubb.
   The company made the offer Thursday in U.S. District Court in
Cincinnati where the lawsuit against Chubb is filed.
   The offer is subject to approval of Judge Carl B. Rubin, who is
presiding over the class-action lawsuit. It potentially represents
about 8,000 farmers in Ohio, Kentucky, Indiana, Tennessee, Illinois,
Minnesota, Michigan, Missouri, Iowa and Wisconsin.
   Chubb said it would be willing to reach an agreement similar to
one proposed in Minnesota, in which eligible applicants would
receive amounts equal to losses that would have been paid if an
applicant had been a policyholder, reduced by applicable premium
amounts and any goodwill payments already made.
   If such a settlement is accepted, Chubb said it would result in
an after-tax charge against earnings of $13 million, or 30 cents per
share, in the fourth quarter of 1988.
   Stanley M. Chesley, lead lawyer for the farmers, complained to
Rubin that Chubb was trying to outmaneuver Chesley by making
separate offers to farmers in Indiana and Minnesota.
   ``Then the judge challenged them to make it available to all the
states,'' said lawyer Janet Abaray, an aide to Chesley.
   After a recess, Chubb attorneys came back with the $43.7 million
proposal. Ms. Abaray said the farmers' lawyers will use the figure
as a starting point for new negotiations.
   She said farmers whose rain insurance claims were honored would
get nothing more. Also ineligible would be farmers whose premiums
were rejected, but whose land got too much rain to qualify if they
had had policies.
   Ms. Abaray said payments would go to farmers whose applications
were rejected, but who would have received payments as drought
victims. The payments would be made in those cases only where the
amounts exceed the premiums and the ``good-will'' payments already
made by Chubb to rejected applicants.
   Whatever settlement is reached will be shared by all of the
members of the class, she said.
   Chubb, based in Warren, N.J., began rejecting payments in
mid-year when it said brokers sold more coverage than planned. Chubb
lawyers said the company was prepared to sell about $40 million
coverage and brokers sold more than $300 million.
   Chubb spokeswoman Gail Devlin said Friday the company has made
$11 million in goodwill payments and plans no further such payments.
   Chubb said in an Oct. 17 statement that its Federal Insurance Co.
subsidiary issued 1,176 policies in seven Midwestern states in the
1988 drought insurance program, extending a total of $43 million in
policy coverage. Chubb said Federal Insurance suffered $20 million
in losses on those policies and has paid virtually all of them to
the policyholders.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP881104-0301 </DOCNO>
