<2ND_LINE>BC-Board of Trade, Close,0245</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Crop Futures Close Mostly Lower</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Grain and soybean futures prices closed mostly
lower Friday in a quiet finish to a volatile session on the Chicago
Board of Trade.
   The markets had opened higher on strength from the soybeans,
which took off like a shot in response to the Agriculture
Department's surprise announcement late Thursday that the Soviet
Union had purchased 535,000 metric tons of U.S. soybeans and that
another 540,000 metric tons of soybeans and soymeal had been sold to
undisclosed destinations.
   But soybean prices fell rapidly as the market absorbed the news.
Grain futures also dropped.
   Soybeans finished mixed on strength stemming from ideas that
additional soybean sales to the Soviets would be forthcoming,
analysts said.
   ``There does seem to be a feeling that some more business will be
transacted,'' said Joel Karlin, a research analyst with Research
Department Inc. in Chicago.
   But traders saw little chance for large export sales of corn or
wheat in the near future, he said.
   At the close, wheat was \ cent to 2 cents lower with the contract
for delivery in December at $4.15{ a bushel; corn was 1{ cents to 4
cents lower with December at $2.78{ a bushel; oats were unchanged to
5 cents lower with December at $2.17 a bushel; soybeans were 2\
cents lower to 2{ cents higher with November at $7.92 a bushel.
</TEXT>
