<FILEID>AP-NR-11-04-88 2043EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r f AM-GoldFields     11-04 0412</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Gold Fields,0428</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>US Will Not Probe Gold Fields Takeover</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CARL HARTMAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Britain's investigation of Minorco SA's $4.7
billion takeover bid for Consolidated Gold Fields PLC makes it
unnecessary for the United States to look into whether a merger of
the two companies would endanger the supply of strategic minerals,
U.S. officials said Friday.
   Under British, law Minorco's bid for Consolidated Gold Fields, a
British company, lapsed on Oct. 25 when it was referred to the
British Monopolies and Mergers Commission.
   ``That won't prevent a U.S. investigation if there is a new
bid,'' Treasury spokesman Robert Levine said.
   The British government decided to investigate the offer after a
federal judge in New York issued an injunction against the deal
because it might violate U.S. antitrust law.
   Sen. Robert Dole, R-Kan., the Republican minority leader, wrote
Treasury Secretary Nicholas F. Brady on Oct. 25 urging an
investigation on the ground that U.S. national security was at risk.
   ``I view with concern the possibility of control by the South
African conglomerate of U.S. gold reserves, coal and other
significant business interests,'' Dole wrote.
   He added that the proposed merger would give South African
interests a substantial percentage of the world supply of platinum
and of feedstocks for titanium, used in alloys for jet engines, and
for zirconium, used in the cores of nuclear reactors.
   ``Continued access to these minerals is of vital strategic
significance to the national security interests of the United
States,'' he said.
   Similar letters were written by at least 20 other members of
Congress.
   On Oct. 5 Consolidated Gold Fields and Newmont Mining Corp. asked
President Reagan for the investigation under the new Trade Act,
which allows him to forbid a merger that threatens national security.
   Consolidated Gold Fields owns 49.3 percent of Newmont, this
country's largest gold producer. It also produces the titanium and
zirconium feedstocks.
   Minorco, based in Luxembourg, is controlled by the big South
African gold and diamond mining firms, Anglo American Corp. and De
Beers Consolidated Mines Ltd. Minorco already owns 29.6 percent of
Consolidated Gold Fields.
   The law gives the president 30 days from the filing of the
request to decide on an investigation. Those 30 days were up on
Friday.
   Levine said Consolidated Gold Fields was informed of the decision
not to investigate by a letter from Stephen J. Canner, director of
the Treasury's office of international investment.
   The Treasury refused to release copies of the letters.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP881104-0307 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-11-04-88 1717EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u f AM-Dollar-Gold     11-04 0524</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Dollar-Gold,0539</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Dollar Rises, Gold Mixed</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The dollar finished higher Friday following a
better-than-expected improvement in the nation's unemployment rate
during October.
   Gold prices were little changed after falling overseas. Republic
National Bank of New York said gold bullion was bid at $421.50 a
troy ounce as of 4 p.m. EST, slightly higher than $420.85 an ounce
late Thursday.
   The dollar rose overseas following release of the Labor
Department employment data, which indicated the economy is not
slowing. The currency continued to gain ground when trading shifted
to the United States.
   The government said the unemployment rate fell to 5.3 percent in
October, from 5.4 percent in the previous month. Traders said the
news might lead the Federal Reserve to tighten monetary policy, a
move that would push up interest rates and make dollar-denominated
investments more attractive.
   Jesse Torres, chief dealer at the Bank of Boston's New York
office, noted that institutional investors had a large appetite for
the dollar. ``The employment report renewed hope in the U.S.
economy,'' he said.
   The belief that Vice President George Bush will win the
presidential election Tuesday and continue current economic policies
also boosted traders' optimism, Torres said.
   But Yani Budiman, vice president of Chemical New York Capital
Markets Group, speculated there is still some concern heading into
the election. He questioned whether market participants would ``have
the nerve to keep their positions'' as polling approaches.
   In Tokyo, the dollar closed at 124.63 yen, down 0.05 yen from
Wednesday's close. Japanese markets were closed Thursday for a
national holiday. In London, the dollar traded Friday at 125.35 yen,
and in New York, the dollar rose to 124.93 yen from 124.68 yen on
Thursday.
   In London, the dollar gained strongly against the British pound.
It cost $1.7655 to buy one pound, cheaper than $1.7805 late
Thursday. In New York it cost $1.7661 to buy one pound, less
expensive than Thursday's $1.7775.
   Other late dollar rates in New York, compared with late
Thursday's prices, included: 1.7910 West German marks, up from
1.7778; 1.5013 Swiss francs, up from 1.4906; 6.1188 French francs,
up from 6.0726; 1,330.50 Italian lire, up from 1,322.25, and 1.2230
Canadian dollars, up from 1.2212.
   Other late dollar rates in Europe, compared with late Thursday,
included: 1.7955 West German marks, up from 1.7760; 1.5060 Swiss
francs, up from 1.4863; 6.1215 French francs, up from 6.0565; 2.0253
Dutch guilders, up from 1.9990; 1,332.50 Italian lire, up from
1,317.50, and 1.2223 Canadian dollars, down from 1.2234.
   Gold prices were mixed. On the New York Commodity Exchange, gold
bullion was unchanged at $421.50 a troy ounce.
   Earlier, gold fell in London to a late bid price of $420.25 a
troy ounce, compared with late Thursday's $422.25. In Zurich, gold
closed at a bid $420.50, down from $421.85 bid late Thursday.
Earlier in Hong Kong, gold closed at a bid $421.86, down from
$422.99 bid at Thursday's close.
   Silver finished at $6.425 a troy ounce on New York's Comex, up
from Thursday's $6.410. In London, the metal was trading at a late
bid price of $6.40 a troy ounce, compared with from $6.51 bid late
Thursday.
</TEXT>
