<1ST_LINE>u f AM-CommodityRdp     11-04 0789</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Commodity Rdp,0816</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Cocoa Prices Soar On Tight-Supply Fears</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVID DISHNEAU</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Cocoa futures prices roared to three-month highs Friday on New
York's Coffee, Sugar & Cocoa Exchange on panic buying amid
speculation that the world's leading producers were planning to
withhold supplies from the market.
   On other exchanges, livestock and meat posted strong gains;
precious metals were mixed; energy futures were mixed; grains and
soybeans were mostly lower and stock-index futures retreated.
   Cocoa for delivery in December, which had hit a 13-year-low near
$1,100 per metric ton in late September, soared above $1,400 Friday
and settled at $1,403, $94 above Thursday's final price. It was the
highest close since Aug. 12.
   ``It seems that everybody was buying _ the trade, the
speculators, the locals _ everybody was buying and nobody was
selling,'' said Arthur Stevenson, a cocoa market analyst with
Prudential-Bache Securities Inc. in New York.
   Analysts said two factors sparked the rally and both of them were
related to the Ivory Coast, the world's largest producer and source
of the most highly prized cocoa beans.
   For much of this year, the Ivory Coast has withheld its cocoa
from the world market, hoping to force prices higher. But with the
new crop now being harvested, the West African nation was running
out of storage space and had to find more room or sell some cocoa.
   On Friday, a rumor surfaced that the Ivory Coast and at least one
French trading firm had reached an agreement that would allow the
Ivory Coast to withhold another 400,000 metric tons of cocoa from
the market, Stevenson said.
   Meanwhile, the Ivory Coast's official newspaper reported Friday
the 11 other nations in the Cocoa Producers Alliance, a group that
accounts for more than four-fifths of the world's cocoa output, were
considering adopting withholding policies similar to the Ivory
Coast's. The alliance is scheduled to meet next week.
   ``Naturally, all of this coming out on one day induced a panic
reaction,'' Stevenson said.
   Live cattle and live hog futures finished strongly higher on the
Chicago Mercantile Exchange, partially reversing Thursday's sharp
losses and continuing the volatile trading pattern of the past week.
   Both the cattle and pork markets are struggling between
conflicting perceptions of their future direction, said Thomas
Morgan, president of Sterling Research Corp. in Arlington Heights,
Ill.
   In the cattle market, heavy slaughter weights and slack demand on
the cash markets signal that prices will weaken. But cattle supplies
typically decline and prices normally rise during the three weeks
before Thanksgiving, and bullish traders expect the market to follow
that pattern, Morgan said.
   The pork markets normally hit a seasonal low at this time of
year, he said. Bullish traders keep trying to pick the bottom while
the bears see near-record supplies of pork bellies in cold storage
and believe pork prices must move lower.
   The choppiness of both markets ``signifies the level of
uncertainty right now and the fact that there are two sides to the
story,'' Morgan said.
   Live cattle settled .10 cent to 1 cent higher with December at
73.75 cents a pound; feeder cattle were .10 cent to .50 cent higher
with November at 81.50 cents a pound; hogs were .25 cent lower to
.75 cent higher with December at 41.75 cents a pound; frozen pork
bellies were .02 cent to .65 cent higher with February at 46.30
cents a pound.
   Precious metals futures were mixed in uneventful trading.
   On New York's Commodity Exchange, gold settled 20 cents lower to
20 cents higher with December at $423.50 a troy ounce; silver was
1.5 cents to 2.7 cents higher with December at $6.465 a troy ounce.
   Energy futures finished mixed on the New York Mercantile Exchange
in trading dominated by technical factors in the absence of fresh
news.
   West Texas Intermediate crude oil settled 9 cents lower to 14
cents higher with December at $14.04 a barrel; heating oil was .24
cent lower to .05 cent higher with December at 44.08 cents a gallon;
unleaded gasoline was .48 cent to 1.14 cents higher with December at
46.34 cents a gallon.
   Grain and soybean futures prices ended mostly lower in a quiet
finish to a volatile session on the Chicago Board of Trade.
   Wheat settled \ cent to 2 cents lower with December at $4.15} a
bushel; corn was 1{ cents to 4{ cents lower with December at $2.78 a
bushel; oats were \ cent to 5 cents lower with December at $2.17 a
bushel; soybeans were 2\ cents lower to 2\ cents higher with
November at $7.92 a bushel.
   Stock-index futures fell sharply on the Chicago Mercantile
Exchange with the contract for December delivery of the Standard &
Poor's 500 off 3.35 points at 276.25.
</TEXT>
