<HEAD>Sun to Sell Some Atlantic Operations in Merger</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Sun Oil Co. has agreed to divest petroleum
stocks and sales operations in two counties of New York and
Pennsylvania as part of its takeover of Atlantic Petroleum, the
Federal Trade Commission announced Friday.
   The company signed a consent agreement promising to dispose of
operations in the Williamsport, Pa., and Binghamton, N.Y. areas to
settle charges the merger would reduce competition in the sale of
gasoline and other light petroleum products.
   Sun, based in Radnor, Pa., has proposed buying the stock of
Atlantic Petroleum from Maatschappij BV, a Netherlands company. Sun
will pay $513 million for the stock and an additional $113 million
for the Atlantic Petroleum inventories. Atlantic is based in King of
Prussia, Pa.
   Under terms of the agreement, Sun has six months to dispose of
facilities in the two areas, including 15 Arco service stations in
Broome County, N.Y. and Lycoming County, Pa.
