<1ST_LINE>u f AM-Bonds     11-04 0623</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Bonds,0653</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Bond Prices Decline</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Bond prices tumbled and interest rates soared
Friday after the government reported the October unemployment rate
fell to the lowest level in more than four years.
   The Treasury's bellwether 30-year bond fell nearly 2 points, or
about $18.75 per $1,000 face amount.
   Its yield, which moves inversely to its price and often is a key
indicator of the direction of interest rates, jumped to 8.90 percent
from 8.74 percent late Thursday. Shorter-term rates also moved
higher.
   Analysts said the lower-than-expected jobless rate and healthy
growth of new jobs last month fueled investor concern the economy is
not slowing down as anticipated.
   ``It's a straight forward story. The market has been rallying
precisely because the labor market for August and September were
weaker than the economics profession suggested,'' said Maury Harris,
an economist with PaineWebber Inc.
   ``Then suddenly the economic data are revised up and now we're
talking about the economy not being as weak as everbody said it
was,'' he said.
   Analysts said prices started out lower as caution gripped the
market in advance of the labor report. Then, almost immediately
after the Labor Department's 8:30 a.m. announcement that October's
jobless rate fell 0.1 percentage point to 5.3 percent _ the lowest
level since May 1984 _ a selloff began.
   ``It was a knee-jerk reaction to these employment numbers,'' said
Marshall B. Front, an economist at the Chicago investment and
mutual-fund management firm of Stein Roe & Farnham. ``They were a
surprise to most people who felt that they would be a continuation
of a trend toward a less robust business.''
   F. Ward McCarthy, chief financial economist for Merrill Lynch
Capital Markets Inc. said the credit markets were unnerved by
numbers showing employers added 325,000 new jobs last month, an
indication the manufacturing sector of the economy remains strong.
   A more vibrant economy signals higher inflation, which erodes the
value of fixed-income securities such as bonds and notes. Higher
inflation also suggests the Federal Reserve might move to tighten
credit by raising interest rates.
   ``Now it's fruitless to talk about the Fed raising interest
rates,'' said Maury Harris, an economist with PaineWebber Inc. ``The
economy is doing well now so the Fed doesn't need to ease anytime
soon either.''
   In the secondary market for Treasury bonds, prices of short-term
government issues lost between 11-32 point and 7-16 point,
intermediate maturities were down between 11-16 point and 1] point
and long-term issues fell 1| points, according to figures provided
by Telerate Inc., a financial information service.
   The movement of a point equals a change of $10 in the price of a
bond with a $1,000 face value.
   The Shearson Lehman Hutton Daily Treasury Bond Index, which
measures price movements on all outstanding Treasury issues with
maturities of a year or longer, fell 9.48 to 1,148.78.
   Corporate bonds also were lower. Moody's Investment Grade
Corporate Bond Index, which measures price movements on 80 corporate
bonds with maturities of five years or longer, dropped 2.08 to
295.96.
   Yields on three-month Treasury bills, meanwhile, rose to 7.71
percent as the discount gained 11 basis points to 7.47 percent.
Yields on six-month bills increased to 8.05 percent as the discount
rose 18 basis points to 7.64 percent. Yields on one-year bills
soared to 8.23 percent with the discount up 19 basis points to 7.66
percent.
   A basis point is one-hundredth of a percentage point. The yield
is the annualized return on an investment in a Treasury bill. The
discount is the percentage that bills are selling below the face
value, which is paid at maturity.
   The federal funds rate, the interest on overnight loans between
banks, was quoted at 8 3-16, down from 8 5-16 percent late Thursday.
</TEXT>
