<DOCNO> AP881104-0316 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-11-04-88 2135EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r f AM-Miami-News-Hearld     11-04 0325</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Miami-News-Hearld,0337</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Proposal to Extend Joint Operating Agreement</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PETE YOST</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A joint operating agreement between The Miami
News and The Miami Herald would be extended from 1996 until Dec. 31,
2021 under an amendment to the agreement released Friday by the
Justice Department.
   Under the amendment filed Thursday with the government, Cox
Enterprises Inc., which owns The News, would continue to share in
the operating income of The Herald until the year 2021.
   The sharing of net annual operating income would continue if The
News is sold or stops publication, Cox chairman James Kennedy said
in a letter to the Justice Department outlining the amendment.
   The amendment filed with the Justice Department also would
require Cox to absorb all losses of The News beginning in 1990; and
reduce Cox's share of the Herald's income beginning in 1989.
   After the first $7.5 million in net annual operating income,
which goes to The Herald, Cox in 1989 would receive 14 percent of
the income; 13 percent in 1990; 12 percent in 1991; 11 percent in
1992; and 10 percent from 1993 to 2021.
   Kennedy's letter said The News has sustained losses of more than
$90 million since the JOA was instituted in 1966 with The Herald,
owned by Knight-Ridder Inc.
   It was announced Oct. 14 that The News would close Dec. 31 if no
buyer is found. Company officials cited declining circulation _
which now stands at less than 48,000 _ and continuing financial
losses at the 92-year-old daily.
   In announcing the decision to sell or close The News, Cox
officials had said a continued JOA would not be a part of the deal.
   Cox Enterprises has fielded more than 30 inquiries from
prospective buyers, and meetings with several of them are scheduled
within the next few days for fact-gathering by both sides.
   The News' production, advertising, circulation and promotion
departments are owned by The Miami Herald Publishing Co.
</TEXT>
