<DOCNO> AP881104-0317 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-11-04-88 1935EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u f AM-Pillsbury     11-04 0640</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Pillsbury,0663</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Grand Met: Pillsbury Using ``Just Say No'' Defense</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MINNEAPOLIS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Pillsbury Co. appears to be using a ``just say
no'' defense against the $5.23 billion takeover bid from Grand
Metropolitan PLC, a lawyer for the British distilling and gaming
conglomerate said Friday.
   ``Pillsbury keeps saying `We need more time,''' Stuart Gold told
a hearing in Delaware Chancery Court in Wilmington, Del. ``That
doesn't cut.''
   Gold was appearing before Justice William Duffy, who was asked to
block Pillsbury from using a corporate poison pill to defend against
Grand Met's unsolicited $60-a-share, all-cash tender offer. Duffy
took the case under advisement and did not indicate when he would
issue a ruling.
   Grand Met has said it intends to start buying Pillsbury stock on
Tuesday.
   Gold urged Duffy to remove the poison pill defense so that
shareholders can decide for themselves if the offer is adequate. He
said Pillsbury's board of directors has not been able to come up
with an alternative after meeting four times since the offer was
made.
   He said Pillsbury has exceeded by 10 days the 20-day deadline
under the Williams Act for a target company to respond to a tender
offer.
   Pillsbury's board of directors rejected the offer as
``inadequate'' Oct. 17, but has not offered an alternative to
shareholders and has not negotiated the offer with Grand Met.
   Steven Rothschild, a Pillsbury lawyer, said the 20-day deadline
under the Williams Act doesn't begin until an ``adequate'' tender
offer is on the table. He also said Pillsbury is not obligated to
negotiate with Grand Met because the food and restaurant company is
not for sale.
   He likened Grand Met's argument about the Williams Act to a
``terrorist time bomb threat.
   ``Come to the target with a hostile offer, drop a time bomb in
the target's pocket, and say, `you have 20 days,''' Rothschild said.
   Rothschild said Pillsbury does not intend to drop its poison pill
defense plan, also known as a shareholders' rights plan.
   He did not say what alternatives to the tender offer the
Pillsbury board is considering, but he said the board is carrying
out its fiduciary responsibility to get maximum value out of the
company's stock.
   The poison pill, which was adopted by Pillsbury in 1986 and
amended before Grand Met launched its takeover bid Oct. 4, would
result in a ``disastrous dilution'' of Pillsbury stock, Gold said.
   Under the poison pill defense, Pillsbury could issue new stock
once Grand Met acquired a certain percentage of the existing stock.
The new stock could be purchased by shareholders for less than Grand
Met could buy it for, making the takeover more expensive.
   Rothschild said Pillsbury is protecting its shareholders by
keeping the poison pill in place. He said outside consultants have
told Pillsbury's board that the $60 price is not fair.
   Gold challenged the statement, asking Rothschild why Pillsbury's
stock price hasn't escalated much higher than $60 a share on the New
York Stock Exchange if it has greater value. The stock traded in the
range of $37 a share before the tender offer was announced. On
Friday, Pillsbury closed at $60.37{ a share, down 50 cents.
   Stephen Oestreich, a lawyer representing dissident shareholders
at Friday's hearing, said, ``shareholders ought to be in the board
room'' if the directors don't think Grand Met's offer is worth
negotiating.
   Oestreich urged Pillsbury to ``take off the boxing gloves'' and
talk to Grand Met about the offer, which Grand Met has said is
negotiable.
   Rothschild said that silence itself is a negotiating tool.
   Grand Met's Gold also asked the judge to enjoin Pillsbury from
challenging the takeover bid on the basis of state tied-house laws.
The laws prevent liquor distillers from selling alcohol at retail
outlets.
   Grand Met has said it would sell Pillsbury's full-service
restaurants, which sell alcohol, if the takeover bid is successful.

</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP881104-0318 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-11-04-88 2353EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>d f PM-OilPrices     11-04 0217</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Oil Prices,0230</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Energy Futures Mixed</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: for Saturday PMs</NOTE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Technical buying continued to dominate the energy
futures market, where prices of petroleum products turned mixed in
quiet trading.
   ``That's been the trend we've seen recently,'' Peter Beutel, an
energy analyst with Elders Futures Inc., said Friday. ``Things have
been quiet in advance of the OPEC meeting.''
   Members of the Organization of Petroleum Exporting Countries plan
to meet in about two weeks to discuss curbing production to help
prop up sagging worldwide oil prices.
   On the New York Mercantile Exchange, prices of unleaded gasoline
and crude oil headed higher Friday while wholesale home heating oil
continued to decline.
   The December contract for unleaded gasoline increased 1.14 cents
to 46.34 cents a gallon, after rising 1.41 cents on Thursday. Other
contract months were higher.
   Beutel said the increase was fundamental. ``To makea long story
short ... there's increased demand and reduced supply,'' he said.
   Among other refined petroleum products traded on the exchange
Friday, the December contract for wholesale home heating oil, which
rose 0.97 cent a gallon on Thursday, closed down 0.24 cent to 44.08
cents.
   The December contract for West Texas Intermediate, the benchmark
U.S. crude, closed at $14.04 a barrel, up 14 cents. The contract
rose 15 cents on Thursday.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
