<1ST_LINE>d f PM-Maxwell     11-04 0600</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Maxwell,0623</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Maxwell Plans to Concentrate on Publishing After Macmillan Buy</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: For Saturday PMs</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By SKIP WOLLENBERG</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   British publisher Robert Maxwell, taking charge
after his hard-fought victory in the battle for Macmillan Inc., says
he plans to encourage the growth of the publishing and information
services giant.
   But at the same time, Maxwell said his Maxwell Communication
Corp. planned to sell its British commercial printing operations and
possibly sell other assets to help reduce the debt incurred in the
buyout.
   The announcement Friday came just one day after Macmillan gave up
its six-month fight for independence and accepted Maxwell's takeover
bid.
   Maxwell Communication said the offer valued Macmillan at $2.6
billion and that 97.5 percent of Macmillan's shares had been
tendered by the deadline set in its $90.25 a share offer.
   Maxwell lost little time Friday in taking charge at Macmillan,
where he was elected chairman of the board, replacing Edward P.
Evans, who resigned.
   Evans had been part of a group led by the buyout firm Kohlberg
Kravis Roberts & Co. which lost out to Maxwell in the bidding for
Macmillan.
   Maxwell told a news conference at Macmillan headquarters that he
met with Macmillan's senior managers to assure them he planned to
make the company grow rather than break it up, and sent letters
making the same point to all of the company's employees.
   He lamented what he said was a change in style in American
management that has placed more emphasis on breakup values of
companies and less on loyalty to the company and its employees.
   Maxwell is chairman of Maxwell Communication, a London-based
printing and publishing concern that he has often said he wants to
make one of the world's 10 largest communications companies.
   The company will focus more on publishing and less on printing
following the Macmillan deal, he said.
   Maxwell said he plans to sell BPCC, Britain's largest commercial
printing business, perhaps to its management. He indicated it could
attract a bid of about $600 million.
   In addition, Maxwell said he is considering selling its British
newspaper printing business, which he said had a book value of $500
million.
   Maxwell is to retain his privately held Mirror Group Newspapers,
which owns the national Daily Mirror.
   At the New York news conference, Maxwell asserted that he has no
intention of selling any of Macmillan's publishing assets.
   ``I am a publisher, not a bookkeeper,'' he said, and added that
he hoped to improve the company's system for distributing books,
compete more aggressively for best-selling works and strive for
international publishing prominence.
   Maxwell said his company is still looking for possible publishing
acquisitions, but he declined to say whether they would approach the
size of the Macmillan purchase.
   Maxwell also recently announced plans to buy Dun and Bradstreet
Corp.'s Official Airline Guides for $750 million.
   BPCC prints books, consumer journals, magazines, documents,
packaging and labels. It had an operating profit of $62 million on
sales of about $534 million in 1987, Maxwell Communication said.
   In addition to the newspaper printing business, Maxwell
Communication said it was considering disposing of three recently
acquired printing plants in Europe and the company's property
portfolio.
   The company also said it intended to sell off divisions of
Macmillan that prove ``peripheral to our core strategy.''
   Macmillan's interests include the Katherine Gibbs secretarial and
Berlitz language schools and its Gumps retailing operations.
   Maxwell said while it was possible that these operations would be
sold, he said no decision on that issue has yet been made and each
company will be evalauted on its own merits.
</TEXT>
